description_code: Bracket shaped end part of the innermost bone of big toe

description_en: Seizures with increase in rate of ongoing movements or inappropriately rapid performance of a movement involving predominantly proximal limb or axial muscles producing irregular sequential ballistic movements, such as pedaling, pelvic thrashing, rocking movements.
Seizures with a decrease in amplitude and/or rate or arrest of ongoing motor activity.

Febrile seizures with focal semiology, duration of more than 15 minutes, or occurring in a cluster of 2 or more convulsions within 24 hours.,Note that semiology refers to the clinical symptoms of an epileptic seizure.
Febrile seizures with generalized tonic-clonic semiology, duration less than 15 minutes, and without recurrence within the next 24 hours.
Seizures with sudden loss or diminution of muscle tone with a preceding myoclonic or tonic event lasting one to two seconds or more, involving head, trunk, jaw or limb musculature.
EEG dominated by diffuse beta-waves (>13 Hz).,Beta-EEG is a rare finding but not generally pathologic.
EEG dominated by diffuse alpha-waves (8-13Hz).,Alpha-EEG is a rare finding but not generally pathologic.
EEG background activity at 4-5/second.,EEG background activity at 4-5/second is rare and unusual but not generally pathologic.
An EEG with constitutional variants contains waves that are rare or unusual but not generally pathologic.
Tonic seizures with a sustained, forced conjugate ocular, cephalic and/or truncal rotation or lateral deviation from the midline.
Auras with sensation of tingling, numbness, electric shock sensations, pain, sense of movement, or desire to move.

Auras with affective, mnemonic or composite perceptual phenomena including illusory or composite hallucinatory events.,Events may appear alone or in combination. Included are feelings of depersonalisation. These phenomena have subjective qualities similar to those experienced in life but are recognised by the subject as occurring outside of actual context.
Auras with sensation of odor, usually disagreeable.
Auras with taste sensations including acidic, bitter, salty , sweet or metallic tastes.
Seizures with regularly repetitive myoclonus, involving the same muscle groups, at a frequency of about 2-3 c/sec.
Focal seizure with eyelid myoclonia, not eyelid myoclonias in the context of absence seizures.
Seizures with sustained increase in muscle contraction in parts of the body lasting a few seconds to minutes.

Auras with sensation of flashing or flickering lights, spots, simple patterns, scotomata, or amaurosis.,Note that there is a distinction between Visual aura and Simple partial occipital seizures. See HPO term HP:0025121 for comments.
A sensation consistent with involvement of the autonomic nervous system, including cardiovascular, gastrointestinal, sudomotor, vasomotor and thermoregulatory functions.
Typical absence seizures starting before the age of 4 years.
Underdevelopment of the vestibular nerve.
description_code: Hypoplasia of the eighth cranial nerve,Thin vestibular nerve,Hypoplasia of cranial nerve VIII

description_en: Atypical absence lasting for more than 30 minutes.,Obtundation status is often seen in patients with Lennox-Gastaut-Syndrome.
Absence of the vestibular nerve,May be seen in CHARGE syndrome.
description_code: Absent the eighth cranial nerve,Absent vestribular nerve,Aplasia of the eighth cranial nerve,Absent cranial nerve viii,Aplasia of cranial nerve VIII

description_en: Rhythmic myoclonic jerks of the shoulders and arms with tonic abduction that results in progressive lifting of the arms during the seizure. The myoclonic jerks are typically bilateral but may be unilateral or asymmetric. Perioral myoclonias and rhythmic jerks of the head and legs may occur. Seizures last 10-60 seconds and typically occur daily. Level of awareness varies from complete loss of awareness to retained awareness.

value_en: Morphological abnormality of the nerves of the inner ear
Morphological abnormality of the inner ear
description_en: A structural anomaly of the internal part of the ear.,The inner ear contains the cochlea and the semicircular canals.

A type of focal sensory seizure that is characterized by elementary auditory phenomena including buzzing, ringing, drumming or single tones.,More complex auditory hallucinations such as voices are considered a focal cognitive seizure. Focal sensory auditory seizures involve auditory cortex in the lateral superior temporal lobe.
A focal sensory seizure involves a sensation being experienced at seizure onset, without objective clinical signs of a seizure evident to the observer.
Atrophy of the tibialis muscle.

value_en: Focal autonomic seizures without altered responsiveness
description_en: An autonomic seizure without altered responsiveness.
description_code: Localized autonomic seizures without altered responsiveness,Partial autonomic seizures without altered responsiveness

description_en: Reduced muscle tone secondary to an abnormality of the central nervous system.

value_en: Focal autonomic seizures with altered responsiveness
description_en: An autonomic seizure with altered responsiveness.
description_code: Localized autonomic seizures with altered responsiveness,Partial autonomic seizures with altered responsiveness

value_en: Abnormality of the dorsal column of the spinal cord
description_en: An abnormality of the dorsal columns, i.e., of the dorsal portion of the gray substance of the spinal cord. The dorsal column consists of the fasciculus gracilis and fasciculus cuneatus and itself is part of the dorsal funiculus.,The dorsal column represents an ascending pathway mediating well-localized fine touch and conscious proprioception.

Focal seizures with an objectively documented and distinct alteration of autonomic nervous system function involving cardiovascular, pupillary, gastrointestinal, sudomotor, vasomotor and thermoregularity functions.
Focal seizures involving musculature in any form.,The motor event can consist of an increase (positive) or decrease (negative) in muscle contraction to produce a movement.
description_code: Partial motor seizures,Focal motor seizures,Localized motor seizures

description_en: Absence or underdevelopment of the cochlea, a spiral shaped cavity in the inner ear, owing to a developmental defect.

A type of cataract (opacification of the lens) that forms during the course of aging.,The lens is formed from ectodermal tissue and contains epithelial cells that give rise to lens fibres throughout life, so with increasing age the lens becomes more compact and thicker.
description_code: Clouding of the lens of the eye with age

description_en: Increased size of the semicircular canal.
A spherical hollow structure with a smooth muscle coat, lined by a mucous membrane, and attached to any part of the gastrointestinal tract, from the base of the tongue to the anus.
Underdevelopment of the semicircular canal.
description_code: Small semicircular canal,Hypoplasia of the semicircular canals

description_en: Absence of the semicircular canal.

value_en: Morphological abnormality of the semicircular canal
description_en: An abnormality of the morphology of the semicircular canal.

Absence seizures accompanied by brief, repetitive, often rhythmic, fast (4-6 Hz) myoclonic jerks of the eyelids with simultaneous upward deviation of the eyeballs and extension of the head. Seizures are typically very brief (less than 6s in duration) and multiple seizures occur on a daily basis. Mostly awareness is retained.

A typical absence seizure is a generalized seizure with abrupt onset and offset of altered awareness which can vary in severity (see specific syndromes). Memory for events during the seizures is usually impaired although there may be some retained awareness particularly for adolescents. Clonic movements of eyelids, head, eyebrows, chin, perioral or other facial parts may occur, most typically at 3Hz. Myoclonus of limbs can rarely occur. Oral and manual automatisms are common and there may be perseveration of behaviors occurring prior to seizure onset.,Typical absences have 2 essential components: (1) clinically the impairment of consciousness (absence), and (2) EEG generalized 3 Hz to 4 Hz (less than 2.5 Hz) spike and slow wave discharges.

value_en: Functional abnormality of the inner ear
description_en: An abnormality of the function of the inner ear.,The inner ear comprises the cochlea, three semicircular canals and the vestibule (labyrinth), and is directly responsible for hearing. Additionally, the vestibule and semicircular canals function to maintain balance or equilibrium.
description_code: Functional abnormality of the inner ear

description_en: Increased size of the cochlear duct, i.e., of a duct that communicates between the perilymphatic space and the subarachnoid space, and transmits a vein from the cochlea to join the internal jugular.,The cochlear aqueduct surrounds the perilymphatic (periotic duct). Enlargement of the cochlear aqueduct may be seen in POU3F4 X-linked deafness with Gusher.
Increased size of the vestibular aqueduct.,Enlarged vestibular aqueduct is commonly seen in Pendred syndrome.
A type of age-related cataract consisting of granular opacities occurring mainly in the central posterior cortex just under the posterior capsule.
Reduction in diameter of the internal auditory canal.

A type of age-related cataract that primarily affects the cortex of the lens.,The cortex of the lens is made of the newest lens fibres. With ageing, discrete opacities can develop within the cortex of the lens that typically cause no visual symptoms unless they involve the visual axis or the entire cortex, in which case the lens becomes white and is said to be mature.
Aplasia of the internal auditory canal.

A type of age-related cataract that primarily affects the nucleus of the lens.,As the lens ages, new layers of fibres are added and the lens nucleus is compressed and becomes harder (nuclear sclerosis cataract), with associated yellowing of the lens. Nuclear sclerosis typically progresses slowly.

value_en: Abnormality of the internal auditory canal
description_en: An abnormality of the Internal acoustic meatus, i.e., of the canal in the petrous part of the temporal bone through which the cranial nerve VII and cranial nerve VIII traverse.
description_code: Abnormality of the internal acoustic meatus

description_en: Gastric duplication is a usually cystic malformation of gastrointestinal tract, usually attached to the greater curvature of the stomach and has no communication with the stomach.,Gastric duplication usually presents as gastric outlet obstruction. They are usually spherical in form, do not communicate with the stomach, and are generally localized at the greater curvature. In some cases they may exhibit adhesion to the pancreas and even communicate with aberrant pancreatic ducts. Gastric duplication is more frequent in females. It is generally either diagnosed in infancy because of symptoms of gastric outlet obstruction or is an incidental finding in adulthood.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.

value_en: EEG with focal sharp slow waves
description_en: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

value_en: EEG with series of focal spikes
description_en: Focal spikes occurring for several seconds.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec.
Focal epileptiform discharges of different shapes and frequencies.
Epileptiform discharges being identified at multiple locations in one hemisphere.

value_en: Uni- and bilateral multifocal epileptiform discharges
description_en: Epileptiform discharges identified at multiple locations temporarily in both hemispheres and temporarily in one hemisphere.

value_en: EEG with generalized sharp slow waves
description_en: EEG with generalized sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.

EEG discharges recorded on the entire scalp typically seen in persons with epilepsy.,Spikes (<70 ms) and sharp waves (70-200 ms) are sharp transient waves that have a strong association with epilepsy. No difference is noted in terms of clinical significance of spikes and sharp waves. Significant spikes usually are followed by a slow wave.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

EEG discharges recorded in particular areas of the A localized (focal) abnormality in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).,Note that a focal EEG abnormality is not synonymous with "focal epileptiform discharges" because a focal EEG abnormality is not necessarily epileptiform (e.g., it could be a focal slowing).

value_en: EEG with hyperventilation-induced generalized epileptiform discharges
description_en: Generalized epileptiform discharges induced by hyperventilation (overbreathing) in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

value_en: EEG with hyperventilation-induced focal epileptiform discharges
description_en: Focal epileptiform discharges induced by hyperventilation (overbreathing) in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

Epileptiform activity refers to distinctive EEG waves or complexes distinguished from background activity found in in a proportion of human subjects with epilepsy, but which can also be found in subjects without seizures. Interictal epileptiform activity refers to such activity that occurs in the absence of a clinical or subclinical seizure.,Epileptiform EEG discharges include small sharp spikes (SSSs), wicket spikes, 14- and 6-Hz positive spikes, phantom spike and waves, psychomotor variant, subclinical rhythmic EEG discharges of adults (SREDA), and midline theta rhythm.
EEG with an amplitude less than 30 microvolts without observable occipital alpha rhythm (8-13 Hz).,A low voltage EEG is a rare finding but not generally pathologic.
EEG dominated by diffuse beta waves (>13 Hz) with occipitally localized alpha waves (8-13 Hz).,A partial beta-EEG is a rare finding but not generally pathologic.
Epileptiform discharges being identified at multiple locations in both hemispheres.

value_en: Focal EEG discharges with secondary generalization
description_en: Focal EEG discharges that secondarily spread to both hemispheres and can then be recorded over the entire scalp.

value_en: Focal EEG discharges with propagation to ipsilateral hemisphere
description_en: Focal epileptiform discharges with spreading to the hemisphere on the same side of the brain.

value_en: Focal epileptiform discharges with limited propagation to contralateral hemisphere
description_en: Focal epileptiform discharges with spreading to contralateral hemisphere but without secondary generalization.

value_en: Abnormal circulating pyruvate family amino acid concentration
description_en: An abnormality of a pyruvate family amino acid metabolic process.
description_code: Abnormality of pyruvate family amino acid metabolism

description_en: Any deviation from the normal circulation of valine in the blood circulation.
An increased concentration of isoleucine in the blood.,Normal isoleucine blood levels are around 60-80 micromole per liter.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of isoleucine in the blood circulation.
An increased concentration of leucine in the blood.,Normal leucine blood levels are around 120-160 micromole per liter.
An increased concentration of valine in the blood.
An abnormality of a homocysteine metabolic process.
An abnormality of a cysteine metabolic process.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of tyrosine in the blood circulation.
An abnormality of an alanine metabolic process.
An abnormality of a histidine metabolic process.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of glutamine in the blood circulation.,Glutamine is a charge-neutral, polar amino acid.

value_en: Abnormal circulating glutamine family amino acid concentration
description_en: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a glutamine family amino acid in the blood circulation.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of methionine in the blood circulation.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of threonine in the blood circulation.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of arginine in the blood circulation.,Arginine is a charged, aliphatic amino acid.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of lysine in the blood circulation.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of proline or a proline metabolite in the blood circulation.
An increased concentration of histidine in the blood.,Blood histidine levels over 500 micromole per liter. Normal blood histidine levels are around 80-90 micromole per liter.
An abnormality of the distribution of hair growth.
description_code: Abnormal distribution of hair,Abnormal hair pattern

description_en: A kind of bronchopulmonary sequestration that is completely discrete from the normal lung and is surrounded by separate pleura.,Extralobar sequestration (ELS) may be asymptomatic. Infants with symptomatic lesions may present with respiratory distress, pneumonia, feeding difficulties, hemorrhage, or even congestive heart failure. The sequestered lobe may cause substantial arteriovenous shunting, leading to high-output cardiac failure.

A kind of bronchopulmonary sequestration that is incorporated into the normal surrounding lung.,Intralobar sequestration (ILS) may be diagnosed on antenatal ultrasound screening. ILS can be asymptomatic in later life or can lead to signs and symptoms related to inadequate tracheobronchial drainage caused by the lesion of adjacent atelectatic lung.

The presence of microscopic cystic masses of nonfunctioning pulmonary tissue that lack an obvious communication with the tracheobronchial tree.,Typically, the lung tissue in BPS receives all or most of its blood supply from an anomalous systemic artery, with the origin of this artery being variable.

Webbing or fusion of the toes, involving soft parts and including fusion of individual bones of the toes. Bony fusions are referred to as "bony" Syndactyly if the fusion occurs in a tibial-fibular axis. Fusions of bones of the toes in a proximo-distal axis are referred to as "Symphalangism".

value_en: Congenital cystic adenomatoid malformation of the lung
description_en: Congenital cystic adenomatoid malformation (CCAM) can be diagnosed prenatally if ultrasound shows a cystic or solid lung tumor. A CCAM does not have systemic arterial blood supply (in contrast to bronchopulmonary sequenstration). It is a cystic area within the lung that originates from abnormal embryogenesis.,Congenital cystic adenomatoid malformation (CCAM) results in a multicystic mass that replaces the normal lung structure. CCAM is usually unilateral and confined to a single lobe of the lung.
description_code: Congenital cystic disease of the lung,CCAM,Cystic adenomatoid lung disease

description_en: Syndactyly with fusion of toes three to five.
A bilateral form of agenesis of the kidney.
Syndactyly with fusion of toes two to five.

A developmental defect resulting in an obstructing membrane in the posterior male urethra.,Congenital posterior urethral valve is a cause of bladder outlet obstruction in male newborns. It results from a failure of resorption of the caudal end of the Wolffian duct into the primitive cloaca at the site of the future verumontanum in the posterior urethra (Following normal resorption of the posterior urethral valve there remain the posterior urethral folds, also called plicae colliculi).
Syndactyly with fusion of toes two to four.
description_code: Webbed 2nd-4th toes,Syndactyly toes 2-4,Syndactyly of toes 2, 3 and 4

description_en: Fetal megacystis is an abnormally enlarged bladder identified at any gestational age.,Abnormal enlargement of the fetal bladder can be detected by prenatal ultrasound by fourteen weeks of gestation. In some cases, dilatation of the fetal bladder is transient and resolves without sequelae, and in other cases it is the earliest manifestation of bladder outlet obstruction.
Syndactyly with fusion of toes one to five (complete syndactyly of all toes of the foot).
The presence of a dilated urinary bladder.
Syndactyly with fusion of toes one to four.

Underdevelopment of the right-sided structures of the heart.,Hypoplastic right heart syndrome (HRHS) causes inadequate blood flow to the lungs postnatally and thus leads to cyanosis. HRHS involves pulmonary valve atresia, hypoplasia of the right ventricle, hypoplasia of the tricuspid valve, and a small, hypoplastic pulmonary artery. As the ductus arteriosus closes postnatally, infants with HRHS become critically ill.
description_code: Underdeveloped right heart,Hypoplastic right heart syndrome

description_en: Syndactyly with fusion of toes one and two.

A form of hydrocephalus in which the flow of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) within the cerebral ventricular system or in the outlets of the CSF to the arachnoid space is obstructed.,The most common form of noncommunicating hydrocephalus is obstructive and is caused by intraventricular or extraventricular mass-occupying lesions that disrupt the ventricular anatomy.
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers three to five.
description_code: Webbed third, fourth and fifth toes

description_en: A kind of ventriculomegaly occurring in the fetal period and usually diagnosed by prenatal ultrasound. Cerebral ventriculomegaly is defined by atrial measurements 10 mm or more. Mild ventriculomegaly (MVM) is defined as measurements between 10 and 15 mm. Measurements are obtained from an axial plane at the level of the thalamic nuclei just below the standard image to measure the BPD (pmid:16100637).,A ventricular atrial diameter of more than 10 mm at 20-24 weeks of gestation has been accepted as defining ventriculomegaly because it represents at least 3 standard deviations above the mean (which is roughly 5 mm at 20-24 weeks of gestation). If the diameter is above 15 mm, the ventriculomegaly is considered to be severe. Amongst the most common causes of ventriculomegaly are impaired absorption of CSF, developmental cerebral defects, and destroyed brain tissue.
An abnormality of the texture of the hair.
description_code: Abnormality of hair texture,Abnormality of hair consistency,Abnormality of hair curl pattern,Abnormality of hair volume

description_en: An abnormality of the third ventricle.,The third ventricle is the cerebral ventricle that is located in the midline between the left and right lateral ventricles.

An abnormality of the fourth ventricle.,The fourth ventricle is the cerebral ventricle that extends from the cerebral aqueduct to the obex, and is located within the pons and the upper part of the medulla oblongata.
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers one to three.

value_en: Abnormality of the fetal cardiovascular system
description_en: An abnormality of the fetal circulation system or fetal echocardiogram.
description_code: Abnormality of the fetal circulation system

description_en: Syndactyly with fusion of fingers four and five.

value_en: Abnormality of ductus venosus blood flow
description_en: A first-trimester prenatal ultrasound finding of abnormal blood flow in the ductus venosus.,The ductus venosus is a bypass between the umbilical vein and the inferior vena cava in the fetus. The blood flow through this bypass decreases immediately after birth. Functional closure, which is followed by anatomic closure, is virtually complete within a few weeks of birth. The typical abnormal finding in abnormal ductus venosus flow is a reversed a-wave.
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers one and two.
description_code: Webbed 1st-2nd finger,Webbed thumb and index finger

description_en: The presence of dilatation of the renal pelvis.

Mild pyelectasis is defined as a hypoechoic spherical or elliptical space within the renal pelvis that measures at least 5mm and not more than 10 mm. The measurement is taken on a transverse section through the fetal renal pelvis using the maximum anterior-to-posterior measurement.,The renal pelvis is the part of the kidney that collects urine. Fetal pyelectasis is a prenatal ultrasound finding that is diagnosed with enlargement of the renal pelvis from 4 to 10 millimeters. In many cases, fetal pyelectasis resolves spontaneously. Note that dilatation of the renal pelvis to more than 10 mm is referred to as severe pyelectasis or hydronephrosis. Measurements less than 5mm are normal, should not be designated as pyelectasis, and should not be reported (pmid:16100637).
description_code: Fetal renal pelvic dilatation,Mild fetal hydronephrosis

description_en: An increased level of gamma globulin (immunoglobulin) in the blood.,In humans, immunoglobulins comprise the five antibody isotypes IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG and IgM.
description_code: Increased gamma globulin,Elevated immunoglobulin levels,Increased immunoglobulin level,Increased serum gamma globulin,Raised immunoglobulin levels,Hyperglobulinemia,Hypergammaglobulinemia,Hypergammaglobulinaemia

description_en: An abnormality of the renal pelvis.

Echogenic bowel is defined as fetal bowel with homogenous areas of echogenicity that are equal to or greater than that of surrounding bone.,Echogenic fetal bowel may be observed in fetuses with normal outcomes, but may also be a marker for diseases such as cystic fibrosis, congenital infection, chromosomal anomalies, and intraamniotic bleeding. This finding can be observed on prenatal ultrasound. The echogenicity has been classified as either focal or multifocal. Grade 2 suggests that echogenicity is equal to bone whereas grade 3 suggests that it is greater.

A finding of a focus of increased echogenicity upon prenatal ultrasound examination of the fetus. The foci may be present in one or both ventricles. Echogenic intracardiac focus (EICF) is defined as a focus of echogenicity comparable to bone, in the region of the papillary muscle in either or both ventricles of the fetal heart.,An echogenic intracardiac focus (EIF) is generally believed to be a normal variant, observed in 5% of all fetuses during second trimester sonography, but the risk of aneuploidies such as Down syndrome is increased in fetuses with EIF.
Absence of the nasal bone.
description_code: Failure of development of the nasal bone,Lack of development of the nasal bone,Agenesis of the nasal bone,Missing nasal bone,Absence of the nasal bone

description_en: Syndactyly with fusion of the fingers two to four.
description_code: Syndactyly of second to fourth fingers,Webbed index through ring fingers

description_en: Syndactyly with fusion of fingers one to five (complete syndactyly of all fingers of the hand).
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers one to four.

value_en: Abnormality of umbilical vein blood flow
description_en: A first-trimester prenatal ultrasound finding of abnormal blood flow in the umbilical vein.,Umbilical vein blood flow (UVBF) is closely related to the mass of placental cotyledons and is considered an expression of the amount of oxygen and nutrients transferred from the mother to the fetus.
Absence or underdevelopment of the nasal bone.
An abnormality of the nasal skeleton.
description_code: Abnormality of the nasal skeleton,Anomaly of the nasal skeleton,Distortion of the nasal skeleton,Distortion of the bones of the nose,Malformation of the nasal skeleton,Deformity of the bones of the nose,Deformity of the nasal skeleton,Malformation of the bones of the nose

value_en: Abnormality of the lower urinary tract
description_en: An abnormality of the lower urinary tract.,The lower urinary tract is a subdivision of urinary system which consists of the urinary bladder and the urethra.

value_en: Abnormality of the upper urinary tract
description_en: An abnormality of the upper urinary tract.,The upper urinary tract is a subdivision of urinary system which consists of the kidney and the ureters.
description_code: Abnormality of the upper urinary tract

description_en: An increased concentration of xanthine in the urine.,Xanthinuria is generally caused by a defect in the xanthine oxidase, an enzyme that catalyzes the oxidation of hypoxanthine to xanthine and can further catalyze the oxidation of xanthine to uric acid. The formation of xanthine stones in the urinary tract is the main evidence of this abnormality.
An increased level of xanthine in the blood circulation.,Xanthine is a purine base that is a product of purine degradation.

An abnormality of a nucleobase metabolic process.,This term is used to refers to abnormality in chemical reactions and pathways involving a nucleobase, a nitrogenous base that is a constituent of a nucleic acid, e.g. the purines: adenine, guanine, hypoxanthine, xanthine and the pyrimidines: cytosine, uracil, thymine.
An abnormal concentration of sodium.
description_code: Abnormality of sodium homeostasis,Abnormal blood Na+ levels,Abnormal circulating Na concentration

value_en: Abnormal blood monovalent inorganic cation concentration
description_en: An abnormality of monovalent inorganic cation homeostasis.
description_code: Abnormality of monovalent inorganic cation homeostasis

description_en: An abnormality of the nasal bone, comprising the left nasal bone and the right nasal bone.
description_code: Abnormality of the nasal bone,Anomaly of the nasal bones,Deformity of the nasal bones,Malformation of the nasal bones

description_en: An abnormality of the external nose.
description_code: Anomaly of the external nose,Abnormality of the external nose,Deformity of the external nose,Malformation of the external nose

description_en: A kind of nuclear cataract characterized by fiberglasslike or needlelike crystals projecting in different directions, through or close to the axial region of the lens.,This phenotype is characterized by fiberglasslike or needlelike crystals projecting in different directions, through or close to the axial region of the lens. Some crystals may be 11 mm in length, and their biochemical composition is not known. This type of cataract is considered to be different from the corraliform cataract, which does not show the needlelike projections. This opacity does not appear to respect the sutures or the direction of the lens fibers (Francois 1963) and appears to originate from the fetal and postnatal nuclei, suggesting a congenital origin with some postnatal progression, if any.
A cataract that affects the posterior part of the cortex of the lens.
A type of cataract affecting the anterior pole of lens immediately adjacent to ('beneath') the lens capsule.
A form of cataract in which the lens substance has shrunk, leaving a collapsed, flattened capsule with little or no cortex or epithelium on the lens.
A 'coral-like' pattern of opacity in the lens of the eye. That is, a cataract with an irregular, stellate form.

Zonular cataracts are defined to be cataracts that affect specific regions of the lens.,Zonular cataracts include specific regions of the lens and include nuclear cataracts, which affect the fetal or embryonic lens nucleus and lamellar cataracts. These tend to affect lens fibers that are formed at the same time, resulting in a shell like opacity. Zonular cataracts can also be characterized as dense or pulverulent (dusty appearing), and can be accompanied by arcuate opacities extending into the lens cortex, called cortical riders.
An abnormality of cation homeostasis.
An abnormality of divalent inorganic cation homeostasis.
description_code: Abnormality of divalent inorganic cation homeostasis

description_en: Absence or abnormal closure of the midnasal cavity.

A disease where there is cellular death (necrosis) of bone components due to interruption of the blood supply.,The interruption of the blood supply may have many different causes such as rapid growth, heredity causes, trauma or overuse, anatomic conformation, dietary imbalances or secondary effects of other diseases.
description_code: Bone infarction,Ischemic bone necrosis,Osteonecrosis,Aseptic bone necrosis,Death of bone due to decreased blood supply,Osteochondronecrosis,Aseptic necrosis

description_en: Shortening of the extremities affecting primarily the distal parts of the limbs (hands and feet) in relation to the other segments of the limbs.
Abnormality of the midnasal cavity which includes the cavity between the nares and the choanae.
A congenital disorder of the aortic valve in which the orifice of the valve fails to develop.
Abnormality of the nasal cavity (the cavity includes and starts at the nares and reaches all the way through to the and includes the choanae, the posterior nasal apertures).
A congenital disorder of the pulmonary valve in which the orifice of the valve fails to develop.
An abnormality of the umbilical cord, which is the cord connecting the developing embryo or fetus to the placenta.

Cystic hygromas can range from increased nuchal translucency to thin-walled cystic masses that may become larger than the fetal head. The cysts may result from a lymphatic abnormality, possibly one caused by absent or inefficient connections between the lymphatic and venous systems. Depending on the site, the cut off may vary from site to site. Lowest would be 2.5 mm and highest 3.5 mm.

Facial nerve palsy is a dysfunction of cranial nerve VII (the facial nerve) that results in inability to control facial muscles on the affected side with weakness of the muscles of facial expression and eye closure. This can either be present in unilateral or bilateral form.,Several conditions can cause a facial paralysis, e.g. brain tumor, stroke, and Lyme disease. However, if no specific cause can be identified, the condition is known as Bell's palsy. Named after Scottish anatomist Charles Bell, who first described it. Bell's palsy is the most common acute mononeuropathy (disease involving only one nerve) and is the most common cause of acute facial nerve paralysis.

value_en: EEG with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges
description_en: Periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs)are periodic, lateralized, and epileptiform. PLEDs show a relatively constant interval between discharges (0.5 to 3 seconds).,The epileptiform morphology of the discharges is not invariable, as PLEDS are often closer to slow waves than to sharp waves in morphology. PLEDs are often are caused by acute destructive focal lesions. PLEDs are often a transitory phenomenon, disappearing in a matter of weeks, even if the causal lesion persists, and often transforming into a less specific but more persistent focal slow appearance.

A benign biphasic tumor of the breast with epithelial and stromal components.,A connective tissue tumor of the breast which is usually benign and painless. Fibromas of the breast are more common in young woman.

EEG abnormalities (epileptiform discharges) evoked by flashing lights or black and white striped patterns.,In some patients, seizures can be provoked by specific external factors (reflex epilepsy), including flickering lights and patterns. These patients commonly show epileptiform discharges in the EEG when stimulated with flashing lights, black and white striped patterns and television. These evoked EEG abnormalities are called photoparoxysmal responses.

The burst suppression pattern in electroencephalography refers to a characteristic periodic pattern of low voltage (<10 microvolts) suppressed background and a relatively shorter pattern of higher amplitude slow, sharp, and spiking complexes.,Burst suppression can occur in a generalized or lateralized distribution and is often a sign of severe encephalopathy. Generally, an interburst interval of 30 seconds or less is associated with a better prognosis than longer interburst intervals (>30 sec). Burst suppression is an electroencephalogram (EEG) pattern in which high voltage activity (burst) and flatline (suppression) periods alternate systematically but quasiperiodically (almost periodic but with variations in inter- and intra-burst duration) is a state of profound brain inactivation.

Complexes of spikes (<70 ms) and sharp waves (70-200 ms), which are sharp transient waves that have a strong association with epilepsy, in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

description_en: A tricuspid valve that has failed to open.,Imperforate valve is distinct from atretic valve. The hallmark of an imperforate valve is that it provides potential communication between an atrium and a ventricle. It exists as fused valve leaflets usually possessing their own hypoplastic tensor apparatus. The presence of an imperforate valve may have important surgical implications. Imperforate valve is in contrast to atretic valve with an absent atrioventricular connection. The cornerstone of the diagnosis of an imperformate valve is the identification of a thin mobile membrane between an atrium and a ventrile and the recognition of the tensor apparatus of the valve. In most cases the tensor apparatusis hypoplastic and it maynot be possible to delineate it by echocardiography.

Unilateral atrophy of facial tissues, including muscles, bones and skin.
description_code: Atrophy of one side of the face,Atrophy of half of face,Decrease in size of half of face,Facial hemiatrophy,Decrease in size of one side of the face,Shrinking of half of face,Shrinking of one side of the face

description_en: Congenital defect characterized by underdevelopment of the tricuspid valve.
Premature fusion of the metopic suture.
A congenital stenotic mitral valvular anomaly with a ring of tissue above the mitral valve.
description_code: Supravalvular mitral ring,Membranous supravalvular mitral stenosis

description_en: Abnormality of the mitral valve apparatus, whereby chordae attach to a single papillary muscle or hypoplastic papillary muscles.
Any anomaly of a cranial suture, that is one of the six membrane-covered openings in the incompletely ossified skull of the fetus or newborn infant.
description_code: Abnormality of the cranial sutures,Abnormality of the bregma sutures,Abnormality of the skull suture,Abnormality of cranial sutures,Abnormality of the calvarium sutures

description_en: An abnormality of the fontanelle.,The fontanelles are the regions in an infant's calvaria that are covered by a thick membrane that normally ossify in the first two years of life.
Asymmetry of the posterior part of the skull.,Anterior plagiocephaly may have synostotic or non-synostotic causes.
Cleft in the anterior mitral valve leaflet not associated with an atrioventricular canal defect.
Asymmetry of the anterior part of the skull.,Anterior plagiocephaly may have synostotic or non-synostotic causes.
description_code: Frontal plagiocephaly,Anterior flat head syndrome,Deformational frontal plagiocephaly,Positional anterior plagiocephaly,Positional frontal plagiocephaly,Deformational anterior plagiocephaly,Unicoronal craniosynostosis,Coronal synostosis

description_en: The left atrio-ventricular connection consists of two anatomically distinct orifices separated by accessory fibrous tissue.,In about 50% of Double orifice mitral valve (DOMV) cases, valvular function is normal, others present with stenosis or regurgitation. In most cases, a larger orifice is accompanied by a small eccentric accessory orifice, and some show duplicated mitral valves. Embryologically, the lesion results from abnormal leaflet fusion and persistence of the left part of the common atrio-ventricular canal.
Craniosynostosis of all calvarial sutures.

An interatrial communication caused by a deficiency of the common wall between the superior vena cava (SVC) and the right-sided pulmonary veins. SVASD is commonly associated with anomalous pulmonary venous connection (APVC) of some or all of the pulmonary veins, which produces additional left-to-right shunting.

Craniosynostosis involving at least 2 cranial sutures, where the exact pattern of sutures fused has not been precisely specified.,If possible, it is preferable to annotate the precise pattern of involvement of the cranial sutures involved in craniosynostosis. This term may be chosen if more information is not available.

A congenital anomaly with partitioning of the right atrium to form a triatrial heart caused by persistence of the right valve of the sinus venosus. Typically, the right atrial partition is due to exaggerated fetal eustachian and thebesian valves, which together form an incomplete septum across the lower part of the atrium. This septum may range from a reticulum to a substantial sheet of tissue.,Cor triatriatum dexter is a Latin phrase meaning that the heart (cor) has three atria (triatriatum) whereby the 'third' atrium is on the right (dexter) side.
Incomplete fusion of the chin, resulting from a developmental defect and manifesting as a midline cleft or fissure of the chin.
description_code: Midline defect of chin,Cleft of chin

description_en: Complete absence of the interatrial septum with common atrioventricular valve and two atrioventricular connections.
Premature synostosis of only the right lambdoid suture.
Premature synostosis of only the left lambdoid suture.

An abnormality of the circulatory connection between the ventricles and the pulmonary artery and aorta.,The cardiac malformations with abnormal ventriculo-arterial connections in situs solitus and atrio-ventricular concordance include the tetralogy of Fallot as well as different forms of double-outlet right ventricle and transposition of the great arteries.
Premature synostosis of only one lambdoid suture.
description_code: Unilateral lambdoid craniosynostosis,Unilateral lambdoid suture synostosis

description_en: Anomalous insertion of the chordae tendinae or papillary muscles into the contralateral ventricle in the presence of a ventricular septum defect.,Straddling and overriding atrioventricular valves usually occur in combination.

An atrioventricular valve that empties into both ventricles. The valve overrides the interventricular septum above a ventricular septum defect.,Straddling and overriding atrioventricular valves usually occur in combination.
A congenital defect with failure to open of the mitral valve orifice.
Premature synostosis of both lambdoid sutures.
description_code: Bilateral lambdoid suture synostosis,Bilateral lambdoid craniosynostosis

description_en: Synostosis affecting the right and the left coronal suture.
description_code: Bilateral coronal craniosynostosis,Bilateral coronal suture craniosynostosis,Bilateral coronal suture synostosis

description_en: Unicoronal synostosis affecting only the right coronal suture.

value_en: Double inlet to single ventricle with two atrioventricular valves

description_en: Synostosis affecting only the left coronal suture.

value_en: Double inlet to single ventricle with common atrioventricular orifice

description_en: Synostosis affecting only one of the coronal sutures.
description_code: Unilateral coronal suture craniosynostosis,Unilateral coronal suture synostosis,Unilateral coronal craniosynostosis

value_en: Double inlet to single ventricle of indeterminate morphology
description_en: The condition in which both atria are joined to a single ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve. The morphology of this ventricle does not allow one to determine if it corresponds to the left or right ventricle.
An abnormality of size or shape of the long bones.
description_code: Abnormal shape of long bone,Abnormality of the tubular bones

description_en: The condition in which both atria are joined to the right ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve. Usually, the left ventricle is hypoplastic.
Decreased width of nail.

The condition in which both atria are joined to the left ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve. Usually there is a hypoplastic right ventricle, which may be on the opposite side of the heart as usual.

A nail plate that has a longitudinal separation with partially separated nails, each with a separate lateral radius of curvature.,The use of the word "fused" is not meant to imply that pathogenetically these nails were separate and merged. This is distinct from a split or cleaved nail, where the two parts of the nails share the same radius of curvature. The involved digits should be specified. It may be associated with underlying syndactylous digits, but these are coded separately.
The condition in which both atria are joined to a single ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve.

Extension of the proximal transverse crease (five finger crease) to the ulnar edge of the palm.,The proximal transverse (five finger) crease starts on the radial side of the hand near the base of the index finger and extends toward the ulnar side of the palm, but does not reach the ulnar side. In this finding, the crease extends completely to the ulnar margin of the palm.
Connection of the right atrium to the left ventricle and of the left atrium to the right ventricle in a biventricular heart.

A crease that connects the proximal and distal transverse palmar creases.,The crease that connects the two transverse creases should itself be more in the transverse (antero-posterior) than longitudinal (proximo-distal) orientation.

With left or right cardiac isomerism in a biventricular, the atrioventricular connections are perforce ambiguous, in that one of the connections is concordant (e.g., right-sided morphologic right atrium connected to a morphologic right ventricle) and one of the connections is discordant (e.g., left-sided morphologic right atrium connected to a morphologic left ventricle).

value_en: Right sided atrium to left ventricle and absent left sided atrioventricular connection
Biventricular heart with straddling right sided atrioventricular valve and absent left sided atrioventricular connection

description_en: The gradual reduction in girth of the toe from proximal to distal.
Toes that are disproportionately narrow (reduced girth) for the hand/foot size or build of the individual.
Divergence of digits along the anteroposterior axis (in the plane of the sole).

value_en: Univentricular heart with absent left sided atrioventricular connection

description_en: A defect where there is no connection between the right atrium and right ventricle.
A defect where there is no connection between the left atrium and left ventricle.
A nuclear cataract with a triangular form.
Increased thumb width without increased dorso-ventral dimension.,Note that this term should not be used for thumbs that meet the definition for Macrodactyly.
description_code: Broad thumb,Wide/broad thumb phalanges,Broad phalanges of the thumb,Wide/broad thumb,Broad thumbs

description_en: An abnormality of the circulatory connection between atria and ventricles.
Mirror image duplication of digits affecting the hands only.
A type of nuclear cataract involving congenital dust-like (pulverulent) opacity of the embryonal and fetal nucleus.
description_code: Pulverulent nuclear cataract,cataracta pulverulenta centralis,Central pulverulent cataract,Coppock-like cataract

description_en: The contour of the foot in lateral profile has a convex shape.,This term was established as the convex contour may occur without the prominent heel, which together comprise the bundled term Rocker-bottom foot.

value_en: Abnormal connection of the cardiac segments
description_en: A deviance in the normal connections between two cardiac segements.
description_code: Discordant connection of the cardiac segments

description_en: A type of anterior polar cataract which projects as a conical opacity into the anterior chamber.
A type of Congenital cataract in which the opacities occupy the subcapsular cortex at the anterior or posterior pole of the lens.
The total absence of the foot, with no bony elements distal to the tibia or fibula.

value_en: Superior-inferior ventricles without criss-cross atrioventricular valves

description_en: A type of congenital cataract in which the opacity follows the anterior or posterior Y suture.,During lens terminal differentiation, the originally cuboidal lens vesicle cells elongate into long fiber-like cells, or fibers. Y-shaped sutures form because of how the lens epithelial cells proliferate during formation. The Y sutures demarcate the boundaries between the lens cortex, which is peripheral to the Y sutures, and the lens nucleus, which is within and includes the Y sutures. The anterior Y suture is oriented upright, and the posterior Y suture is inverted.

Increased width of the distal segment of a finger.,This term should be reserved for use when the distal digit is significantly broader than the middle part. It should not be used if the digit has Clubbing or Macrodactyly or if the entire finger is broad.

value_en: Criss-cross atrioventricular valves with superior-inferior ventricles
description_en: Criss-cross atrioventricular valves with a rare cardiac malformation characterized by the two ventricles lying one above the other instead of side by side.
A Lamellar cataract with a pulverulent (punctate, "dust-like" opacities) appearance.,Opacities located in the perinuclear (lamellar) zones of the lens.
Crossing of the inflow streams of the two ventricles, due to an apparent twisting of the heart about its long axis.

A kind of congenital cataract that is characterized by a hollow sphere of punctate opacities involving the fetal nucleus and that usually occurs bilaterally.,The word "pulverulent " means dust-like and refers to the dustlike appearance of the punctate opacities in this type of cataract. The word pulverulent refers to the very small size of the punctate opacities (like flecks of dust) rather than to a dust-like color.

value_en: Congenitally corrected transposition of the great arteries
description_en: The essence of the lesion is the combination of discordant atrioventricular and ventriculo-arterial connections. Thus, the morphologically right atrium is connected to a morphologically left ventricle across the mitral valve, with the left ventricle then connected to the pulmonary trunk. The morphologically left atrium is connected to the morphologically right ventricle across the tricuspid valve, with the morphologically right ventricle connected to the aorta.
Syndactyly with fusion of fingers two to five.
description_code: Webbed 2nd-5th fingers,Webbed index, middle and little finger,Webbed index, middle and pinkie finger,Webbed index, middle and pinky finger

description_en: Mirror image duplication of digits affecting the feet.
Common atrium without defining morphologic features.
Mirror image atrial arrangement, with morphologic right atrium on the left hand side and morphologic left atrium on the right hand side.

In left atrial isomerism there is a bilateral small finger-shaped morphologically left atrial appendage joining the atrial chamber along a narrow front without an internal terminal crest.,Left and right hand side atria have left atrial morphology.

A hand or foot with more than five digits that has a recognizable A/P axis of symmetry. The axis can lie within a normally formed or partially duplicated digit resembling a middle finger, index finger, thumb, toe, or hallux. Alternatively, the axis can be in an interdigital space with a flanking pair of digits that resemble a middle finger, index finger, thumb, toe or hallux. The most lateral digits on each side of the hand typically resemble fifth fingers/toes.,Transplantation of the ZPA (zone of polarised activity) to the anterior margin of a limb bud in the chick results in mirror image duplication of limb elements (Tabin, 1991). Similarly, mirror image duplication in the forelimb of the mouse has been observed with ectopic expression of Hox b-8 (Charit6 et al, 1994). Mirror hand anomaly in humans has been shown to be due to either aberrant positioning of the ZPA or altered inductive interactions of the Shh gene resulting in impairment of the mechanism responsible for the organization and differentiation of the limb bud, rather than a primary duplication event. In other words, the primary event results in failure of the radial ray to develop. The ulnar area will then induce the differentiation of two groups of ulnar rays. Timing of this insult could play a critical role in severity of this phenotypic feature. Syndromal mirror hand is probably due to agene mutation of the Shh gene (Hersh et al, 1995). Finally, the multiple hand deformity may be explained by true duplication of the ZPA.
Right atrial isomerism is characterized by bilateral triangular, morphologically right atrial, appendages, both joining the atrial chamber along a broad front with internal terminal crest.
An abnormally reduced level of alkaline phosphatase, placental type in the blood.
Abnormality of the spatial relationship of the atria to other components of the heart.
Any abnormality of the morphology of the major calices or minor calices of the kidney.
Absence of the inner ear due to a developmental defect.,Aplasia of the inner ear is usually diagnosed on MR or CT imaging.
description_code: Aplasia of the labyrinth,Michel deformity,Absent inner ear,Labyrinthine aplasia

description_en: Increased susceptibility to viral skin infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of viral skin infections.
Increased susceptibility to cutaneous fungal infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of cutaneous fungal infections.

Pale reddish slightly elevated papules and plaques of 0.5-3 cm in diameter and not accompanied by pruritus.,Although the English-language names for uritcaria and non-pruritic urticaria are very similar these are treated as distinct lesions. Non-pruritic urticaria should not be considered to be a subclass of urticaria, because the latter is characterized by pruritus.

value_en: Dilated vestibule of the inner ear
description_en: Dilatation of the vestibule of the inner ear.
Absence of the sweat glands.
description_code: Lack of sweat glands,Absent sweat glands

value_en: Hypoplasia of the vestibule of the inner ear
description_en: Underdevelopment of the vestibule of the inner ear.
Absence or developmental hypoplasia of the sweat glands.
Complete absence of the vestibule of the inner ear.
Mild fever that does not exceed 38.5 degree centrigrade.
Absence of the cochlea, a spiral shaped cavity in the inner ear, owing to a developmental defect.

A furuncle (boil) is a skin infection involving an entire hair follicle and nearby skin tissue. Chronic furunculosis refers to recurrent episodes of furuncles, often caused by recurrent staphylococcus infection.,Note that a confluence of several furuncles results in a carbuncle.

value_en: Incomplete partition of the cochlea type I
description_en: Incomplete partition I is also known as cystic cochleovestibular malformation, where the cochlea has no bony modiolus, resulting in an empty cystic cochlea. This is accompanied by a dilated cystic vestibule with developmental arrest at the fifth week of gestation.
The presence of a rash (change of color and texture) of the perianal skin.

Incomplete formation of the cochlear partition. The scala vestibuli and scala tympani separated by the cochlear partition, except in the apical turn where the two scalae are in continuity via the helicotrema.
A bilateral form of fetal pyelectasis.

A condition characterized by necrosis of the mucosal and submucosal layers of the esophagus not related to ingestion of caustic or other injurious agents. Endoscopically, there is a dark lesion ('black esophagus') distributed in a circumferential manner in the distal one-third of the esophagus with or without exudates. There is involvement of the distal esophagus ending sharply at the gastroesophageal junction.
A congenital abnormality of the distribution of hair growth.
An abnormality of the distribution of hair growth that is acquired during the course of life.
A type of eczema that occurs in the lips and perioral area.,Perioral eczema mainly affects children.
Congenital deep dermal melanosis in the sacral area.

A significant descent of the kidney as the patient moves from the supine to the erect position.,Nephroptosis is diagnosed if the descent of the kidney is greater than 5 cm or two vertebral bodies on intravenous urogram. The kidney is capable of moving back to the normal position, which differentiates it from an ectopic kidney, which constantly remains in an abnormal position. Nephroptosis may be asymptomatic or may cause symptoms including pain and intermittent ureteric obstruction with hydronephrosis, and ischemia due to elongation, narrowing, or kinking of a renal artery.
Thickening of the epidermal layer of the skin.
An abnormality of the melanosomes, i.e., of the cellular organelles in which melanin pigments are synthesized and stored within melanocytes (the cells that produce pigment in the dermis).
Yellowish discoloration of the nails.
An abnormality of the morphology of the epidermis.
The presence of inflammation of the skin. That is, an abnormality of the skin resulting from the local accumulation of fluid, plasma proteins, and leukocytes.
description_code: Skin inflammation,Abnormal tendency to infections of the skin,Inflammatory abnormality of the skin,Dermatitis,Inflammatory skin disease

description_en: Reduced pigmentation of hair in patches.
Any abnormality of the physiological function of the skin.
Hypopigmented hair that appears white.
Any morphological abnormality of the skin.
Hair whose growth rate deviates from the norm.,Hair growth rate is normally about 1.25 centimeters per month.
description_code: Abnormality of speed of hair growth,Abnormality of hair growth rate,Abnormality of pace of hair growth

description_en: Nasal ridge curving posteriorly to an imaginary line that connects the nasal root and tip.,A saddle-nose deformity can be congenital or acquired (e.g., traumatic) and is associated with structural compromise of the nasoseptal cartilage leading to decreased dorsal nasal structural support. A depression of the dorsum of the nose with loss of nasal tip support and definition, shortened (vertical) nasal length, overrotation of the nasal tip, and retrusion of the nasal spine and caudal septum.
description_code: Concave dorsum of nose,Boxer's nose deformity,Boxer's nasal deformity,Saddle shaped nasal dorsum,Concave nasal dorsum,Saddle nose,Ski jump nose,Saddle nose deformity

description_en: An abnormal amount of hair.
An abnormality of the nasal dorsum, also known as the nasal ridge.,The nasal ridge is the midline prominence of the nose, extending from the nasal root to the tip.
description_code: Anomaly of the nasal ridge,Abnormality of the dorsum of nose,Abnormality of the nasal ridge,Malformation of the dorsum of nose,Deformity of the dorsum of the nose,Deformity of the nasal ridge,Abnormal morphology of dorsum of nose,Crooked nasal dorsum,Malformation of the nasal ridge,Crooked dorsum of nose,Crooked nasal ridge,Deformity of the nasal dorsum,Malformation of the nasal dorsum

value_en: Abnormality of tumor necrosis factor secretion
description_en: An abnormality in the production or cellular release of tumor necrosis factor.
description_code: Abnormality of cachectin secretion,Abnormality of cachexin secretion

description_en: An abnormality in the production or cellular release of interleukins (a class of cytokines).
Hair that lacks the lustre (shine or gleam) of normal hair.
A mild delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.

value_en: Left aortic arch with isolated subclavian artery
description_en: The subclavian artery arises from ductus arteriosus. While the ductus arteriosus is patent its blood supply comes from the ductus, hence from the pulmonary artery. After it closes, the blood supply is retrogradely from the vertebral artery via the circle of Willis.

value_en: Left aortic arch with cervical origin of the right subclavian artery

description_en: A conenital abnormality of the aortic arch in which the two embryonic aortc arches form a vascular ring that surrounds the trachea or esophagus and then join to form the descending aorta. Double aortic arch can cause symptoms because of compression of the esophagus (dysphagia, cyanosis while eating) or trachea (stridor).
An abnormality in the production or cellular release of interferons (a class of cytokines).
Reduced pigmentation of hair diffusely.
An abnormality in the production or cellular release of a chemokine (a class of cytokines).
An abnormality of the density of hair growth.
Mesocardia is an abnormal location of the heart in which the heart is in a midline position and the longitudinal axis of the heart lies in the mid-sagittal plane.
An impairment in the production by leukocytes of NFKB1-dependent cytokines such as tumor necrosis factor-alpha and interferon-alpha.
An abnormality of the skin that is restricted to a particular body region.

value_en: Right aortic arch with retroesophageal left subclavian artery
description_code: Right aortic arch with anomalous left subclavian artery,Right aortic arch with aberrant left subclavian artery

description_en: An abnormality in the production or cellular release of a cytokine (i.e., any of the non-antibody proteins made by inflammatory leukocytes and some non-leukocytic cells that affect the behavior of other cells).
A lesion of the skin that is located in a specific region rather than being generalized.

value_en: Right aortic arch with left descending aorta and left ductus arteriosus

description_en: Abnormality of the cytokine levels in the blood, i.e., an abnormality of any of the non-antibody proteins made by inflammatory leukocytes and some non-leukocytic cells that affect the behavior of other cells.
An abnormality of the skin that is not localized to any one particular region.
description_code: Generalized abnormality of skin,Generalised abnormality of skin

value_en: Left aortic arch with right descending aorta and right ductus arteriosus
description_en: The ring may be completed by the ductal ligament.

value_en: Abnormality of immune serum protein physiology
description_en: An abnormality of the concentration or function of circulating immune proteins.
Formation of excess fibrous connective tissue in the tunica intima (innermost layer) of arteries.

value_en: Left aortic arch with retroesophageal right subclavian artery
description_en: Aortic arch crosses the left mainstem bronchus. The first branch is the right carotid artery, the second branch is the left carotid artery, the third branch is the subclavian artery, the fourth branch is the right subclavian artery arising from the posteromedial aspect of the distal aortic arch and continuing posterior to the esophagus to the right hand side of the body.
An inflammation of the tonsils.
A severe delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.

value_en: Right aortic arch with retroesophageal diverticulum of Kommerell
description_en: Aortic arch crosses the right mainstem bronchus. The left carotid artery is the first branch, right carotid artery the second branch and right subclavian artery as the third branch.
A moderate delay in the acquisition of the ability to understand the speech of others.

value_en: Left aortic arch with retroesophageal diverticulum of Kommerell
description_en: A patent ductus arteriosus or ductal ligament completes the ring.
A chronic form of sinusitis.
A recurrent form of sinusitis.,Recurring inflammation of the paranasal sinuses.

Malfunction of the abducens nerve as manifested by impairment of the ability of the affected eye to be moved outward.,Affected individuals may experience diplopia as well as esotropia or convergent strabismus.
An decrease in the amount of intravascular fluid, particularly in the volume of the circulating blood.

value_en: Abnormality of the sixth cranial nerve
description_en: An abnormality of the abducens nerve.,The abducens nerve (also known as the sixth cranial nerve or cranioal nerve VI) controls the movement of the lateral rectus muscle of the eye, which moves the eyeball in the outward direction (towards the side of the head).
A congenital defect of heart development characterized by origin of both pulmonary artery and aorta from the morphological left ventricle.

value_en: Short chordae tendineae of the mitral valve
description_en: Abnormally short chordae tendineae of the mitral valve.,The chordae tendineae connect the papillary muscles to the tricuspid valve and the mitral valve in the heart.
An increase in the amount of intravascular fluid, particularly in the volume of the circulating blood.
An abnormality involving the movement of the eye outwards.

value_en: Common origin of the right brachiocephalic artery and left common carotid artery
description_en: The left common carotid artery has a common origin with the innominate artery.,Commonly the three great vessels (innominate artery, left common carotid artery, and the left subclavian artery) originate from the arch of the aorta. The second most common variant of aortic arch branching occurs when the left common carotid artery has a common origin with the innominate artery.
An abnormality in the amount of volume occupied by intravascular blood.
A mild delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.
The aortic arch extends into the soft tissues of the neck before turning down into to become the descending aorta.

value_en: Abnormal left ventricular outflow tract morphology
description_en: An abnormality of the outflow tract of the left ventricle.
description_code: Abnormality of the left ventricular outflow tract

description_en: A moderate delay in the acquisition of the ability to use language to communicate needs, wishes, or thoughts.

value_en: Abnormal branching pattern of the aortic arch
description_en: A deviance from the norm of the origin or course of the right brachiocephalic artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery or the proximal vertebral arteries.,The normal aortic arch crosses the left mainstem bronchus and descends in the left paravertebral gutter. The coronary arteries arise from the aortic sinuses. The first branch of the aorta is normally the right brachiocephalic artery, then the left common carotid artery, then the left subclavian artery. Abnormal branching refers to any deviance from the norm of the origin or course of these branches or the proximal vertebral arteries. An anomaly of the aortic arch that results in complete encirclement of the trachea and oesophagus by vascular structures is a vascular ring.
An abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the ileum.
A severe delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
description_code: Global developmental delay, severe,Severe psychomotor retardation

description_en: Congenital malformation of the ventral wall with partial or total evisceration of the heart outside the thoracic cavity and displacement partially into the abdominal cavity.,In many cases, thoracicoabdominal ectopia cordis is characterized by partial absence or cleft of the sternum, deficiency of the anterior diaphragm, deficiency of the diaphragmatic pericardium, midline abdominal wall defect, and congenital intracardiac abnormalities. These five characteristics comprise the pentalogy of Cantrell.
A moderate delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
description_code: Global developmental delay, moderate,Psychomotor retardation, moderate

description_en: Congenital malformation of the thoracic wall with partial or total displacement of the heart outside the thoracic cavity. This feature is associated with sternal cleft or absence of the sternum.

An abnormal closure, or atresia of the tubular structure of the intestine.,Intestinal atresia is a broad term used to describe a complete blockage or obstruction anywhere in the intestine, in contrast to stenosis, which refers to a partial obstruction that results in a narrowing of the intestinal lumen.
A mild delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
description_code: Global developmental delay, mild,Psychomotor retardation, mild

description_en: A type of ectopia cordis with the heart partially in the cervical region with a defect of the superior portion of the sternum.
Increased width of the upper lip.
description_code: Increased height of upper lip,Increased vertical length of upper lip,Long upper lip,Elongation of upper lip

description_en: A type of ectopia cordis with the heart partially in the cervical region and without a defect of the sternum.,This type of ectopia cordis presumably represents a retention of the heart in its embryonic position in the neck.

value_en: Incomplete cleft of the upper lip
description_en: A subtle unilateral cleft of the upper lip, which may appear as a small indentation.
description_code: Forme fruste unilateral cleft lip,Partial cleft of the upper lip,Incomplete cleft of the upper lip,Incomplete cheiloschisis,Notched cleft of the upper lip

An abnormality of the vermilion border, the sharp demarcation between the lip (red colored) and the adjacent normal skin.
description_code: Deformity of the upper lip vermillion,Anomaly of the upper lip vermillion,Abnormality of the red part of the upper lip,Malformation of the upper lip vermillion

In complete AVSD, the common AV valve can be situated either equally over the right and left ventricles (balanced) or unequally over the ventricles (unbalanced).

Agenesis of maxillary premolar.,Note that premolar teeth occur only in the permanent dentition.

Agenesis of premolar tooth.,Note that premolar teeth occur only in the permanent dentition.

description_en: A soft tissue prominence of the ventral aspects of the fingertips or toe tips.,The prominence of the finger or toe pads varies throughout life, being greater in neonates and dependent on the state of hydration. This term should not be used if the digit has clubbing. Note that the synonym "fetal fingertip pads" should not be interpreted to mean that the prominent pad necessarily was present in this individual since fetal life. We do not endorse the use of the term "Persistent fetal pads" as this term implies knowledge of the natural history of this finding, which may or may not be known.
Agenesis of secondary molar tooth.

Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the cervical vertebral column.
An abnormality of the metencephalon. The metencephalon is the part of the hindbrain that consists of the pons and the cerebellum.

An abnormality of the hindbrain, also known as the rhombencephalon.,The hindbrain consists of two main structures: The pons and the cerebellum.

description_code: Agenesis of deciduous maxillary central incisor,Failure of development of primary maxillary central incisor,Failure of development of deciduous maxillary central incisor,Missing deciduous maxillary central incisor,Absence of primary maxillary central incisor,Missing upper front baby tooth,Missing upper front milk tooth,Missing primary maxillary central incisor,Absence of upper front baby tooth,Absence of deciduous maxillary central incisor
