The presence of an altered number of of permanent teeth.
description_code: Abnormal number of adult teeth,Abnormal number of secondary dentition,Abnormal permanent tooth count,Abnormal complement of permanent teeth,Abnormal number of permanent teeth

description_en: A type of aganglionic megacolon in which the aganglionic segment comprises the entire colon.

An abnormal concentration of corticotropin in the blood.,Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), also known as corticotropin, is a polypeptide hormone produced and secreted by the pituitary gland comprising 39 amino acid residues coupled in a linear sequence. . It is a component of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis and stimulates increased production and release of corticosteroids and cortisol from the adrenal cortex.
A type of aganglionic megacolon in which the aganglionic segment extends proximal to the sigmoid.
An abnormality of the homeostasis (concentration) of iron cation.
Abnormally increased variability in the size of erythrocytes.
description_code: Unequal size of red blood cells

value_en: Abnormal blood transition element cation concentration
description_en: An abnormality of the homeostasis (concentration) of transition element cation.
description_code: Abnormality of transition element cation homeostasis

description_en: Decreased posterolateral protrusion of the tragus.
Increase posterolateral protrusion of the tragus.
description_code: Large tragus,Hypertrophic tragus,Enlarged tragus,Tragus, prominent,Hyperplastic tragus

description_en: An abnormality of the helix. The helix is the outer rim of the ear that extends from the insertion of the ear on the scalp (root) to the termination of the cartilage at the earlobe.
An abnormality of renal absorption.
A decreased rate of urine production.,A reduction in the overall amount of urine output.
An abnormality of the concentration of hydrogencarbonate in the urine.
An altered ability of the kidneys to void urine and/or specific substances.
A type of pulmonary sequestration that occurs within the visceral pleura of normal lung tissue, usually without communication with the tracheobronchial tree.
An abnormality of the cortex of the kidney.

value_en: Abnormality of the urinary system physiology

description_en: The presence of amyloid deposition in one or more tissues. Amyloidosis may be defined as the extracellular deposition of amyloid in one or more sites of the body.,The medical literautre on amyloidosis is confused with clinical and histochemical designations used when the amyloid disease processes were poorly understood. To be designated an amyloid fibril protein, the protein must occur in tissue deposits and exhibit affinity for Congo red and green birefringence when viewed by polarisation microscopy.

description_code: Skin vascular malformation,Vascular abnormalities restricted to skin

description_en: An impairment of a fructose metabolic process.

Increased susceptibility to mycobacterial avium complex infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of mycobacterial infection.,Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC) is a group of species including M. avium, M. avium paratuberculosis, and others. Disseminated MAC infections can be seen associated with HIV infection. Pulmonary disease and cervical adenitis are other sequellae of MAC infection.
An abnormality of the regulation of body fluids.

Increased susceptibility to mycobacterial infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of mycobacterial infection.,Mycobacteria represent a family of slowly growing bacteria, including M. tuberculosis, the agent of tuberculosis, M. leprae, the agent of leprosy, M. avium complex species, and others. Mycobacteria infection can be asymptomatic or not, and are typically difficult to treat with antibiotics.
The presence of hemorrhage within the body.
An abnormality of the metabolism of mucopolysaccharide.

Linear, circumferential indentation in the convexity of the outer surface of the helix.,The crimp is usually found in the middle third of the descending helix. The helix has the appearance of having been pinched or flattened along its posterior margin. The crimp may distort the free margin of the helix.
Small expansion of the helical fold at the junction of the superior and descending portions of the helix.
Small defect of the helical fold that lies at the junction of the superior and descending portions of the helix.
An abnormality of blood circulation.
An abnormality of the fallopian tube.,The Fallopian tubes (also known as oviducts, uterine tubes, and salpinges) are ducts that lead from the ovaries into the uterus.
Increased height of the tragal ridge with a shallow indentation at the apex, giving the appearance of a double peak.
Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the vagina.

Lack of convexity or prominence of the contour of the ridge between the bottom of the incisura and the confluence of the ascending helix and crus helix.,This appears to be unusual in an otherwise normal ear, and is most often seen in microtia with atretic auditory meatus, but those findings should be coded separately.
Abnormal functionality of the cardiovascular system.

Presence of some auricular structures, but none of these structures conform to recognized ear components.,This malformation is commonly associated with atresia of the external canal, but that anomaly should be coded separately. Complete absence of the ear should be coded as Anotia.
An abnormality of the gastrointestinal tract.
description_code: Abnormality of the GI tract,Abnormality of the gastrointestinal tract,Gastrointestinal disease,Digestive system disease

description_en: Presence of all the normal ear components and the median longitudinal length more than two standard deviations below the mean.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a prostaglandin in the blood circulation.

Discontinuity in the convexity of the inferior margin of the lobe.,The cleft is often more visible if the lobe is pulled forward or when seen from behind. Tears acquired from earrings should be distinguished.

value_en: Abnormal circulating unsaturated fatty acid concentration
description_en: A deviation from the normal concentration of an unsaturated fatty acid in the blood circulation.
Interruption between the ascending helix and the crus helix, allowing the ascending helix to be attached directly to the mastoid.

Positioning of the anterior surface of the ear lobe in a more coronal plane than the remainder of the ear.,The lobe should be viewed from the front. This feature is distinct from the situation where the entire ear is forward facing and prominent. The lobe normally lies more or less in the same plane as the remainder of the ear. This feature should be distinguished from Uplifted lobe.
An abnormality of chromosome condensation.
An abnormality of the cell cycle.

A sudden flexion, extension or mixed extension-flexion of predominantly proximal and truncal muscles which is usually more sustained than a myoclonic movement but not as sustained as a tonic seizure.,The maximum age of onset is between 3 and 12 months, the peak being at 6 months. However, spasms may start from birth, or appear long after the age of 12 months, including into adulthood. Infantile spasms represent a specific type of seizure seen in an epilepsy syndrome of infancy and childhood known as West Syndrome. West Syndrome is characterized by infantile spasms, developmental regression, and hypsarrhythmia (as demonstrated by electroencephalography).

A loss of myelin from the internode regions along myelinated nerve fibers of the peripheral nervous system.,This feature is generally diagnosed on the basis of a sural nerve biopsy. Demyelination is associated with slowed nerve conduction, increased refractoriness, and conduction block.
An abnormal anteroposterior extension of the maxillary teeth beyond the plane of the mandibular teeth upon jaw closure.
description_code: Abnormality of horizontal incisor relationship,Protrusion of upper teeth in front of lower teeth,Protrusion of the maxillary incisors,Upper teeth sticking out forward,Buck teeth

description_en: Maxillary teeth cover the mandibular teeth when biting to an increased degree.
description_code: Increased overlap of upper and lower incisors,Overbite,Deep overbite,Scissors bite,Deep bite

description_en: Increased size and molar morphology of premolar tooth.
description_code: Molar shape of premolar,Molarization of bicuspid,Molar shape of bicuspid,Enlarged premolar,Increased size of premolar

description_en: Mulberry molars are irregular teeth generally affecting the first molars and are characterized by a grossly deformed crown imitating, as the name implies, the surface of a mulberry.

The development of two teeth from a single tooth bud, leading to a larger fused tooth.,If the fused tooth is counted singly, then the total number of teeth is normal with gemination. Usually, there is a larger dental crown with a single root and single canal.
description_code: Splitting of crown of tooth,Gemination of tooth

description_en: The union of two separately developing tooth germs typically leading to one less tooth than normal in the affected dental arch.
Unilateral paresis (weakness) with spasticity of the affected muscles and increased tendon reflexes.

A type of apraxia that is characterized by difficulty or inability to execute speech movements because of problems with coordination and motor problems, leading to incorrect articulation. An increase of errors with increasing word and phrase length may occur.,Speech apraxia may co-occur with oral apraxia and limb apraxia.

value_en: Dentinogenesis imperfecta of primary and permanent teeth
description_en: Developmental dysplasia of dentin or both the primary dentition and the permanent dentition.
description_code: Dentinogenesis imperfecta of adult and baby teeth,Dentinogenesis imperfecta of both sets of teeth

description_en: A form of hypomineralization of enamel characterized by a chalky appearance of the enamel with orange, brown, or white color.,Radiographically there is normal thickness of enamel and the enamel is slightly more radiolucent than dentin.
description_code: Immature tooth enamel,Soft tooth enamel,Soft teeth

description_en: A form of hypomineralization of enamel characterized by reduced calcification.
description_code: Decreased enamel calcification,Poorly calcified tooth enamel

description_en: An abnormal conical morphology of either maxillary primary incisor tooth or maxillary permanent incisor tooth or both.
description_code: Cone shaped upper front tooth,Cone shaped maxillary incisor,Conoid maxillary incisor,Upper front shark tooth,Pointed upper front tooth,Pointed maxillary incisor,Peg shaped upper front tooth

description_en: An abnormal conical morphology of the primary incisor.
description_code: Conical deciduous incisor,Conoid primary incisor,Primary front shark tooth,Cone shaped front baby tooth,Pointed front baby tooth,Pointed primary incisor,Peg shaped front baby tooth,Peg shaped primary incisor

description_en: Increased size of the incisor tooth.
description_code: Increased size of incisor,Hypertrophy of incisor,Large incisor,Hyperplasia of incisor,Increased width of incisor

description_en: An abnormality of morphology of premolar tooth.
description_code: Abnormality of bicuspid morphology,Abnormality of shape of premolar,Abnormality of shape of bicuspid

description_en: A dental anomaly characterized by the presence of a two fused teeth.
An abnormality of the incisor characterized by invagination of the enamel, giving a radiographic appearance that suggests a tooth within a tooth.,Dens in dente is Latin for tooth inside of tooth.
Talon cusp is an accessory cusp located near the cingulum (the portion of the lingual or palatal aspect of the tooth that forms a convex protuberance at the cervical third of the anatomic crown).
description_code: Extra cusp on inside of front tooth,Dens evaginatus,Talon cusps

description_en: A green staining of teeth.,Green teeth are a rare finding in children with neonatal hyperbilirubinaemia due to blood group incompatibility, sepsis-induced cholestasis or biliary atresia. Rarely, green staining of the teeth may be seen with cholestasis and sepsis.
description_code: Green colored teeth,Green teeth,Green tooth shade

description_en: A localized form of developmental hypoplasia of the dental enamel.
description_code: Localized hypoplasia of tooth enamel,Localized dysplasia of tooth enamel

description_en: A developmental defect of tooth color.
description_code: Abnormality of tooth color,Abnormality of tooth shade,Abnormality of dental color,Abnormality of dental shade
Absence of tooth root,Missing tooth root,Rootless teeth,Teeth without roots,Aplasia of tooth root,Agenesis of tooth root,Tooth with dentin dysplasia type i

description_en: An abnormality of morphology of permanent molar.
description_code: Abnormality of shape of adult molar,Abnormality of shape of permanent molar

description_en: An abnormality of morphology of molar tooth.
A tooth that has not erupted because of local impediments (overcrowding or fibrous gum overgrowth).
An abnormality of canine tooth.
description_code: Abnormality of eye tooth,Abnormality of canine

description_en: An abnormality of molar tooth.
An abnormality of premolar tooth.
The presence of an altered number of the incisor teeth.
description_code: Abnormal number of front teeth,Abnormal number of incisors

description_en: An abnormality of morphology of the incisor tooth.
Misaligned incisor.
description_code: Abnormality of position of incisors,Malposition of incisors,Abnormality of alignment of incisors,Crooked front teeth,Misalignment of incisors,Crooked incisors

description_en: An abnormality of the structure or composition of the teeth.
description_code: Abnormality of tooth part,Abnormality of tooth structure

value_en: Dentinogenesis imperfecta limited to primary teeth
description_en: Developmental dysplasia of dentin affecting only the primary dentition.
description_code: Dentinogenesis imperfecta of baby teeth,Dentin dysplasia

description_en: The presence of a supernumerary, i.e., extra, tooth or teeth.,The most frequent supernumerary tooth is a mesiodens, which occurs between the two maxillary central incisors. Often it fails to erupt, but creates a large anterior diastema, and would not be detected on physical examination (requires X-ray evaluation). This designation excludes coexistence of primary and permanent dentition due to delayed loss of the former. Note that this term does not refer to the situation in which two rows of teeth are seen at the time of eruption of permanent dentition before exfoliation of primary teeth, which can be a normal finding.
description_code: Increased number of teeth,Supplemental dentition,Extra teeth,Supernumerary teeth,Supplemental teeth,Supernumerary tooth,Increased tooth count,Hyperdontia,Supernumary teeth,Supernumary dentition,More teeth than normal

description_en: The presence of an odontoma.,MPATH defines odontoma as a hamartomatous malformation of odontogenic tissue. It may vary from nondescript masses of dental tissue (complex odontoma) to multiple well-formed teeth (compound odontoma).

The presence of a supernumerary tooth in the midline between the maxillary central incisors.,A mesiodens is not a supernumerary incisor (i.e., it does not have the morphology of an incisor). Rather, it is a conoid, extra tooth located between the maxillary central incisors.
description_code: Extra tooth in the midline,Extra tooth,Median supernumary tooth,Midline supernumary tooth,Mesiodentes

description_en: An abnormal conical morphology of the incisor tooth.,Conical incisors are incisors that are round in cross-sectional views of the crown or that have a rounded appearance. Conical incisors may have a pointed shape that tapers to a point at the tip of the tooth. One speaks of conical incisor for a conical shaped tooth that is located in the region where incisors normally are.
description_code: Shark tooth incisor,Peg shaped incisors,Peg-shaped incisors,Cone shaped front tooth,Conoid incisor,Pointed front tooth,Pointed incisor,Peg shaped front tooth

description_en: An abnormality in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG) and being identified at multiple locations (foci).
An increased concentration of non ceruloplasmin bound copper in the blood.

Decreased concentration of ceruloplasmin in the blood.,Ceruloplasmin is the major copper-carrying protein in the serum. Decreased serum ceruloplasmin levels can indicate other defects in copper metabolism.
An abnormal concentration of copper.,An abnormality in the concentration of copper, which normally occurs as a cofactor for a number of proteins including amine oxidases and chaperone proteins.

A pattern of sensory loss with selective loss of touch sensation and proprioception without loss of pain and temperature, or vice-versa.,Dissociated sensory loss indicates a focal lesion within the spinal cord or brainstem.

Trophic changes is a term used to describe abnormalities in the area of pain that include primarily wasting away of the skin, tissues, or muscle, thinning of the bones, and changes in how the hair or nails grow, including thickening or thinning of hair or brittle nails.
Spontaneous pain is a kind of neuropathic pain which occurs without an identifiable trigger.

Pain is an unpleasant sensation that can range from mild, localized discomfort to agony, whereby the physical part of pain results from nerve stimulation and is often accompanied by an emotional component. This term groups abnormalities in pain sensation presumed to result from abnormalities related to the specific nerve fibers that carry the pain impulses to the brain.
A loss or impairment of the sensation of the relative position of parts of the body and joint position.
An increased concentration of copper in the urine.
A reduced sense of touch (tactile sensation). This is usually tested with a wisp of cotton or a fine camel's hair brush, by asking patients to say 'now' each time they feel the stimulus.
description_code: Impaired touch sensation,Loss of tactile sensation

value_en: Abnormality of the seventh cranial nerve
description_en: Abnormality of the seventh cranial nerve sometimes also referred to as the facial nerve.

value_en: Abnormality of the twelfth cranial nerve
description_en: Abnormality of the twelfth cranial nerve.
description_code: Abnormality of cranial nerve xii,Abnormality of the hypoglossal nerve,Abnormality of cranial nerve 12

value_en: Abnormality of the eleventh cranial nerve
description_en: Abnormality of the eleventh cranial nerve.
description_code: Abnormality of the accessory nerve,Abnormality of cranial nerve XI

description_en: Any structural abormality of the fifth cranial nerve.
description_code: Abnormal trigeminal nerve morphology,Abnormality of the nervus trigeminus,Abnormality of the fifth cranial nerve

description_en: An overlap of the bony plates of the skull in an infant, with or without early closure.

A scintillating scotoma is a common visual aura that can preced a migraine, whereby a spot of flickering light near the center of the visual fields occurs. The spot prevents vision, and is thus termed scotoma. The scotoma can extend into one or more shimmering arcs of white or colored flashing lights.

A type of seizure characterized by laughing or an outburst of laughing as a major feature.,Laughter is usually lasts briefly, about 30s. Laughing can also be a component of several other kinds of seizures such as partial seizures with motor symptoms, myoclonic seizures, axial tonic seizures, flexor spasms, generalized convulsive seizures, and petit mal absences.
A type of seizure characterized by crying or an outburst of crying as a major feature.,The word dacrystic is derived from the Greek word dakryon (tear).

A reduced ability to discriminate between different temperatures.,Temperature sensation can be tested by touching the skin several seconds with a water flask filled to the desired temperature. Persons with normal temperature sensation should at least be able to identify as warm a flask that is 35-36 degrees C and identify as cool a flask at 28-32 degrees C.
description_code: Impaired temperature sensation,Loss of temperature sensation,Abnormality of temperature sensation

description_en: Intermittent clonic or tonic contraction of muscles supplied by facial nerve. Muscles are relaxed in between contractions.,Hemifacial spasm presents in the fifth or sixth decade of life, and is almost always unilateral. An attack usually begins with brief clonic movements of the orbicularis oculi and spreads over years to other facial muscles. Hemifacial spasm is often the result of chronic irritation of the facial nerve or nucleus.
description_code: Spasms on one side of the face,Hemifacial spasms

description_en: Epidermal naevi are due to an overgrowth of the epidermis and may be present at birth (50%) or develop during childhood.,Epidermal nevus arises from a defect in the ectoderm and in general are due to an overgrowth of keratinocytes. Subclasses of epidermal nevus include Linear epidermal naevus, epidermolytic epidermal naevus, acantholytic epidermal naevus, linear porokeratosis, and systematised epidermal naevus. Several other conditions are also characterised by benign overgrowth of the epidermis and its appendages (organoid naevi), including inflammatory linear verrucous epidermal naevus, sebaceous naevus, sweat gland naevi, comedone naevus, and Becker naevus.

A congenital, hairless plaque consisting of overgrown epidermis, sebaceous glands, hair follicles, apocrine glands and connective tissue. They are a variant of epidermal naevi. Sebaceous naevi most often appear on the scalp, but they may also arise on the face, neck or forehead. At birth, a sevaceous nevus typically appears as a solitary, smooth, yellow-orange hairless patch. Sebaceous naevi become more pronounced around adolescence, often appearing bumpy, warty or scaly.
description_code: Naevus sebaceous,Sebaceous mole,Organoid nevus,Sebaceous nevus,Sebaceous naevus

description_en: Hair growth from a single point on the scalp in any location other than lateral to the midline and close to the vertex of the skull.,Placement of hair whorl should be described as parietal, vertex, eccentric, etc. In addition, the number of hair whorls should be noted. Five percent of the population has two whorls.
description_code: Abnormal position of hair whorl,Abnormal location of hair swirl

description_en: More than two clockwise hair whorls.,Most individuals have one clockwise hair whorl at a single point on the scalp lateral to the midline but close to the vertex of the skull. Five percent of the population has two whorls. A double hair whorl is sometimes referred to as a double crown. In 10%, whorl direction is counter-clockwise.
description_code: Supernumary hair swirls,Double crown (hair whorls),Supernumary hair whorl,Extra hair whorl,Abnormal number of hair swirls,Extra hair swirls,Abnormal number of hair whorls

description_en: Decreased length of the uvula.,Objective measurement of the length of the uvula can be determined on a lateral cephalograms. However, in this series we are not relying on radiographs for assessment of findings. In clinical practice, the size of the uvula cannot be easily measured and is not static, since it depends on the position of the soft palate, the base of the tongue, and the head. Therefore, judgment of change in length of the uvula depends heavily on the experience of the observer.
Decreased width of the uvula.

Increased length of the uvula.,In clinical practice, the size of the uvula cannot be easily measured and is not static, since it depends on the position of the soft palate, the base of the tongue, and the head. Therefore, judgment of change in length of the uvula depends heavily on the experience of the observer.
description_code: Hyperplasia of uvula,Long palatine uvula,Elongated uvula

description_en: Seizures characterized by a sudden loss or diminution of muscle tone, which may be fragmentary, confined to a segment (limb, jaw, head), or massive, leading to a slumping to the ground .
description_code: drop seizures,drop attacks,astatic seizures,Hypotonic seizures,Sudden loss of muscle tone

description_en: Generalized seizures with sustained increase in muscle contraction lasting a few seconds to minutes.,Characterized by a sudden increase in muscle tone whereby the body, arms, or legs make sudden stiffening movements and consciousness is usually preserved. Tonic seizures can occur during sleep. Tonic seizures usually affect both sides of the body, and cause a fall if the affected person was standing when the seizure started.
A type of nevus sebaceous with a linear form, raised borders and yellowish color.

Oral commissures positioned superior to the midline labial fissure.,This finding should be assessed with the mouth closed, the lips in relaxed contact, and the face relaxed. The finding may be difficult to assess if the upper lip is enlarged.
description_code: Upturned corners of mouth,Upturned oral commisures,Upturned mouth

description_en: Triangular appearance of the oral aperture with the apex in the midpoint of the upper vermilion and the lower vermilion forming the base.,This finding is distinguished from an Exaggerated Cupid's bow by the alteration of the shape of the oral aperture.
description_code: Inverted V-shaped upper lip,Tented mouth,Tented upper lip

description_en: Inner aspect of the upper lip vermilion (normally apposing the teeth) visible in a frontal view, i.e., the presence of an everted upper lip.,In frontal view, with the face relaxed, the apparent height of the upper lip vermilion is excessive and the upper incisors may be visible. On profile view, the vermilion is more convex than usual. An everted upper lip may be associated with a short philtrum, and may be secondary to protruded upper teeth, but these should be assessed and described separately.
description_code: Eclabium of upper lip,Outward turned upper lip,Everted upper lip,Everted prominent upper lip,Protruding upper lip,Drooping upper lip

description_en: Increased pigmentation, either focal or generalized, of the skin surrounding the vermilion of the lips.,Periorbital hyperpigmentation may be accompanied by Lip freckles, but this should be assessed separately.
description_code: Increased pigmentation around the mouth,Darkening of skin around the mouth

description_en: Reduced bulkiness of the crease or fold of skin running from the lateral margin of the nose, where nasal base meets the skin of the face, to a point just lateral to the corner of the mouth (cheilion or commissure).
description_code: Shallow nasolabial fold,Nasolabial crease, underdeveloped,Flat nasolabial fold,Nasolabial fold, hypoplastic,Nasolabial crease, hypoplastic

description_en: Lack of paramedian peaks and median notch of the upper lip vermilion.,This bow is often absent in a Thin vermilion of the upper lip, but that should be assessed separately. This finding is commonly associated with Smooth philtrum, but that should be coded separately.
description_code: Agenesis of cupid's bow,Absent cupid's bow,Missing cupid's bow,Failure of development of cupid's bow,Lack of cupid's bow,Aplasia of cupid's bow

description_en: Increased width of the uvula (subjective finding).,This finding often accompanies a Submucous cleft palate, but this should be coded separately. A longitudinal groove indicating incomplete fusion of the two parts of the uvula may be present with a broadened uvula and has sometimes been called abortive cleft uvula.
Tongue extending beyond the alveolar ridges or teeth at rest.,Protruding tongue may or may not be associated with a Large tongue, and that finding should be assessed and coded separately.
description_code: Lingual protrusion,Lingual prolapse,Lingual prominence,Tongue protrusion,Prolapse of tongue,Protruding tongue,Prominent tongue,Tongue sticking out of mouth

description_en: Visible space between the dental arches in occlusion.,An open bite produces an absence of vertical overlap of the two dental arches. It may be associated with malocclusion, but this should be coded separately. Open bite can be accompanied by malocclusion, which is a complex bundled term. The Angle classification of malocclusion (Classes I-III) is widely used in the orthodontics community [Moyers, [1973]] for the characterization of malocclusion.
description_code: Open bite between upper and lower teeth,Absence of overlap of upper and lower teeth,Open bite

description_en: Decreased length of the eyelashes (subjective).,Normal values are 7.99 - 1.05 mm in boys and 7.76 - 1.03 mm in girls.
Non-continuity of the arch of aorta with an atretic point or absent segment.
description_code: Atretic transverse aortic arch,Aortic arch obstruction

description_en: Insertion of the posterior columella below the nasal base.,This feature is different from a convex Low hanging columella that has a normal insertion. It may be associated with a Short philtrum, but this should be assessed and coded separately. A low insertion is best appreciated when viewed from the side.
description_code: Ala higher than columella,Columella, low insertion

description_en: Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) whereby the aortic arch is hypoplastic or interrupted, and a large patent ductus arteriosus is present.,According to the Van Praagh classification (pmid:2856609). The Van Praagh classification additionally specifies the presence (subtype A) or absence (subtype B) of a ventricular septal defect.
description_code: Persistent truncus arteriosus type IV,Type 4 truncus arteriosus

description_en: A chordoma is a tumors that arises from embryonic remnants of the notochord along the length of the neuraxis. Chordomas generally occur in the sacrum, intracranially at the clivus, or along the spinal axis.,The notochord is a mesodermal embryonic structure that defines the primitive axis of the embryo and which survives in the adult vertebral column as the intervertebral disks.
Increased width of the columella.
description_code: Columella, broad,Increased width of columella,Fullness of columella,Columella, wide,Hyperplasia of columella

description_en: Aplasia of a toe. That is, absence of all phalanges of a non-hallux digit of the foot and the associated soft tissues.,This descriptor does NOT require absence of the metatarsal. The definition excludes partial absent hallux.
description_code: Aplasia of toe,Absent toe,Aplasia of the toes,Absent toes

description_en: Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) with each pulmonary artery arising separate from each other on the posterior or lateral aspect of the truncus.,According to the Van Praagh classification (pmid:2856609). The Van Praagh classification additionally specifies the presence (subtype A) or absence (subtype B) of a ventricular septal defect.
description_code: Type 2 truncus arteriosus,Persistent truncus arteriosus type II

description_en: Prominent positioning of the premaxilla in relation to the rest of the maxilla, the facial skeleton, or mandible. Not necessarily caused by an increase in size (hypertrophy of) the premaxilla.,As a consequence of prominence of the premaxilla, the overlying structures, the nose and philtrum, may appear prominent. There is increased convexity of the face and an increased nasolabial angle. In the presence of a normal sized mandible, retrognathia may be appreciated.
description_code: Premaxillary bone excess,Prominence of the primary palate bone,Prominence of the intermaxillary bone,Anterior position of the primary palate bone,Anterior position of the premaxilla

description_en: An abnormality of the premaxilla [UBERON_0002244], the most anterior part of the maxilla that usually bears the central and lateral incisors and includes the anterior nasal spine and inferior aspect of the piriform rim. The premaxilla contains the bone and teeth of the primary palate.
description_code: Abnormality of the primary palate bone,Abnormality of the intermaxillary bone,Abnormality of the intermaxillary segment of the maxilla,Abnormality of the premaxillary bone

value_en: Congenitally corrected transposition of the great arteries with ventricular septal defect
description_en: A congenitally corrected transposition of the great arteries with a ventricular septal defect: a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart. The ventricular septal defect is centered around the most superior aspect of the ventricular septum.
Absence of the Premaxilla, which is the embryonic structure that forms the anterior part of the maxilla.
description_code: Missing primary palate bone,Absence of the primary palate bone,Failure of development of the primary palate bone,Absence of the premaxilla,Absence of the intermaxillary bone,Missing premaxilla,Aplasia of the intermaxillary bone,Failure of development of premaxilla,Aplasia of the primary palate bone

description_en: A congenital anomaly with an abnormal connection between the aorta and the main pulmonary artery resulting in an aortopulmonary shunt.
Absence or underdevelopment of the premaxilla.
description_code: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the intermaxillary bone,Aplasia/hypoplasia of the primary palate bone

value_en: Increased susceptibility to spontaneous sister chromatid exchange
description_en: An increase in the number of spontaneous sister chromatid exchanges observed in cell culture of lymphocytes or other cells.,Increased susceptibility to spontaneous sister chromatid exchange is characteristic for Bloom syndrome.

value_en: Congenital malformation of the great arteries
description_en: Defect or defects of the morphogenesis of the aorta and pulmonary arteries.
Asymmetry between the left and right sides of the maxilla.
description_code: Asymmetry of the upper jaw,Asymmetry of upper jaw,Crooked upper jaw,Canted upper jaw,Asymmetry of right and left side of the maxilla,Uneven upper jaw,Crooked maxilla,Uneven maxilla,Tilted upper jaw,Unequal sides of maxilla,Tilted maxilla,Canted maxilla,Deviation of the upper jaw,Deviation of the maxilla

value_en: Chromosomal breakage induced by ionizing radiation
description_en: Increased amount of chromosomal breaks in cultured blood lymphocytes or other cells induced by treatment with ionizing radiation.,Increased tendency to chromosomal breakage induced by crosslinking agents is typical for several disorders including ataxia teleangiectasia and Nijmegen breakage syndrome.
Abnormal plane of direction of the heart from the base to the apex in the midline. Left sided is normal.
An anomaly of the temporomandibular joint.
description_code: Malformation of jaw joint,Deformity of the jaw joint,Abnormality of the jaw joint,Anomaly of the temporomandibular joint,Malformation of the temporomandibular joint,Deformity of the temporomandibular joint,Derangement of the temporomandibular joint

description_en: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a monocarboxylic acid in the blood circulation.
Abnormal plane of direction of the heart from the base to the apex towards the right. Left sided is normal.

Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) whereby one of the two pulmonary artery branched does not arise from the common pulmonary trunk, but instead from the ductus arteriosus or directly from the aorta.,According to the Van Praagh classification (pmid:2856609). The Van Praagh classification additionally specifies the presence (subtype A) or absence (subtype B) of a ventricular septal defect.
description_code: Persistent truncus arteriosus type III,Type 3 truncus arteriosus

description_en: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a dicarboxylic acid in the blood circulation.,A dicarboxylic acid is an oxoacid containing two carboxy groups.
Abnormal plane of direction of the heart from the base to the apex. Left sided is normal.
Midline deficiency of the mandible and some or all overlying tissues.

Abnormality of the striatum, which is the largest nucleus of the basal ganglia, comprising the caudate, putamen and ventral striatum, including the nucleus accumbens.,The striatum (also known as the neostriatum or striate nucleus) contains the caudate nucleus and putamen, which are separated from one another by a white matter tract called the internal capsule. The striatum is part of the basal ganglia and receives input from the cerebral cortex. Essentially all cortical areas (sensory, motor and associational) project to the striatum. The other major input to the striatum comes from the thalamus, particularly the intralaminar thalamic nuclei.
description_code: Abnormality of the striatum,Abnormality of the striate nucleus,Abnormality of the neostriatum

description_en: A persistent midline depression of the skin over the fat pad of the chin.
description_code: Dimple chin,Chin dent,Chin skin dimple,Chin butt,Chin dimple,Indentation of chin,Gelasin of chin,Chin dimples

description_en: An abnormality of the cerebral subcortex.,The cerebral subcortex contains the basal ganglia and the cerebral white matter.
Loss of elasticity of the upper and lower eyelids causing the skin to sag and bulge.
description_code: Droopy eyelid skin,Baggy eyes,Redundant eyelid skin,Extra eyelid skin,Eyelid dermatochalasia,Hooding of eyelids

description_en: Involuntary urine leakage synchronous with exertion, or actions such as sneezing, or coughing.
An abnormality of the abdominal musculature.

value_en: Abnormality of the common coagulation pathway
description_en: An abnormality of blood coagulation, common pathway.,The common pathway is a protein activation cascade that contributes to blood coagulation and consists of events leading from the formation of activated factor X to the formation of active thrombin, the cleavage of fibrinogen by thrombin, and the formation of cleaved fibrin into a stable multimeric, cross-linked complex.

Blepharochalasis is characterized by recurrent, non-painful, nonerythematous episodes of eyelid edema. It has been divided into hypertrophic and atrophic forms. In the hypertrophic form recurrent edema results in orbital fat herniation through a weakened orbital septum. Most patients who have blepharochalasis present in an atrophic condition with atrophy of redundant eyelid skin and superior nasal fat pads.,Most patients who have blepharochalasis present in an atrophic condition with atrophy of redundant eyelid skin and superior nasal fat pads. Most of these atrophic patients do not go through a hypertrophic phase. Multiple attacks of eyelid edema result in thinning, stretching, and atrophy of eyelid tissues. The eyelid skin becomes redundant, discolored, and atrophic, appearing like wrinkled cigarette paper. The upper eyelids are more commonly affected, but the lower eyelids may also be involved. Blepharochalasis is not synonymous with dermatochalasis.

Positioning of a lacrimal punctum other than at the medial margins of the eyelid.,The openings of the tear ducts are normally located at the medial margin of each eyelid. The opening on the lower eyelid border is more visible than the opening on the upper eyelid border. Ectopic positions can include the upper eyelid, nasal bridge, or inferior to medial aspect of the lower lid.
description_code: Abnormal position of the lacrimal punctum

description_en: An abnormal distribution of eyebrow hair growth in the medial direction.

An abnormality of the intrinsic pathway (also known as the contact activation pathway) of the coagulation cascade.,The intrinsic pathway requires coagulation factors VIII, IX, X, XI, and XII, as well as the proteins prekallikrein (PK) and high-molecular-weight kininogen (HK or HMWK), in addition to calcium ions and phospholipids secreted from platelets.

value_en: Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the toes

description_en: An abnormality of the extrinsic pathway (also known as the tissue factor pathway) of the coagulation cascade.,The extrinsic pathway is a protein activation cascade that contributes to blood coagulation and consists of the self-limited process linking exposure and activation of tissue factor to the activation of clotting factor X.

value_en: Aplasia of the phalanges of the toes
description_en: Absence of a digit or of one or more phalanges of a toe.
description_code: Absent bones of the toes,Aphalangia of the toes

description_en: An abnormality of the morphology or counts of the cells that make up the immune system.
A developmental abnormality characterized by the absence (aplasia) of a metatarsal bone.
description_code: Aplasia of the metatarsal bones,Absent long bone of foot

description_en: Diminished length of a metatarsal bone, with resultant proximal displacement of the associated toe.,This is a subjective assessment and one generally compares the position of the MTP joint to that of the contralateral digit or the putatively shortened ray in proportion to the other rays. The affected digits should be specified.
description_code: Short long bone of foot,Short metatarsals,Hypoplastic metatarsals,Hypoplasia of the metatarsal bones,Shortened metatarsals,Short metatarsal bone,Short metatarsal bones

description_en: A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on the sex chromosomes.
An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin of the arms.
A type of multifactorial inheritance governed by the simultaneous action of two gene loci.
An abnormal accumulation of excess fluid in the lower extremity resulting in swelling of the feet and extending upward to the lower leg.
description_code: Edema of the lower limbs,Bipedal edema,Peripheral edema of lower extremity,Fluid accumulation in lower limbs,Lower leg swelling,Leg edema

description_en: A type of multifactorial inheritance governed by the simultaneous action of a few gene loci. It is recommended this term be used for traits governed by three loci, although it is noted that usage of this term in the literature is not uniform.

A lamellar pattern visible on radiographs and mainly localized at the metaphyses of the long tubular bones. Pathologic-anatomical studies revealed that these benign signs on x-rays are the result of a juvenile metaphyseal bone necrosis. Calcifications in the necrotic marrow lead to this lamellar or lattice-like appearance.
A type of multifactorial inheritance governed by the simultaneous action of many (more than three) gene loci.
An abnormal decrease in the level of lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.
An abnormal increase in the level of lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

Osteopoikilosis is a benign, asymptomatic sclerotic dysplasia of the bones. It affects both male and female and may be seen at any age. Radiographically sclerotic circular or ovoid lesions are usually symmetrically distributed in a periarticular location. Lesions can increase or decrease in size and number in serial radiographs or even disappear and do not have increased bone radiotracer uptake.
Fibrous dysplasia of the bones were lesions are localized in only one bone.
A functional abnormality of the immune system.
Fibrous dysplasia of the bones were lesions are localized in many bones throughout of the body. Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia is a cardinal feature of McCune-Albright syndrome.

An abnormal functioning of phagocytosis. Phagocytosis is an elegant but complex process for the ingestion and elimination of pathogens, but it is also important for the elimination of apoptotic cells and hence fundamental for tissue homeostasis. Phagocytosis can be divided into four main steps: (i) recognition of the target particle, (ii) signaling to activate the internalization machinery, (iii) phagosome formation, and (iv) phagolysosome maturation.

Tumor-like growths that consist of replacement of the medullary bone with fibrous tissue, causing the expansion and weakening of the areas of bone involved. Especially when involving the skull or facial bones, the lesions can cause externally visible deformities. The skull is often, but not necessarily, affected, and any other bone or bones may be involved. Fibrous dysplasia can either effect isolated bones (Monostotic fibrous dysplasia) or also generalized all bones of the body (Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia).
An abnormal decrease from the normal count of B cells.,Plasma B cells differentiate from B cells and secrete large amounts of antibodies.
description_code: Low B cell count,Reduction in B cell number,B cell lymphopenia

description_en: Naevus flammeus localised in the skin of the eyelid.
A deviation from the normal count of B cells, i.e., the cells that are formed in the bone marrow, migrate to the peripheral lymphatic system, and mature into plasma cells or memory cells.
description_code: Abnormality of B cell count,Abnormality of B cell numbers,Abnormal number of B cells,Abnormal numbers of B cells

description_en: Nodular changes affecting the eyelids may have many different causes such as cystic lesions (chalaziae, hordeolae), lipogranulomas, melanomas, infectious diseases (Molluscum contagiosum) and many more.
An abnormality of myeloid leukocytes.,A myeloid leukocyte refers to a cell of the monocyte, granulocyte, or mast cell lineage.

value_en: Extension of eyebrows towards upper eyelid
description_en: The eyebrows extend towards - or even all the way down to - the margin of the upper eyelid.,This is commonly a feature of Jacobson syndrome.
description_code: Extension of eyebrows towards upper eyelid

description_en: This may present as a partial or complete duplication of the eyebrows.,Double eyebrow is commonly a feature of Mowat Wilson syndrome.
A kind of anemia characterized by inadequate production of erythrocytes.

value_en: Absence of Lutheran antigen on erythrocytes
description_en: Absence of the Lutheran antigen (a type I integral membrane glycoprotein) from the surface of red blood cells.
An abnormality of an erythrocyte cell surface molecule.,During development, the human immune system recognizes antigens of the body as 'self' and does not generate antibodies against them.
A developmental defect characterized by absence of the retina.
Rupture of the eyeball not due to trauma.
An abnormality of glycolipid metabolism.
Abnormal prominence of the corneal nerve fibers.
An abnormality of liposaccharide metabolism.

Any deviation from the normal concentration of carnitine in the blood circulation.,L-carnitine (3-hydroxy-4-N.trimethylammonium butyrate) plays a key role in facilitating the transport of long-chain fatty acids from the cytosol into the mitochondrial matrix, where they undergo 13-oxidation.

value_en: Advanced pneumatization of the mastoid process
description_en: An abnormally advanced degree of pneumatization (i.e., formation of air cells) in the mastoid process with respect to age-dependent norms.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of a fatty acid anion in the blood circulation.,A fatty acid anion is the conjugate base of a fatty acid.

Any deviation from the normal concentration of phytanic acid in the blood circulation.,Phytanic acid is a branched-chain saturated fatty acid consisting of hexadecanoic acid carrying methyl substituents at positions 3, 7, 11 and 15.
An asymmetriy, i.e., difference in size, shape or position between the left and right ear.

Any deviation from the normal concentration of a long-chain fatty acid in the blood circulation.,A long-chain fatty-acid is defined as an aliphatic monocarboxylic acid with a chain length of C13 to C18.
An abnormal hair whorl (that is, a patch of hair growing in the opposite direction of the rest of the hair).
description_code: Abnormal hair whorl,Abnormal hair whorls,Abnormal whorl of hair

value_en: Absence of stomach bubble on fetal sonography
description_en: By the 14th week of gestation it is nearly always possible to visualized the fluid-filled fetal stomach bubble on prenatal sonography. This term refers to the absence of a normal fetal stomach bubble on fetal ultrasonography performed at around 16 to 20 weeks' gestation.,The absence of stomach bubble on fetal sonography can be an indication of malformations such as esophageal atresia, especially in combination with polyhydramnios.

value_en: Cherry red spot of the macula
description_en: Pallor of the perifoveal macula of the retina with appearance of a small circular reddish choroid shape as seen through the fovea centralis due to relative transparancy of the macula.

Shoulder dystocia occurs when the fetal anterior shoulder impacts against the maternal symphysis following delivery of the vertex.,Adelivery in which additional maneuvers are required to deliver the fetus after normal gentle downward traction has failed.

value_en: Double outlet right ventricle with subaortic ventricular septal defect and pulmonary stenosis
description_en: A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the aortic origin. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
description_code: DORV with subaortic VSD and pulmonary stenosis

description_en: Delivery of newborn by means of a ventouse, a vacuum device used to assist the delivery of a baby when the second stage of labour has not progressed adequately.
Delivery of a fetus through surgical incisions made through the abdominal wall (laparotomy) and the uterine wall (hysterotomy).

value_en: Double outlet right ventricle with doubly committed ventricular septal defect without pulmonary stenosis
description_en: A double outlet right ventricle with a subaortic ventritricular septal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that extends anterosuperiorly and are closely related to the pulmonary artery as well, are considered to be doubly committed. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
description_code: Double outlet right ventricle, doubly committed ventricular septal defect,DORV with doubly committed VSD

value_en: Double outlet right ventricle with doubly committed ventricular septal defect and pulmonary stenosis
description_en: A double outlet right ventricle with a subaortic ventritricular septal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that extends anterosuperiorly and are closely related to the pulmonary artery as well, are considered to be doubly committed. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
description_code: DORV with doubly committed VSD and pulmonary stenosis

description_en: The presence of both a left and a right ductus arteriosus.
Intrauterine growth retardation that is at least 3 standard deviations (SD) below average, but not as low as 4 SD, corrected for sex and gestational age.

value_en: Patent ductus arteriosus after premature birth
description_en: Abnormal persistent patency of the ductus arteriosus when birth was at less than 37 weeks completed gestation.
A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs with onset in infancy.

value_en: Patent ductus arteriosus after birth at term
description_en: Abnormal persistent patency of the ductus arteriosus in postnatal life when birth was at 37 completed weeks of gestation or greater.

Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized distal to the ductus arteriosus, i.e., to the postductal region of aortic arch.,Blood flow to the aorta distal to the coarctation may be dependent on a patent ductus arteriosus, and hence closure of the ductus arteriosus can lead to serious ischemia of the affected tissues.
A neoplasm of the pineal gland.
A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short trunk but a average-sized limbs that is lethal at birth.

Narrowing or constriction of the aorta localized at the insertion of the ductus arteriosus, i.e., to the juxtaductal region of aortic arch.,Juxtaductal coarctation usually presents when the ductus arteriosus closes.

Increased focal pigmentation of the vermilion of the lips.,Lip freckles may be accompanied by Perioral hyperpigmentation, but this should be assessed separately. Lentigo is commonly used as a synonym for freckle in reference to the vermilion, but these are distinct terms when referring to the skin.
description_code: Lip freckle,Labial lentigo,Ephelis of lip,Lip lentigo

value_en: Dilatation of the sinus of Valsalva
description_en: Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation of one of the anatomic dilations of the ascending aorta, which occurs just above the aortic valve.,Aneurysm is considered a severe form of dilatation.
description_code: Aortic sinus aneurysm,Sinus of Valsalva aneurysm,Aneurysm of the aortic sinus

description_en: A hemangioblastoma is a benign vascular neoplasm that arises almost exclusively in the central nervous system. Hemangioblastomas consist of a tightly packed cluster of small blood vessels forming a mass of up to 1 or 2 cm in diameter.
Demyelination of peripheral sensory nerves.
A venous pouch within the left ventricular wall, with a neck opening into the coronary sinus.
A glioma affecting the brainstem.
Delayed myelination in the peripheral nervous system.

An atrial septal defect characterized by a deficiency in the tissue separating the coronary sinus from the left atrium (LA). This results in partial or complete unroofing of the coronary sinus leading to a predominantly left-to-right shunt through the coronary sinus (LA to coronary sinus to right atrium [RA]). The orifice of the ostium is frequently large because of the increased flow. From the RA side, the defect is located at the level of the coronary sinus ostium and may also include some deficiency in atrial tissue around the ostium. From the LA side, the size can be variable depending on the degree of unroofing of the coronary sinus.
A glioma affecting the cerebellum.

An abnormality of myelination of nerves in the central nervous system.,In the CNS, myelin is the product of oligodendrocytes (and not of Schwann cells, as in the PNS). This term refers to an abnormality of the process in which myelin sheaths are formed and maintained around neurons or the result of such an abnormality.

An abnormality of the coronary sinus, which is formed by the union of the great cardiac vein and the left marginal vein and terminates in the right atrium. The coronary sinus functions to o collect deoxygenated blood from the myocardium of the heart and drain it into the right atrium.

Reduced ability affecting mainly visuospatial cognition which may be tested using pattern construction (for example by Differential Ability Scales, which test a person's strengths and weaknesses across a range of intellectual abilities).,The ability to see an object or picture as a set of parts and then to construct a replica of the original from these parts is known as visuospatial constructive cognition. Impaired visuospatial constructive cognition is one of the characteristic featrues of most patients with Williams-Beuren Syndrome.

A congenital malformation with abnormal connection between one of the coronary arteries and a heart chamber or another blood vessel.,Coronary artery fistulas are congenital malformations. This term does not apply to surgical fistulas.
A digit with two nails, with at least some soft tissue between them.
The presence of a single coronary artery ostium from which both coronary arteries arise.
Hypertrophy or overdevelopment of the interstitial (Leydig) cells of the testis. These cells produce testosterone.
Underdevelopment of the interstitial (Leydig) cells of the testis. These cells produce testosterone.

value_en: Anomalous origin of right coronary artery from the pulmonary artery
description_en: Right coronary artery begins (branches off from) the pulmonary artery rather than as normal from the root of the aorta, above the right cusp of the aortic valve.

value_en: Anomalous origin of left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery
description_en: Left main coronary artery begins (branches off from) the pulmonary artery rather than as normal from the root of the aorta, above the left cusp of the aortic valve.,In this anomaly the function of the LMCA territory often requires extensive collateral formation from the RCA, which is often dilated. In the first month of life, physiologic pulmonary hypertension tends to preserve anterograde flow within the left coronary artery, and infants are usually asymptomatic. As pulmonary pressure drops, left-to-right shunting from the higher pressure left coronary arterial system to the lower pressure pulmonary arterial system occurs, and patients become symptomatic. Imaging findings may include markedly dilated collateral arteries and coronary veins.
description_code: Anomalous left coronary artery from the pulmonary artery,Bland-Garland-White syndrome,ALCAPA

value_en: Anomalous origin of coronary artery from the pulmonary artery
description_en: A coronary artery begins (branches off from) the pulmonary artery rather than as normal from the root of the aorta.

Isolated abnormalities of the coronary artery origins. This may be in associated with other structural heart malformations but not the patterns of complex structural heart malformations which result in abnormal course of the coronary arteries.
The presence of a neoplasm of the testis.
Lack of a part of the pericardium over the diaphragmatic surface of the heart. It is a congenital defect, not the result of a pericardectomy. Pericardium is present on other parts of the heart.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the genital system.

value_en: Partial left sided absence of pericardium
description_en: A congenital anomaly with lack of part of the pericardium on the lefthand side of the heart.,A congenital anomaly and not the result of a pericardectomy.
The presence of a neoplasm of the urinary system.

value_en: Complete left sided absence of pericardium
description_en: A congenital anomaly with complete lack of the pericardium on the lefthand side of the heart.,A congenital anomaly and not the result of a pericardectomy.
description_code: Absent lining around of left side of heart

description_en: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of a gonad.

value_en: Partial right sided absence of pericardium
description_en: A congenital anomaly with lack of part of the pericardium on the righthand side of the heart.,A congenital anomaly and not the result of a pericardectomy.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the uterus.

value_en: Complete right sided absence of pericardium
description_en: No pericardium is present on the righthand side of the heart. It is a congenital absence of pericardium rather than the result of a pericardectomy.
Redness of the skin, caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin.
description_code: Redness of skin or mucous membrane

description_en: No pericardium over the diaphragmatic surface of the heart. It is a congenital defect, not the result of a pericardectomy. Pericardium is present on other parts of the heart.
A subtype of skin dimples occurring in the shoulder region.,Symmetrical dimples of the skin overlying the acromial process of the scapulae are called bi-acromial dimples.
Skin dimples are cutaneous indentations that are the result of tethering of the skin to underlying structures (bone) causing an indentation.

Over-sensitivity to certain frequency ranges of sound.,Hyperacusis refers to a general hypersensitivity to sound of any frequency, and phonophobia to an anxious sensitivity towards specific sound largely independent of its volume. Hyperacusis and phonophobia represent disturbances of central auditory processing without peripheral pathology, often combined with psychosomatic reactions.
No pericardium around the heart, occurring as a congenital defect, not the result of a surgical pericardectomy.
description_code: Absent pericardium,Congenital absence of the pericardium

description_en: A developmental defect of the pericardium with congenital onset.
Aorto-ventricular tunnel is a congenital, extracardiac channel which connects the ascending aorta above the sinutubular junction to the cavity of the left, or (less commonly) right ventricle.
The presence of an abnormally large pelvis.
Right pulmonary venous return to the inferior vena cava.
Marked widening of the trachea.
A type of muscular ventricular septal defect characterized by the presence of multiple small defects in the ventricular septum.
Marked widening of the major bronchi that may be predispose to chronic respiratory tract infection.
A muscular ventricular septal defect located at the apex of the heart.

Marked widening of the trachea and major bronchi that may be predispose to chronic respiratory tract infection.,Tracheobronchmegaly is typically characterized by atrophy or absence of elastic fibers and thinning of smooth muscle layers in the trachea and main bronchi.

The trabecular septum is the largest part of the interventricular septum. It extends from the membranous septum to the apex and superiorly to the infundibular septum. A defect in the trabecular septum is called muscular VSD if the defect is completely rimmed by muscle.
description_code: Type 4 ventricular septal defect,Ventricular septal defect, muscular

description_en: A developmental defect of the aortic arch system in which the trachea and esophagus are completely encircled by connected segments of the aortic arch and its branches. This occurs if the normal process of regression and persistence of the bilateral embryonic aortic arches fails.

A ventricular septal defect that involves the inlet of the right ventricular septum immediately inferior to the AV valve apparatus.,The muscular septum is a nonplanar structure that can be divided into inlet, trabecular, and infundibular components. The inlet portion is inferioposterior to the membranous septum. It begins at the level of the atrioventricular valves and ends at their chordal attachments apically.
description_code: Type 3 ventricular septal defect,Atrioventricular canal type ventricular septal defect

description_en: The presence of an additional membrane in the left or right cardiac atrium which results in the subdivision of the affected atrium (and thus in total three atria, whence the name).

A type of ventricular septal defect communicating directly between the left ventricle and right atrium. This is anatomically possible because the normal tricuspid valve is more apically displaced than the mitral valve.,Echocardiography may visualize a jet across a small defect between left ventricle and right atrium.
A form of anomalous pulmonary venous return in which not all pulmonary veins drain abnormally. Partial anomalous pulmonary venous return frequently involves one or both of the veins from one lung.
An abnormality of the abdominal situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the abdomen and its organs.

A developmental defect characterized by abnormal connection of one or more pulmonary veins to the superior or inferior vena cava, the right atrium, or the coronary sinus, resulting in a left-to-right shunt of oxygenated blood.
A hair-containing cyst or sinus usually in the coccygeal region.

value_en: Pulmonary situs ambiguus with bilateral morphologic left lungs
description_en: An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, in which both lungs have the morphology of a left lung.

value_en: Pulmonary situs ambiguus with bilateral morphologic right lungs
description_en: An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, in which both lungs have the morphology of a right lung.
An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, in which the morphology of both left and right lungs is the same.
A sinus in the coccygeal region (the region of the intergluteal cleft). A pilonidal sinus often contains hair and skin debris.
Mirror image arrangement of the mainstem bronchi with the right pulmonary artery posterior to the right upper lobe bronchus and the left pulmonary artery anterior to the left upper lobe bronchus.

An abnormality of the pulmonary situs, i.e., of the sidedness of the morphological right and left lungs, which is defined by characteristics such as the number of lobes per lung and the relationship of the pulmonary arteries to their bronchi.
The presence of a cyst, fistula, or abscess in the sacrococcygeal region (gluteal crease) characteristically accompanied by hair and skin folds.
Non-continuity of the aortic arch with an atretic point or absent segment between the innominate and left carotid arteries.
Deposition of calcium salts in a tissue or location in which calcification does not normally occur.
Non-continuity of the aortic arch with an atretic point or absent segment between the left carotid and subclavian arteries.
Hyperkeratosis affecting the palm of the hand.
Non-continuity of the aortic arch with an atretic point or absent segment at the level of the isthmus.
Hypsarrhythmia occurring in one hemisphere.

This term refers to the loss of eyelashes that were previously present.,Common causes of loss of eyelashes include inflammation, autoimmunity, tumors,endocrine disorders, drugs and medications, and a number of congenital conditions.
description_code: Loss of eyelashes,Milphosis,Ciliary Madarosis,Missing eyelashes,Eyelashes fell out

An abnormality of the malleus, an ossicle in the middle ear.

description_en: Occurrence of epileptiform discharges in occipital regions during photic stimulation.
An abnormality of the incus, an ossicle in the middle ear.
Slowing in occipital areas of the scalp EEG.

value_en: Functional abnormality of the middle ear
description_en: An abnormality of the function of the middle ear.,The middle ear comprises the tympanic cavity in the temporal bone of the skull behind the eardrum, and is separated from the outer ear by the ear drum. The tympanic cavity contains the auditory ossicles (malleus, incus, stapes) that vibrate when exposed to sound, forming a chain that extends to the oval window of the inner ear and whose main function is to amplify sound. Additionally, the middle ear connects to the back of the throat and nose through the Eustachian tube.
description_code: Functional abnormality of the middle ear

description_en: Head circumference below 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender at birth.
