description_en: A type of infection of the central nervous system that can be regarded as a sign of a pathological susceptibility to infection.

value_en: EEG with generalized slow activity grade 4
description_en: EEG without electrical activity.

value_en: EEG with generalized slow activity grade 3
description_en: Generalized slowing of EEG activity at frequencies between 0.5-3 Hz.

value_en: EEG with generalized slow activity grade 2
description_en: Generalized slowing of EEG activity at frequencies between 4-7 Hz.
Clonus is an involuntary tendon reflex that causes repeated flexion and extension of the foot. Knee clonus can be tested by rapidly pushing the patella towards the toes.

value_en: EEG with generalized slow activity grade 1
description_en: Slowing at frequencies between 7.5 and 8.5 Hz.

Clonus is an involuntary tendon reflex that causes repeated flexion and extension of the foot. Ankle clonus is tested by rapidly flexing the foot upward.,Ankle clonus is generally caused by corticospinal disease.
Non-continuous diffuse slowing of electroencephalographic patterns.
Hyposegmented (hypolobulated) or bilobed neutrophil nuclei.,Hyposegmented cells are neutrophils with fewer than three nuclear lobes.
description_code: Hyposegmentation of neutrophil nuclei in peripheral blood,Pelger-Huet anomaly

description_en: EEG showing diffuse slowing without interruption.
Cognitive, psychiatric or memory anomaly.
EEG with abnormally slow frequencies.
A type of cerebral palsy characterized by slow, involuntary muscle movement and mixed muscle tone.,Athetoid cerebral palsy is caused by damage to the basal ganglia.
EEG frequency is abnormally increased.

A type of rigidity in which the arms are in flexion and adduction and the legs are extended. This signifies a lesion in the cerebral white matter, internal capsules, or thalamus.,Decorticate posturing
EEG with abnormal amplitude.

value_en: EEG with generalized polymorphic epileptiform discharges
description_en: Generalized epileptiform discharges of different shapes and frequencies.
An anomaly of the control or production of movement in the central nervous system.

An abnormality of the medulla oblongata, the lower half of the brainstem.,The medulla oblongata, which is often referred to simply as the medulla, comprises the medullary reticular formation, inferior olivary complex and cochlear nuclear complex, among other structures.
Rhabdomyolysis induced by intake of alcohol.
Rhabdomyolysis induced by anesthesia.

A medical history of exposure of the mother of a child or fetus to a teratogenic substance during pregnancy.,Commonly encountered maternal teratogens include alcohol, antiepileptic drugs, antihypertensive and antithyroid medications, aspirin, bisphosphonates, chemotherapy, monoclonal antibodies, ionizing radiation, recreational drugs, and serotonin-specific reuptake inhibitors (a class of antidepressants).

A medical history of a fetus or child born to a mother with an autoimmune disease.,Maternal autoimmune diseases with potential adverse effects for the fetus include autoimmune forms of hyperthyroidism and hypothyroidism, myasthenia gravis, systemic lupus erythematodes, and autoimmune forms of thrombocytopenia.
An abnormally elevated or decreased level of a maternal serum marker analytes used in screening for aneuploidy.

An abnormally low concentration of serum PAPP-A (pregnancy associated plasma protein A), as compared to normal values for gestational-age.,Reduced levels of alpha-fetoprotein can be seen in some fetal disorders such as Down syndrome.

An abnormally low concentration of maternal serum human chorionic gonadotropin as compared to normal values for gestational-age.,Reduced levels of alpha-fetoprotein can be seen in some fetal disorders such as Down syndrome.

An abnormally high concentration of maternal serum human chorionic gonadotropin as compared to normal values for gestational-age.,Reduced levels of alpha-fetoprotein can be seen in some fetal disorders such as Down syndrome.

An abnormally high concentration of serum alpha-fetoprotein as compared to normal values for gestational-age.,Reduced levels of alpha-fetoprotein can be seen in some fetal disorders such as Down syndrome.

Fifth finger clinodactyly is defined by a hypoplastic or absent mid-phalanx of the fifth digit. Ultrasound identification of the fetal hand must first be undertaken and then appropriate magnification accomplished. The evaluation requires stretching of the 5 fingers. The diagnosis is established when the middle phalanx of the fifth finger is markedly smaller than normal or absent, which often causes the finger to be curved inward (pmid:16100637).
description_code: Fetal little finger curvature,Fetal pinky finger curvature,Fetal pinkie finger curvature

description_en: On prenatal ultrasound, the nasal bone is a thin echogenic line within the bridge of the fetal nose. The fetus is imaged facing the transducer with the fetal face strictly in the midline. The angle of insonation is 90 degrees, with the longitudinal axis of the nasal bone as the reference line. Calibres are placed at each end of the nasal bone. Absence of the nasal bone or measurements below 2.5th percentile are considered significant (pmid:16100637).

A short humerus length is defined as a length below the 2.5th percentile for gestational age or as a measurement less than 0.9 of that predicted by the measured biparietal diameter. The humerus should be measured with the bone perpendicular to the ultrasound beam and with epiphyseal cartilages visible but not included in the measurement (pmid:16100637).
description_code: Short fetal long bone in upper arm length

description_en: A short femur length is defined as either a measurement below the 2.5th percentile for gestational age or a measurement that is less than 0.9 of that predicted by the measured biparietal diameter. The femur should be measured with the bone perpendicular to the ultrasound beam and with epiphyseal cartilages visible but not included in the measurement (pmid:16100637).

The cisterna magna is measured on a transaxial view of the fetal head angled 15 degrees caudal to the canthomeatal line. The anterior/posterior diameter is taken between the inferior/posterior surface of the vemis of the cerebellum to the inner surface of the cranium. An enlarged cisternal magna is defined by an anterior/posterior diameter of 10 mm or more (pmid:16100637).

Fetal choroid plexus cysts (CPCs) are sonographically discrete, small cysts found in the choroid plexus within the lateral cerebral ventricles of the developing fetus at 14 to 24 weeks gestation. Imaging of the choroid plexus is performed in the transverse plane of the fetal head at the same level that the lateral cerebral ventricle is evaluated. The choroid plexus should be inspected bilaterally for the presence of cysts. The size of CPCs is not of clinical relevance (pmid:16100637).,There is agreement that ultrasound characteristics of CPC, such as bilaterality, size, number, complexity, and resolution, are not related to the risk of aneuploidy. However, cysts with diameters less than 5 mm may not be linked with trisomy and large cysts in excess of 10 mm may impart a higher risk.

An finding upon obstetric ultrasound examination performed at around 16 to 20 weeks of gestation that is abnormal but not clearly identifiable as a fetal anatomic malformation or growth restriction. Such findings are known as soft markers since they are associated with increased risk for fetal aneuploidy or other disorders.,The screening ultrasound at 16 to 20 weeks should evaluate 8 markers, 5 of which (thickened nuchal fold, echogenic bowel, mild ventriculomegaly, echogenic focus in the heart, and choroid plexus cyst) are associated with an increased risk of fetal aneuploidy, and in some cases with nonchromosomal problems, while 3 (single umbilical artery, enlarged cisterna magna, and pyelectasis) are only associated with an increased risk of nonchromosomal abnormalities when seen in isolation (pmid:16100637).
An increased consentration of zinc in the blood.
An abnormally increased chloride concentration in the blood.
An abnormality of chloride homeostasis or concentration in the body.
description_code: Abnormal blood Cl concentration,Abnormality of chloride homeostasis,Abnormal blood Cl- concentration

description_en: Death during adolescence, the period between childhood and adulthood (roughly between the ages of 10 and 19 years).
The age group when the cessation of life happens.

value_en: Anomalous origin of one pulmonary artery from ascending aorta
description_en: Anomalous origin of one pulmonary artery from the ascending aorta with the contralateral pulmonary artery arising from the right ventricle.,Origin of a pulmonary artery from the aorta is also known as hemitruncus. One pulmonary artery branch, usually the right, arises from the ascending aorta just above the aortic sinuses, while the main pulmonary artery and the other pulmonary branch arise in their normal position from the right ventricle.
Separation of the placenta from the uterus wall before delivery.
Increased length of the umbilical cord.

value_en: Tetralogy of Fallot with absent pulmonary valve
description_en: Features of tetralogy of Fallot with either rudimentary ridges or the complete absence of pulmonic valve tissue.
description_code: Tetralogy of Fallot with absent pulmonary valve syndrome

value_en: Double outlet right ventricle with subpulmonary ventricular septal defect without pulmonary stenosis
description_en: A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the pulmonary origin. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
description_code: DORV with subpulmonary VSD without pulmonary stenosis,Taussig-Bing anomaly

value_en: Double outlet right ventricle with subpulmonary ventricular septal defect and pulmonary stenosis
description_en: A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the pulmonary origin. There is associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
description_code: DORV with subpulmonary VSD and pulmonary stenosis

description_en: An abnormality of the placenta in which there are numerous cystic spaces within the placenta as well as placental enlargement.

value_en: Double outlet right ventricle with subaortic ventricular septal defect without pulmonary stenosis
description_en: A double outlet right ventricle with a ventricular spetal defect (a hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart), that is considered to be closely related to the aortic origin. There is not associated pulmonary stenosis, the abnormal narrowing or constriction of the pulmonary artery, in the main pulmonary artery and/or in the left or right pulmonary artery branches.
description_code: DORV with subaortic VSD without pulmonary stenosis

description_en: Reduction in the anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.
Reduced transparency of the central portion of the corneal stroma.
Double rather than single peak of the antitragus.
An abnormality of the stroma of cornea, also known as the substantia propria of cornea.

value_en: Reduced number of corneal endothelial cells
description_en: A reduction in the number of corneal endothelial cells.
Abnormality of Descemet's membrane, which is the basement membrane of the corneal endothelium.
An abnormality in a cellular process.

value_en: Expanded terminal portion of crus of helix
description_en: Widening, rather than tapering, of the crus at its posterior border near the antihelix.
An abnormality of the concentration of glucose in the urine.

value_en: Tragal bridge of crus of helix
description_en: The anterior origin of the crus encompasses the superior margin of the tragus, the crus overrides the upper portion of the conchal cavum and ends at the antihelix.
An abnormality of the concentration of glucose in the blood.
Curving course of the crus of the helix, approaching or joining the antitragus.
Abnormal dilatation of the iris.
Abnormality of glucose homeostasis.,An abnormality of any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of glucose within an organism or cell.

value_en: Crus of helix connected to antihelix
description_en: Extension of the ridge of the crus helix across the ear and connection of the crus to the antihelix.

A deviation from the normal concentration of a carbohydrate in the blood circulation.,An abnormality of the metabolism (include abnormality of the concentration) of a carbohydrate, including monosaccharides, oligosaccharides and polysaccharides, and substances derived from them.
Continuum between the tragus and ascending helix, without any evidence of a posterior extension (crus) towards the concha.
New growth of vessels on the surface of the iris.
description_code: New blood vessel formation in iris

description_en: A deviation from the normal concentration of a polysaccharide in the blood circulation.
A type of cryptotia associated with reduction in size of the antihelix and inferior crus that are affected.

Ingrowth of new blood vessels into the cornea.,New blood vessels, which sprout from the capillaries and venules of the pericorneal plexus, may block light, compromise visual acuity, and lead to inflammation, corneal scarring, and edema. Corneal neovascularization may be a consequence of corneal hypoxia. Neovascular patterns can be separated into three clinical groups: deep neovascularization overlying Descemet's membrane (seen in herpetic and luetic interstitial keratitis), stromal neovascularization (as a result of stromal keratitis), and vascular pannus (from ocular surface disorders).
description_code: Corneal neovascularisation,New blood vessel formation in cornea,Corneal vascularization,Limbal neovascularization

description_en: Somewhat rapid onset and change of disease manifestations.,Subacute is between acute and chronic.
A type of cryptotia associated with reduction in size of the antihelix and superior crus.
Abnormality of the corneal epithelium, that is of the epithelial tissue that covers the front of the cornea.
Slow, creeping onset, slow progress and long continuance of disease manifestations.,According to the U.S. National Center for Health Statistics, a chronic condition is one lasting 3 months or more.
Generalized reduced transparency of the stroma of the cornea.

Sudden appearance of disease manifestations over a short period of time.,The word acute is applied to different time scales depending on the disease or manifestation and does not have an exact definition in minutes, hours, or days.
The speed at which disease manifestations appear and develop.
Absence of the anterosuperior prominence of the area between the bottom of the incisura and the inner margin of the antihelix.,The size of the antitragus is highly variable.

Increased protrusion of the antihelical ridge, proximal to its bifurcation, relative to the prominence of the helix.,This finding is highly variable. The relative prominence is attributable to either increased volume of the cartilage and/or the acuteness of the folding angle. Interpretation of relative antihelical prominence may be difficult when the conchal anatomy is distorted, for example, with a cupped ear.
Abnormality of the lacrimal gland, i.e., of the almond-shaped gland that secretes the aqueous layer of the tear film for each eye.
An abnormality of the lacrimal duct, a duct that drain tears from the conjunctiva, via the lacrimal puncta, into the lacrimal sac.
description_code: Abnormality of the lacrimal duct,Abnormality of the lacrimal canaliculus

description_en: A developmental anomaly characterized by abnormal smallness of one eye.
description_code: Abnormally small eyeball on one side,Unilateral nanophthalmos

value_en: Abnormality of the musculature of the neck
description_en: An abnormality of the neck musculature.
description_code: Neck muscle issue,Abnormality of cervical musculature,Abnormality of the musculature of the neck

description_en: Positioning of the antitragus at an angle perpendicular to the plane of the ear (oriented away from the plane of the ear).
A type of cirrhosis characterized by the presence of regenerative nodules of a variety of sizes.,In mixed cirrhosis, there are regenerating nodules under and over 3 mm in size.

Increased protrusion of the superior crus relative to the prominence of a normal antihelix stem.,This finding is highly variable. There may be an inverse relationship between the relative sizes of the superior and inferior crura, but these findings should be coded separately.
description_code: Hypertrophic superior crus of antihelix,Hyperplastic superior crus of antihelix

description_en: Abnormality of the corneal endothelium, that is, the single layer of cells on the inner surface of the cornea.
A severe form of myopia with greater than -6.00 diopters.
description_code: Severe near sightedness,Severe myopia (> -6.00 diopters),Severely close sighted,Severely near sighted,Severe myopia

value_en: Abnormality of superior crus of antihelix
description_en: An abnormality of the superior crus of the antihelix is the upper cartilaginous ridge arising at the bifurcation of the antihelix that ends beneath the fold of the ascending helix, and separates the concha from the triangular fossa.,The inferior antihelical crus runs in an anterior and slightly superior direction, and is usually sharply defined, and appears less variable than its superior counterpart. A synonym is anterior crus of the antihelix.
description_code: Abnormality of posterior crus of antihelix

description_en: A increased anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.
Abnormally increased formation of dense trabecular bone tissue. Despite the increased density of bone tissue, osteopetrotic bones tend to be more fracture-prone than normal.
description_code: Harder, denser, fracture-prone bones,Albers-Sch√∂nberg disease,Albers-Schoenberg disease,Marble bone disease,Albers-Schonberg disease

description_en: An abnormality of the stem of the antihelix, which is the part below the bifurcation of the antihelix into the inferior and superior crura.
An abnormal anteroposterior thickness of the cornea.

An abnormal increase of bone mineral density, that is, of the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones which is often referred to as osteosclerosis. Osteosclerosis can be detected on radiological examination as an increased whiteness (density) of affected bones.,This term may be merged with Increased bone density in the future or made obsolete.
description_code: Increased bone mineral density,Osteosclerosis of bones,Increased bone density,Osteosclerosis

value_en: Abnormality of inferior crus of antihelix
description_en: An abnormality of the inferior crus of the antihelix is the lower cartilaginous ridge arising at the bifurcation of the antihelix that ends beneath the fold of the ascending helix, and separates the concha from the triangular fossa.,The inferior antihelical crus runs in an anterior and slightly superior direction, and is usually sharply defined, and appears less variable than its superior counterpart. A synonym is anterior crus of the antihelix.
description_code: Abnormality of anterior crus of antihelix

description_en: Developmental abnormality in which the lens and cornea are not separated.

Decreased protrusion of the antihelical ridge, proximal to its bifurcation, relative to the prominence of a normal helix.,The degree of prominence of the stem is highly variable and is attributable to the volume of the cartilage and/or the acuteness of the folding angle. Interpretation of degree of antihelical prominence may be difficult when the conchal anatomy is distorted, e.g., in cupped ear.

value_en: Posterior synechiae of the anterior chamber
description_en: Adhesions between the iris and the lens.
Posterior curving of the antihelix from its origin at the antitragus, traveling initially almost perpendicular to the descending helix and obscuring some of the concha.

value_en: Anterior synechiae of the anterior chamber
description_en: Adhesions between the iris and the cornea.
Decreased protrusion of the inferior crus relative to the prominence of the antihelix stem.,This finding is highly variable.
description_code: Hypoplastic inferior crus of antihelix,Antihelix, inferior crus, underdeveloped,Hypotrophic inferior crus of antihelix

description_en: Increased protrusion of the inferior crus relative to the prominence of the antihelix stem.
description_code: Antihelix, inferior crus, prominent,Hyperplastic inferior crus of antihelix,Hypertrophic inferior crus of antihelix

description_en: Feeding problem necessitating gastrostomy tube feeding.,This is an extremely severe form of feeding problems in infancy.
Feeding problem necessitating nasogastric tube feeding.,This is a severe form of feeding problems in infancy.
Increased width of the inferred cross-section of the inferior crus.,This finding is highly variable. The inferior crus is usually sharply folded giving a narrow profile.
An abnormality of the lacrimal punctum, an opening on the eyelid close to the medial canthus that drains tears from the conjunctival sac into the lacrimal duct in the same eyelid.
Antihelical ridge that forms an acute angle between the antitragus and its bifurcation (stem) instead of a gently curving arc.
Absence of globe, optic nerve, chiasm and optic tracts. No evidence of ocular tissue on MRI scan or examination.,True anophthalmia implies an early failure of eye development.

Supernumerary ridge or crus of the ear arising from the antihelix.,The supernumerary crus usually emanates posteriorly from the antihelix at, or just above, the point of its bifurcation but may have a different origin. In the former case, the finding is termed Stahl ear.

In primary position, the eyes drift slowly downward and then spontaneously beat upward. Upward gaze accentuates the nystagmus. The associated oscillopsias are often very irritating, but the symptoms are usually transient.,In most cases, paramedian lesions in the medulla oblongata or the midbrain are found, for example, in patients with multiple sclerosis, brainstem ischemia or tumors, or Wernicke's encephalopathy.

No discernible ridge between concha and triangular fossa and helix.,This finding is common in a protruding and cupped ear, where the superior and inferior parts of the antihelix are often absent. This is distinct from partial absence of the antihelix as may occur in, for example, underdeveloped inferior crus of the antihelix.
Complete loss of hearing related to a sensorineural defect.

Antihelix protrusion directed more anteriorly than laterally, forming a shelf overlying the posterior concha.,In marked cases this often appears to be associated with lack of lateral protrusion of the antihelix.
Persistence of the stapedial artery, which normally regresses during embryonic life.
Elevated ridge(s) of skin starting well below the medial aspect of the lower lid that curves gradually upward toward and/or across the nasal bridge.,This term excludes epicanthus inversus.
Sensorineural hearing impairment with childhood onset.
Eyelashes that draw the attention of the viewer due to increased density and/or length and/or curl without meeting the criteria of trichomegaly.
The enteric villi are atrophic or absent.
description_code: Villous degeneration,Atrophy of small intestinal villi,Variable degree of villous atrophy,Biopsy shows villous atrophy,Duodenal villous atrophy,Small intestine biopsy shows villous atrophy

Regurgitation of milk through the nose.
Onset of disease at up to 8 weeks of gestation.
Absence or underdevelopment of the eyelid.

Nevertheless, as it is difficult or impossible to make this distinction on clinical grounds, the term was felt to be useful.

description_code: Concave glabella,Flat area between the eyebrows,Flat glabella,Deficiency of glabella,Deficient area between the eyebrows,Hypoplasia of glabella

description_en: Onset of disease at the age of between 1 and 5 years.,This term refers to ages up to but not including the fifth birthday (see Juvenile onset).

Onset prior to birth but after 8 weeks of gestation.

Persistence of blood flow through the ductus venosus for longer than the normal time after birth.,The ductus venosus is a bypass between the umbilical vein and the inferior vena cava in the fetus. The blood flow through this bypass decreases immediately after birth. Functional closure, which is followed by anatomic closure, is virtually complete within a few weeks of birth.

Aorta descends on right instead of on the left.,The are several types of right aortic arch (RAA). RAA can recognized radiographically by leftward displacement of barium-filled esophagus or of an air-filled trachea. The aortic knob is absent from left side, and the para-aortic stripe returns to left side of spine just above diaphragm.

Any anomaly of the normal motility of motile cilia. Evaluation of ciliary beat frequency and ciliary beat pattern requires high-speed videomicroscopy of freshly obtained ciliary biopsies that are maintained in culture media under controlled conditions.,Ciliated epithelial cells bear approximately 200 motile (9 + 2) cilia that move with both intracellular and intercellular synchrony. The pattern of beat in 9 + 2 motile cilia occurs in a waveform having a forward effective stroke followed by a return stroke. The direction of stroke is a function of the directional orientation of the central microtubules. In addition to moving in synchrony, individual cilia in normal cells are very plastic and move fluidly, sometimes deforming briefly upon encountering resistance and/or particles being transported over the mucosal surface. Cilia are embedded in a watery periciliary fluid of low viscosity, which facilitates the rapid beat cycle to move the more viscous overlying layer of mucus. Ciliary beat frequency ranges from approximately 8-20 Hz under normal conditions but may be accelerated by exposure to irritants such as tobacco smoke.
Any functional anomaly of the respiratory motile cilia.,Abnormal respiratory motile cilium physiology may include alterations in ciliary beating pattern or frequency.

value_en: Abnormal central microtubular pair morphology of respiratory motile cilia
description_en: A structural anomaly of the two central microtubules of motile cilia with a 9+2 microtubuluar configuration.,The central microtubular pair is referred to as the central part of axoneme of cilium.
An abnormal concentration of a hormone in the urine.
A benign tumor of the liver of presumably epithelial origin.
An abnormal accumulation of fluid and swelling in the tissues of the larynx.
Any anomaly in the amount of glycogen in muscle tissue.,Glycogen functions as a secondary short term energy storage in muscle.
Increased concentration of ornithine in the blood.
A liposarcoma that contains myxomatous tissue.

Deviation from the normal concentration of ornithine in the blood circulation.,Ornithine is an amino acid produced in the urea cycle by the splitting off of urea from arginine. Ornithine is a naturally occurring, non-proteinogenic amino acid found in meat, fish, dairy and eggs.

value_en: Absent respiratory ciliary axoneme radial spokes
description_en: Absence of the radial spokes of the axoneme of the respiratory cilium.

Elevated concentration of galactose in the blood.,Hypergalactosemia is used here to mean the increased concentration of galactose in the blood. Note that the word galactosemia is occasionally used with the same meaning but more commonly denotes the disease entity called galactosemia caused by mutations in the galactose-1-phosphate uridyltransferase gene (MIM:230400).
A periodic beat-to-beat variation in the amplitude or shape of the T wave in an EKG.
Elevated concentration of galactose in the urine.

A deviation from the normally well coordinated pattern of intracellular and intercellular synchrony of motile cilia. Dyskinetic cilia usually beat out of synchrony relative to neighboring cilia.,Typically, but not always, dyskinesia is characterized by markedly attenuated ciliary beat frequency.

A congenital defect of the vasculature such that there is a shunt (by-pass) of blood directly from the portal vein to the vena cava (i.e., the blood from the portal vein is not filtered through the liver).

value_en: Absent central microtubular pair morphology of respiratory motile cilia
description_en: Absence of the two central microtubules of motile cilia with a 9+2 microtubuluar configuration.
Complete dislocation of the lens of the eye.

value_en: EEG with frontal focal spike waves
description_en: EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the frontal region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.
A structural anomaly of the respiratory system.
Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of the anterior cerebral artery.

An electrocardiographic anomaly in which the ST segment is observed to be located superior to the isoelectric line.,ST segment elevation may have multiple causes including myocardial infaction, left ventricular aneurysm, and hyperkalemia.
Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of the middle cerebral artery.
An electrocardiographic anomaly in which the ST segment is observed to be located inferior to the isoelectric line.
Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of a cerebral artery.

An anomaly of the intracellular membrane complexes known as the dense tubular system.,The dense tubular system (DTS) functions to regulate platelet activation by sequestering or releasing calcium, similar to the sarcotubules of skeletal muscle. In resting platelets, the DTS exists as thin elongated membranes. Within 10 seconds of the addition of thrombin, platelets show a major ultrastructural change in their DTS: from the thin elongated form to a rounded vesicular form.
Inflammation of adipose tissue.,Panniculitis most commonly affects the skin and characterized by reddened subcutaneous nodules.
description_code: Inflammation of fat tissue,Inflammation of adipose tissue

description_en: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the temporal region.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the parietal region.

value_en: Absent inner and outer dynein arms
description_en: Complete absence of the dynein arms of respiratory motile cilia, that is, absence of the inner and the outer dynein arms, which normally are situated inside and outside of the peripheral microtubules of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the occipital region.

value_en: Abnormal axonemal organization of respiratory motile cilia
description_en: Abnormal arrangement of the structures of the axoneme, which is the cytoskeletal structure that forms the inner core of the motile cilium and displays a canonical 9 + 2 microtubular pattern of motile cilia studded with dynein arms.,Abnormal axonemal organization comprises anomalies such as an eccentric central pair of microtubuli, abnormal radial spokes and nexin links, reduced number of inner dynein arms, and displacement of the outer doublet.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the frontal region.

Absence of the outer dynein arms of respiratory motile cilia, which normally are situated within the peripheral microtubules of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.

A separation of the layers within the wall of the descending aorta. Tears in the intimal layer result in the propagation of dissection (proximally or distally) secondary to blood entering the intima-media space.,According to the Stanford classification, type B aortic dissection begins beyond brachiocephalic vessels (begins distal to the left subclavian artery).
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the central region.

Absence of the outer dynein arms of respiratory motile cilia, which normally are situated outside of the peripheral microtubules of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.
A complication of pregnancy and delivery in which the umbilical cord wraps around the fetal neck once or multiple times.

value_en: EEG with temporal focal spike waves
description_en: EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the temporal region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

value_en: Dynein arm defect of respiratory motile cilia
description_en: An anomaly of the dynein arms of motile cilia. This feature is usually appreciated by electron microscopy.,The peripheral microtubules in the canonical 9 + 2 microtubular pattern of motile cilia are studded with dynein arms that contain adenosine triphosphatases and act as molecular motors to effect the sliding of the peripheral microtubular pairs relative to one another.
A decrease in the maximum amount of pressure of expired air achieved by a person after a full inspiration.

value_en: EEG with parietal focal spike waves
description_en: EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the parietal region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

A malignant tumor of the bone which always arises in the medullary tissue, occurring more often in cylindrical bones.,Histologically, Ewing's sarcoma is composed of a homogeneous population of small round cells with high nuclear to cytoplasmic ratios that are arrayed in sheets. There is scant cytoplasms, which is pale, vacuolated and characterized by faded boundaries. In contrast, the nuclei are clearly visualized by their intense color. Mitotic activity is typically low.
A decrease in the maximum amount of negative pressure a person can generate during an inhalation.

value_en: EEG with occipital focal spike waves
description_en: EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the occipital region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.
Any structural anomaly of the pseudostratified ciliated epithelium that lines much of the conducting portion of the airway, including part of the nasal cavity and larynx, the trachea, and bronchi.
Narrowing or constriction of the inner surface (lumen) of the posterior cerebral artery.

value_en: EEG with central focal spike waves
description_en: EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the central region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

Auras with an alteration of actual percepts involving the visual, auditory, somatosensory, olfactory or gustatory systems.,See the Glossary of Descriptive Terminology for Ictal Semiology at http://www.ilae.org.
Atrophy of the levator palpebrae superioris, the extraocular muscle that elevates the superior eyelid.

Defective structure, size or content of alpha granules, platelet organelles that contain several growth factors destined for release during platelet activation at sites of vessel wall injury.,This feature can be observed by electron microscopy. Alpha granules normally contain a number of proteins including von Willebrand factor, and fibrinogen.

An abnormal increase in intracellular lipid droplets In a muscle. The number and size of these drops can increase with somd disorders of lipid metabolism affecting muscle. See pmid 20691590 for histological images.,In normal muscle cells, lipid content takes the aspect of small droplets which concentration and size are usually higher in type 1 fibres than in type 2 fibres.
A venous angioma of the frontal lobe of the brain.

A congenital malformation of veins which drain normal brain characterized by a caput medusae or an umbrellalike convergence of multiple venules on a single, or occasionally multiple, enlarged parenchymal or medullary vein, like the trunk of a tree or the shank of an umbrella. This dilated terminal vein penetrates the cortex to drain either (a) superficially to cortical veins or sinuses, (b) deeply to subependymal veins of the lateral ventricle and then into the galenic system, (c) to the fourth ventricle and then to the pontomesencephalic vein, or (d) to the precentral cerebellar vein and into the galenic system.,DVA is characterized by a caput medusae or an umbrellalike convergence of multiple venules on a single, or occasionally multiple, enlarged parenchymal or medullary vein, like the trunk of a tree or the shank of an umbrella. This dilated terminal vein penetrates the cortex to drain either (a) superficially to cortical veins or sinuses, (b) deeply to subependymal veins of the lateral ventricle and then into the galenic system, (c) to the fourth ventricle and then to the pontomesencephalic vein, or (d) to the precentral cerebellar vein and into the galenic system.
An anomaly of cerebral veins.

Auras with creation of composite perceptions without corresponding external stimuli involving visual, auditory, somatosensory, olfactory and/or gustatory phenomena.,See the Glossary of Descriptive Terminology for Ictal Semiology at http://www.ilae.org.

An electrocardiographic anomaly of the ST segment, which is the segment that connects the QRS complex and the T wave. The ST segment normally has a duration of 80 to 120 ms, is flat and at the same level (isoelectric) as the PR and TP segment.
A subjective feeling that an experience which has occurred before is being experienced for the first time.
Increased time for the PR interval (beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the QRS complex).,In adults, normal values are 120 to 200 ms long.
description_code: Electrocardiographic long PR interval,Lengthened PR interval on EKG

description_en: A subjective feeling that an experience which is occurring for the first time has been experienced before.
Anosmia for one particular odor.

An arachnoid cyst that progressively enlarges from an abnormality in the membrane of Liliequist or in the interpeduncular cistern, and typically, expands from the prepontine space, displacing the floor of the third ventricle upwards, the pituitary stalk and optic chiasm upwards and forwards, and the mammillary bodies upwards and backwards.,As the cyst increases in size it fills and occludes the third ventricle, and distorts and blocks the aqueduct, which finally results in hydrocephalus.
Auras which reflect ictal dysmnesia such as: feelings as familiarity (deja-vu) and unfamiliarity (jamais-vu).,See the Glossary of Descriptive Terminology for Ictal Semiology at http://www.ilae.org.
Reduced ability to control the movement of the eye associated with damage to the third cranial nerve (the oculomotor nerve).
An arachnoid cyst located within the ventricular system.,Arachnoid cysts very rarely occur within the ventricular system, where no arachnoid tissue exists.

Affective auras with subjective qualities similar to those experienced in life but are recognized by the subject as occurring outside of actual context.,See the Glossary of Descriptive Terminology for Ictal Semiology at http://www.ilae.org.

Development of the reproductive system is inconsistent with the chromosomal sex.,Sex reversal is present if an XX individual develops phenotypically as a male or if an XY individual develops as a female.
An arachnoid cyst located at the margin of the cerebellum and pons.

Affective, mnemonic or composite perceptual auras with subjective qualities similar to those experienced in life but are recognized by the subject as occurring outside of actual context.,See the Glossary of Descriptive Terminology for Ictal Semiology at http://www.ilae.org.
Anomaly of primary or secondary sexual development or characteristics.
Inflammation of the spinal cord.
EEG with repetitive generalized sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec.
A structural or developmental anomaly of any of the tissues involved in the genital system.

An anomaly of the invaginations of the surface membrane that form the open canalicular system (OCS). The OCS serve as the pathway for transport of substances into the cells and as conduits for the discharge of alpha granule products secreted during the platelet release reaction.
EEG with generalized sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec.
Atrophy of the superior rectus, the extraocular muscle whose primary function is to elevate the globe.

Defective structure, size or content of dense granules, platelet organelles that contain granules proaggregatory factors such as adenosine diphosphate (ADP), adenosine triphosphate (ATP), ionized calcium , histamine and serotonin.,This feature can be observed by electron microscopy.
Absence of transferrin, a protein that transports iron, in the blood.

A type of retinal detachment associated with a retinal tear, that is, with a break in the retina that allows fluid to pass from the vitreous space into the subretinal space between the sensory retina and the retinal pigment epithelium.
A turning outward of the lip or lips, that is, eversion of the lips.
Increased width of the skin of vermilion border region of upper lip.
description_code: Thick lips,Prominent lips,Plump lips,Full lips,Increased volume of lip,Increased volume of lip vermillion

description_en: An ophthalmologic sign in young children resulting from upward-gaze paresis. In this condition, the eyes appear driven downward, the sclera may be seen between the upper eyelid and the iris, and part of the lower pupil may be covered by the lower eyelid.,Setting-sun eye phenomenon can also be transiently elicited in healthy infants up to 7 months of age by changes of position or removal of light (benign setting-sun phenomenon). When persistent, this sign is one of the most frequent markers of elevated intracranial pressure.
description_code: Sunsetting eye,Setting-sun eye phenomenon,Sun setting eyes,Eyes fixed downward

description_en: Increased plasma concentrations of chylomicrons, the large lipid droplet (up to 100 mm in diameter) of reprocessed lipid synthesized in epithelial cells of the small intestine and containing triacylglycerols, cholesterol esters, and several apolipoproteins.
An increased concentration of urocanic acid in the urine.
Noises from the temporomandibular joint during mandibular movement (e.g., chewing). Temporomandibular joint crepitus is often described as a clicking, popping, grating sound.
description_code: Temporomandibular joint noise,Temporomandibular joint sounds,Jaw joint sounds,Jaw joint noise,Jaw joint crepitus,Temporomandibular joint popping sound,Jaw joint popping sound,Temporomandibular joint grating sound,Temporomandibular joint clicking sound,Jaw joint grating sound,Jaw joint clicking sound

description_en: An increased concentration of chloride in the sweat.,Sweat chloride is notably increased in cystic fibrosis, but also in some other diseases.
description_code: Elevated sweat Cl,Elevated sweat chloride,Elevated sweat Cl-

description_en: Bony fusion of the mandibular condyle to the base of the skull, resulting in limitation of jaw opening.
description_code: Ankylosis of temporomandibular joint,Rigidity of the temporomandibular joint,Temporomandibular joint fusion,Freezing of jaw joint,Freezing of the temporomandibular joint,Adhesion of the temporomandibular joint

description_en: A type of agranulocytosis related to ingestion of a specific medication.

A wavering, unsteady voice that reflects involuntary and approximately sinusoidal oscillation of motor unit firings of laryngeal muscles. Vocal tremor results in low frequency modulations of voice frequency or amplitude and intermittent voice instability.
Marked decrease in the number of granulocytes.,Agranulocytosis is defined as an absolute neutrophil count less than 500 cells/microliter.
The presence of normal overall immunoglobulin levels with deficiency of specific immunoglobulins directed against pneumococci.
Blood clot formed within muscle tissue following leakage of blood into the tissue.

value_en: Decreased circulating level of specific antibody
description_en: The presence of normal overall immunoglobulin levels with deficiency of specific immunoglobulins directed against a specific antigen or microorganism.
description_code: Decreased specific antibody in blood,Specific antibody deficiency

description_en: Decreased time between the start of the Q wave and the end of the T wave as measured by the electrocardiogram (EKG).
Complete obstruction of a carotid artery.,Carotid artery occlusion is usually caused by caused by atherosclerosis.

A type of retinal detachment arising from damage to the outer blood-retinal barrier that allows fluid to access the subretinal space and separate the neurosensory retina from the retinal pigment epithelium.
Wasting of the tongue.
description_code: Atrophy of the tongue,Lingual atrophy,Wasting of the tongue,Lingual wasting

description_en: An increased white blood cell count in the cerebrospinal fluid.
description_code: Increased leukocyte count in CSF,Cerebrospinal fluid pleocytosis

description_en: A type of headache that last hours with continuous pain of mild or moderate intensity, bilateral location, a pressing/tightening (non-pulsating) quality and that is not aggravated by routine physical activity such as walking or climbing stairs.
Presence of multiple cystic changes in multiple areas or multiple bones.
A benign fluid filled simple cyst of bone filled with serous fluid.
Radiographic features include a dilated, radiolucent lesion typically located eccentrically within the metaphyseal portion of the bone, with fluid levels visible on magnetic resonance imaging.
A fluid filled cavity that develops with a bone.,Many bone cysts are asymptomatic. However, larger cysts can make the bone more susceptible to fracture.
Excretion of oligosaccharides conjugated to sialic acid in the urine.

A type of cutaneous melanoma localized to the palm, sole, or beneath the nail (subungual melanoma). Acral lentiginous melanoma starts as a slowly-enlarging flat patch of discoloured skin and usually displays a size above 6 mm and often several centimetres or more in diameter upon diagnosis and variable pigmentation with a mixutre of colors including brown, and blue-grey, black and red. The surface of the lesion is initially smooth but later in the course may become thicker and irregular, and may ulcerate or bleed.
An increased concentration of keratan sulfate in the urine.,Keratan sulfate is a a glycosaminoglycan.
Excretion of excess amounts of aspartylglucosamine in the urine.

Increased excretion of glycopeptides in the urine. Glycopeptides are peptides with carbohydrate moieties covalently attached to the side chains of the amino acid residues.,This feature is often the result of a defect in glycosidase activate. Glycosidases catalyze the release of sugar moieties.
Increased concentration of disaccharide in the urine.,Excess amount of disaccharides such as mannosyl-N-acetylglucosamine excreted in the urine.

Malignant tumor of melanocytes of the choroid. The classic appearance of choroidal melanoma is a pigmented dome-shaped or collar button-shaped tumor with an associated exudative retinal detachment. Choroidal melanoma is usually pigmented, but can be variably pigmented and even amelanotic (non-pigmented).
Reduced diameter of the distal phalanx of finger.
A reduced concentration of calcifediol in the blood. Calcifediol is also known as calcidiol, 25-hydroxycholecalciferol and 25-Hydroxyvitamin D3.
Reduced diameter of the middle phalanx of finger.
A reduced concentration of calcitriol in the blood. Calcitriol is also known as 1,25-dihydroxycholecalciferol or 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3.
Abnormality of the occipital bone of the skull.
Hypoglycermia following a meal (or more generally, after intake of glucose).,Reactive hypoglycemia may be the result of an exaggerated insulin response.
description_code: Low blood sugar after a meal,Postprandial hypoglycemia

description_en: An abnormal pigmentation pattern of the external genitalia.
An extreme form of generalized edema with widespread and massive edema due to effusion of fluid into the extracellular space.
A congenital defect with an abnormal joining of the gums of the upper and lower jaw.
description_code: Partial fusion of the gums,Synechia of the gums,Fusion of gums,Fusion of the gingiva,Gingival synechia,Upper and lower gums fused together

description_en: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the mouth.

A subtype of melanoma in situ that typically develops on sun-damaged skin. The lesion is typically a large, irregularly pigmented macule that has developed from an ordinary lentigo (a small pigmented spot on the skin with a clearly-defined edge). Change to a malignant lentigo typically takes place over 20 years or more, and many patients accept the change as a consequence of aging.
A type of melanoma that starts as a raised area that is usually dark blackish-blue or bluish-red but may not have any color.
A type of melanoma that is flat and irregular in shape and color, with different shades of black and brown.
Increased length of the distal phalanx of finger.
Increased length of the middle phalanx of finger.
Malignant tumor of melanocytes of the ciliary body.
Reduced diameter of the proximal phalanx of finger.
Rhythmic, involuntary sinusoidal oscillations of one or both eyes. The waveform of pendular nystagmus may occur in any direction.
An abnormal functionality of the hypothalamus.,The hypothalamus is linked vascularly with the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland and thereby controls the secretion of pituitary hormones.
A type of asthma in which aspirin and other nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) that inhibit cyclooxygen-ase 1 (COX-1) exacerbate bronchoconstriction.
Reduced size of the proximal epiphysis of the tibia.
description_code: Small end part of innermost shinbone,Small end part of innermost shankbone

description_en: Reduced size of the Distal epiphysis of femur.
description_code: Small end part of outermost thighbone

description_en: Abnormal accumulation of fluid and swelling of the stroma of cornea.

An exanthema consisting of widespread pink-to-red macules (flat spots of 2-10 mm in diameter) or papules (red bumps) that blanch with pressure. The macules and papules may cluster and merge to form sheets over several days.,A morbilliform rash is said to resemble the rash of measles, rubella or scarlet fever, thus mimicking viral and bacterial exanthemas.
Extravasation of chyle into the peritoneal cavity.
A form of amyloidosis that affects the liver.

A form of focal dystonia that affects the vocal cords, associated with involuntary contractions of the vocal cords causing interruptions of speech and affecting the voice quality and often leading to patterned, repeated breaks in speech.
A kind of focal dystonia characterized by forceful contractions of the face, jaw, and/or tongue causing difficulty in opening and closing the mouth and often affecting chewing and speech.
A visual defect characterized by the inability to see as clearly in bright light as in dim light. The word hemeralopia literally means day blindness.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the face.
Inability to elicit tendon reflexes in the upper limbs.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the head and neck region with origin in the lip, oral cavity, nasal cavity, paranasal sinuses, pharynx, or larynx.
description_code: Head and neck tumor,Head and neck cancer

description_en: Presence of multiple yellowish-white lesions of various size and configuration on the retina not related to vascular lesions.
Decreased secretion of luteinizing hormone-releasing hormone by the hypothalamus.

Seesaw nystagmus is a type of pendular nystagmus where a half cycle consists of the elevation and intorsion of one eye, concurrently with the depression and extortion of the fellow eye. In the other half cycle, there is an inversion of the ocular movements.,Seesaw nystagmus can be a manifestation of lesions of the optic chiasma.

Any structural anomaly of the hypothalamus.,The hypothalamus is a cone-shaped cerebral structure that projects downward, ending in the pituitary (infundibular) stalk, a tubular connection to the pituitary gland. It is linked vascularly with the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland and thereby controls the secretion of pituitary hormones.
description_code: Abnormal shape of hypothalamus,Abnormality of the hypothalamus,Abnormality of hypothalamus morphology

description_en: Benign neoplasia derived from lipoblasts or lipocytes of white or brown fat. May be angiomatous or hibernomatous.

value_en: Autosomal dominant inheritance with paternal imprinting
description_en: A type of autosomal dominant inheritance involving a gene that is imprinted with paternal silencing.,Since the paternally inherited copy of such genes is silenced normally, only a maternally transmitted mutation leads to disease in this kind of inheritance.

value_en: Increased carotid artery intimal medial thickness
description_en: An increase in the combined thickness of the intima and media of the carotid artery.,This feature can be measured by ultrasonography and is thought to be a risk foctor for myocardial infarction and stroke.
Abnormally increased concentration of cortisol in the urine.

The J wave is a positive convex deflection that occurs at the junction of the QRS complex and ST segment, the J-point.,J waves can be seen in hypothermia when the core body temperature falls below 32 degrees C. Then, they occur most prominently in the inferior leads: II, III, and aVF and the precordial leads: V5-V6. J waves can also be observed in other conditions such as some forms of Brugada syndrome.
Intermittent episodes of increased resistance to the passage of air in the upper airway.
A decreased amount of glycogen in muscle tissue.

Presence of folds in the Descemet membrane, which is the basement membrane of the endothelial (inner) cell layer of the cornea. Descemet membrane folds are generally a manifestation of inflammation or edema of the cornea.

Corneal guttata are droplet-like accumulations of non-banded collagen on the posterior surface of Descemet's membrane. The presence of focal thickenings of Descemet's membrane histologically named guttae. Cornea guttata can be easily diagnosed in vivo and ex vivo by means of specular microscopy as it gives dark areas where no endothelial cells are visible.,Corneal guttata are often observed in elderly people and are known to be associated with Fuchs corneal endothelial dystrophy, and also with trauma, congenital glaucoma, and macular dystrophy.
Wasting of the pectoral muscles, i.e., of the pectoralis major and pectoralis minor.
Reduced concentration of serine in the blood.
Wasting of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, the muscle in the anterior part of the neck that acts to flex and rotate the head.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of serine in the blood circulation.

Multiple, localized or widespread, asymptomatic or inflammatory dermal cysts involving the pilosebaceous units. Lesions can appear anywhere on the body, but steatocystoma multiplex is more commonly involved with those areas of the skin with a high density of developed pilosebaceous units (e.g., the axilla, groin, neck, and proximal extremities).,Steatocystoma multiplex can present with localized, generalized, facial, acral, or suppurative involvement.
An abnormally reduced concentration of glycine in the blood.
Malignant neoplasms which probably originate in primitive mesenchymal stem cell populations differentiating down a lipomatous pathway.

Inflammation of the flexor digitorum tendon, often associated with the Kanavel signs: (i) finger held in slight flexion, (ii) fusiform swelling, (iii) tenderness along the flexor tendon sheath, and (iv) pain with passive extension of the digit.,Tenosynovitis refers to inflammation of the protective sheath that surrounds a tendon. Stenosing tenosynovitis, or trigger finger, is diagnosed when a patient presents with a symptomatic locking or clicking of a finger or the thumb. It is caused by a mismatch between the volume of the flexor tendon sheath and its contents. As the flexor tendon attempts to glide through a relatively stenotic sheath, it catches, producing an inability to flex or extend the digit smoothly.
Presence of a lipoma in the region of the sacrum.

value_en: Autosomal dominant inheritance with maternal imprinting
description_en: A type of autosomal dominant inheritance involving a gene that is imprinted with maternal silencing.,Since the maternally inherited copy of such genes is silenced normally, only a paternally transmitted mutation leads to disease in this kind of inheritance.

value_en: Edema of the dorsum of feet
description_en: An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin on the back of the feet.

A congenital inclusion cysts that arises from the inclusion of ectodermally committed cells at the time of neural tube closure (3rd-5th week of embryogenesis). The capsule of dermoid cysts consists of simple epithelium supported by collagen. In thicker parts, the lining is supplemented with dermis containing hair follicles, sebaceous glands, and apocrine glands.,See Figure 9 in pmid:16714456. These cysts increase in size by means of glandular secretion and epithelial desquamation. Growth can lead to rupture of the cyst contents, causing a chemical meningitis that may lead to vasospasm, infarction, and even death.

A congenital inclusion cysts that arises from ectodermal cells that normally form skin cells being left behind in the nervous system during development.,See Figure 8 in pmid:16714456. Epidermoid cysts arise from ectodermal inclusion during neural tube closure in the 3rd-5th week of embryogenesis. The microscopic cyst lining consists of stratified squamous epithelium supported by an outer layer of collagenous connective tissue. Cystic contents usually include debris, keratin, water, and cholesterol laid down in a lamellar fashion. Epidermoid cysts do not contain dermal appendages.
Dislocation of many joints.
A deviation from the normal size of the pancreas.
A function abnormality of the endocrine pancreas.
A functional anomaly of the acinar gland portion of the pancreas that secretes digestive enzymes.
An anomaly of the function of the pancreas.
An abnormal catecholamine concentration in the blood.

description_code: Abnormally shaped pancreas,Abnormality of pancreas morphology

description_en: An anomaly in the surface contour of mitochondria.
An abnormal color of the urine, that is, the color of the urine appears different from the usual straw-yellow color.
description_code: Abnormal urinary colour,Abnormal urinary color,Abnormal urine color

description_en: Presence of an increased number of neutrophils in the urine.

value_en: Abnormality of skeletal muscle fiber size
description_en: Any abnormality of the size of the skeletal muscle cell.
Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates that show positive staining with antibodies against ubiquitin within cells of the brain.
Atrophy of the cerebellum affecting primarily the Purkinje cell layer.
An abnormally increased size of the cerebellum compared to other brain structures.
Atrophy of the cerebellum affecting primarily the granular cell layer.
Arterial inflammation.

A deviation from the normal odor of the urine.,Urine does not usually have a strong smell, but the odor may be altered by a number of factors including some diseases. Foul-smelling urine may be due to bacteria that have caused a urinary tract infection. Sweet-smelling urine may be a sign of uncontrolled diabetes or more rarely a disease of metabolism. Liver disease and certain metabolic disorders may cause musty-smelling urine.
description_code: Abnormal urinary odor,Abnormal urinary odour,Abnormal urine smell

description_en: A personality disorder characterized by impulsive behavior and unpredictable and capricious mood. Affected individuals show a liability to outbursts of emotion and an incapacity to control the behavioural explosions.

An abnormality of mental functioning affecting the personality and behavioural tendencies of an individual and characterized by a rigid and unhealthy pattern of thinking and behavior. The definition of a personal disorder implies that the abnormality is not the result of damage or insult to the brain or from another psychiatric disorder.,A Personality disorder is generally associated with significant problems and limitations in relationships, social encounters, work and school. It is usually manifest since childhood or adolescence and continues throughout adulthood.

An abnormality of the pupillary light reaction characterized by a marked slowing of the light reaction of usually just one pupil. The pupil tends to be relatively dilated, and there is reduced accommodation.

An abnormal distribution of N-acylglycines in the urine. There are numerous different N-acylglycines, and this term refers to pathological alterations in their level or distribution.,N-acylglycines result from glycine conjugation with exogenous compounds to enhance their excretion in urine. Glycine conjugation is also an effective detoxification system for preventing accumulation of acyl-CoA esters in several inherited metabolic disorders.
Excretion of urine with an acid pH.

Any deviation from the normal concentration in the blood circulation of acylcarnitine, which is produced by reversible esterification of the 3-hydroxyl group of carnitine.,Carnitine fundergoes reversible esterification of its 3-hydroxyl group producing acylcarnitine, which can enter the mitochondria with the assistance of specific translocases.
An increased concentration of chondroitin sulfate (CHEBI:37397) in the urine.,Chondroitin sulfate refers to a class of 10-60 kDa glycosaminoglycan sulfates, which are widely distributed in cartilage.

Any anomaly of the conduction of motor nerve impulses in the central nervous system.,Nerve conduction velocity in the central motor pathways of the brain and spinal cord can be studied by methods including transcutaneous electrical stimulation of the cortex, cervical cord, thoracic cord and conus medullaris and determination of motor latencies to various muscles. This measure is thought to represent conduction in large diameter fibres in the corticospinal tracts.
Blockade of impulses at a focal site along the course of a motor axon.

A personality disorder characterized by shallow and labile affectivity, self-dramatization, theatricality, exaggerated expression of emotions, suggestibility, egocentricity, self-indulgence, lack of consideration for others, easily hurt feelings, and continuous seeking for appreciation, excitement and attention.
A structural abnormality of a skeletal muscle.
description_code: Issue with muscle structure,Abnormally shaped muscle,Abnormality of muscle morphology

description_en: A functional abnormality of a skeletal muscle.
description_code: Issue with muscle function,Abnormality of muscle physiology

description_en: Visually assessable vertical indentation, cleft, or depression of the nasal bridge, ridge and tip.,This is a bundled term, but as it is useful in practice it is kept here. If it is only an indentation or cleft of the nasal tip, this should be coded as Bifid nasal tip.
description_code: Bifid nasal bridge,Indentation or clefting of the nose,Cleft nose,Cleft nasal bridge,Indented bridge of nose

description_en: A benign (noncancerous) tumorlike malformation made up of an abnormal mixture of cells and tissues that originates in the tongue.
Increased size of the parotid gland.
description_code: Increased size of parotid gland,Hyperplasia of parotid gland,Hypertrophy of parotid gland

description_en: Posterior positions and/or vertical shortening of the infraorbital and perialar regions, or increased concavity of the face and/or reduced nasolabial angle.
description_code: Small midface,Midface deficiency,Underdevelopment of midface,Midface hypoplasia,Midface retrusion,Flat midface,Midface, flat,Retrusive midface,Hypoplasia of midface,Decreased size of midface,Decreased projection of midface,Hypotrophic midface

description_en: A type of myotonia that worsens with repeated muscle contractions.,In classic myotonia the myotonia improves as muscles warm up, whereas in paradoxical myotonia (paramyotonia) it worsens with repeated muscle contractions.
Decreased intensity of the patellar reflex (also known as the knee jerk reflex).
description_code: Decreased patellar reflexes,Decreased knee jerk reflex

description_en: Atrophy (wasting) affecting primary type 1 muscle fibers. This feature in general can only be observed on muscle biopsy.
Any structural anomaly of the adrenal glands.
Replacement of bone marrow by fibrous tissue.
An abnormality of the concentration of cortisol in the blood.
Repeated episodes of sudden-onset and transient lethargy.

An abnormality of cortical sensation. Assuming the primary sensory modalities are intact and the patient is alert and cooperative, the presence of an abnormality of sensory function usually indicates a lesion of a parietal cortex or of the thalamocortical projections to the parietal cortex.
Abnormally low glucose concentration in the cerebrospinal fluid.
description_code: Low glucose levels in cerebral spinal fluid,Increased CSF glucose,Decreased CSF glucose

description_en: An exaggerated whealing tendency when the skin is stroked, that is, formation of red, itchy bumps and lines on the skin as a result of pressure on the skin (for instance, stroking the skin with a pen or tongue depressor).

Amyloid deposition in the walls of leptomeningeal and cortical arteries, arterioles, and less often capillaries and veins of the central nervous system.,Vascular beta-amyloid deposition in the walls of small to medium-sized, blood vessels (mostly arterial) of the central nervous system. Cerebral amyloid angiopathy mostly occurs in the sporadic form in the elderly, while rare familial forms occur in younger patients and are generally lead to more severe clinical manifestations. Extracellular deposition of the amyloid protein in the brain is associated with neurologic and physiological disease progression.
An abnormality in the range and ease of motion of joints across their normal range.
Clonus at the elbow joint, i.e., an exaggerated phasic stretch reflex characterized by repetitive, rhythmic contractions at the elbow, generated by rapid passive stretch at the elbow joint.

Weakness of the peroneal muscles.,THe peroneal muscles (also known as fibularis muscles) originate from the fibula. The peroneal longus and brevis muscles are located on the lateral side of the leg, while peroneal tertius is on the anterior side.
An elevated concentration of luteinizing hormone in the blood.
description_code: Increased circulating luteinizing hormone level,Elevated LH level,Elevated luteinizing hormone

description_en: Systemic desaturation of a liveborn baby resulting from persistent pulmonary hypertension with a patent ductus arteriosus and patent foramen ovale, such that the circulation in postnatal life follows the fetal course.
Impaired ability to eat related to problems gathering food and getting ready to suck, chew, or swallow it.
A reduced concentration of copper in the blood.
Uhl anomaly of the right ventricle refers to the almost complete absence of right ventricular myocardium, normal tricuspid valve, and preserved septal and left ventricular myocardium.
An increased concentration of citrulline in the blood.

value_en: Congenital malformation of the right heart
description_en: Defect or defects of the morphogenesis of the right heart identifiable at birth.
Any deviation from the normal concentration of citrulline in the blood circulation.,Citrulline is an alpha-amino acid that is a key intermediate in the urea cycle.

value_en: Mixed total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
description_en: Type 4 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
description_code: Total anomalous pulmonary venous connection, mixed,Type 4 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection

description_en: History of repeated intermittent involuntary muscle contractions that were painful.

value_en: Infracardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
description_en: Type 3 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
description_code: Type 3 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection

description_en: Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen, due to a hypothalamic or pituitary abnormality diagnosed with hypo-gonadotropic-hypogonadism. The diagnosis is made on the basis of low LH and FSH levels and low or normal testosterone levels.

value_en: Cardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
description_en: Type 2 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
description_code: Type 2 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection,Total anomalous pulmonary venous connection, intracardiac

description_en: Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen, resulting from post-testicular obstruction or retrograde ejaculation. Can be differentiated from obstructive azoospermia on the basis of testicular biopsy.

Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen, resulting from a defect in the production of spermatozoa in the testes. Can be differentiated from obstructive azoospermia on the basis of testicular biopsy.
Focal proliferation of glial cells in the substantia nigra.
An abnormality of the pulmonary veins.,The right superior, right inferior, left superior, and left inferior pulmonary veins carry oxygenated blood to the left atrium.

Accessory pathway-related atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) involves an abnormal electrical conduction of the accessory pathway. The accessory pathway connecting impulses between the atrium and the ventricle can be seen at any site in the AV groove.

value_en: Unilateral hypoplasia of pectoralis major muscle
description_en: Hypoplasia (underdevelopment) of the pectoralis minor on only one side of the chest.
description_code: Small pec muscle on one side,Underdeveloped pec muscle on one side

description_en: Junctional ectopic tachycardia (JET) is a unique type of supraventricular arrhythmia defined by narrow QRS complex and atrioventricular (AV) dissociation or retrograde atrial conduction in a 1:1 pattern.

A small hole through the whole thickness of the retina.,Retinal perforations can be cause by inflammation, trauma, degeneration, or other factors, and comprise retinal breaks, tears, dialyses, and holes.
Abnormal conduction in all three divisions of the intraventricular conducting tissue.

An abnormality of the pectoral muscle, comprising the pectoralis major, a thick, fan-shaped muscle of the anterior chest and the pectoralis minor, a thin, triangular muscle situated underneath the pectoralis major.

Libman-Sacks valvular lesions are sterile fibrofibrinous vegetations that favor the left-sided heart valves and usually form on the ventricular surface of the mitral valve.,Libman-Sacks lesions are y typical manifestation of systemic lupus erythematosus.
A conduction block of the left branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a generalized disturbance of QRS morphology on EKG.

The presence of multiple granulomas in the liver as based on pathological examination. Granulomas are small 0.5 to 2 mm collections of modified macrophages called epithelioid cells usually surrounded by lymphocytes.

A conduction block of the right branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a prolongation of the QRS complex (greater than 0.12 s) with delayed activation of the right ventricle and terminal delay on the EKG.
Diffuse benign transformation of the hepatic parenchyma into small regenerative nodules with minimal or no fibrosis.
description_code: Nodular transformation of liver,Partial nodular transformation of liver,Noncirrhotic nodulation

description_en: Conduction block in the anterior division of the left bundle branch of the bundle of His.
Lung parenchymal involvement with lymphoma.

value_en: Supracardiac total anomalous pulmonary venous connection
description_en: Type 1 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection.
description_code: Total anomalous pulmonary venous connection, supracardiac,Type 1 total anomalous pulmonary venous connection

description_en: Block of conduction of electrical impulses along the Bundle of His or along one of its bundle branches.,The Bundle of His conducts the electrical impulse from the atrioventricular node into the ventricles. THe Bundle of His divides into right and left bundle branches. A universal feature of a bundle branch block is a prolongation of the time required for depolarization of a portion of the ventricles, reflected in an abnormality of the QRS complex.
An acute episode of pneumonia due to the aspiration (breathing in) of food, liquid, or gastric contents into the upper respiratory tract.
Pneumonia due to the aspiration (breathing in) of food, liquid, or gastric contents into the upper respiratory tract.
Inflammation of the bronchioles.

Progressive PR interval prolongation with the subsequent occurrence of a single nonconducted P wave that results in a pause. The pause that follows the nonconducted impulse is less than fully compensatory (less than the sum of two normal sinus intervals).,Mobitz I atrioventricular block is associated with a normal QRS duration.
Acute inflammation of the lung due to an infection.

An intermittent atrioventricular block with failure of some atrial impulses to conduct to the ventricles, i.e., some but not all atrial impulses are conducted through the atrioventricular node and trigger ventricular contraction.
A history of repeated acute infections of the upper or lower respiratory tract.

Delay of conduction through the atrioventricular node, which is manifested as prolongation of the PR interval in the electrocardiogram (EKG). All atrial impulses reach the ventricles.,The conduction of the cardiac impulse through the atrioventricular node is manifested in the EKG by the PR interval, which is normally less that 200 milliseconds in adults. Normal values are age-dependent in children, but normal values are less that 160 milliseconds in young children.
An infection of the upper or lower respiratory tract.

An abnormality involving the generation of the action potential by the sinus node and is characterized by an atrial rate inappropriate for physiological requirements. Manifestations include severe sinus bradycardia, sinus pauses or arrest, sinus node exit block, chronic atrial tachyarrhythmias, alternating periods of atrial bradyarrhythmias and tachyarrhythmias, and inappropriate responses of heart rate during exercise or stress.

Inflammation and fibrosis of the bronchioles leading to partial or complete obstruction of these airways.,Note that Bronchiolitis obliterans is not to be confused with the similarly named feature Bronchiolitis obliterans organizing pneumonia.
Heart rate of greater than 100 beats per minute.

Bronchiolitis obliterans organizing pneumonia (BOOP) is and interstitial lung abnormalitiy characterized histopathologically by plugs of granulation tissue lying within small airways, alveolar ducts, and alveoli and by chronic inflammatory cell infiltration in alveolar walls. Patients with BOOP generally present with subacute illness, including shortness of breath, fever, malaise, and weight loss.

value_en: Abnormal electrophysiology of sinoatrial node origin
description_en: An abnormality of the sinoatrial (SA) node in the right atrium. THe SA node acts as the pacemaker of the heart.
A type of vasculitis (inflammation of blood vessel walls) that affects blood vessels that are smaller than arteries, i.e., arterioles, venules, and capilllaries.
Multifocal atrial tachycardia is a rare supraventricular arrhythmia in neonates and young infants that is characterized by multiple P waves with varying P wave morphology and is usually asymptomatic.
Increased concentration of thiosulfate(2-) in the urine.
Chronic supraventricular tachycardia predominantly seen in childhood.
Increased concentration of SO3(2-), i.e., sulfite, in the urine.

Atrioventricular (AV) dissociation is present if the atria and the ventricles are under the control of two separate pacemakers. AV dissociation can occur in the absence of a primary AV conduction disturbance.,Atrioventricular dissociation can develop in response to severe sinus bradycardia with AV junctional rhythm or with an enhanced lower (junctional or ventricular) pacemaker that competes with the normal sinus rhythm and exceeds it.

A type of second degree atrioventricular (AV) block characterized by sudden failure to conduct an impulse through the AV node without a preceding change in the PR interval.,Mobitz I atrioventricular block is usually associated with a prolonged QRS duration.
An abnormality of the shape of the lumbar vertebra L2 such that it is wedge-shaped (narrow towards the front).
An abnormality of the shape of the thoracic vertebra T12 such that it is wedge-shaped (narrow towards the front).
description_code: Anterior wedging of the 12th thoracic vertebra,Wedge-shaped 12th thoracic vertebra

description_en: Underdeveloped nails of the fifth toes.
A decreased concentration of total carnitine in the blood.
Decreased concentration of urate in the urine.,Xanthine oxidase oxidizes oxypurines such as xanthine and hypoxanthine to uric acid. Uric acid is the final oxidation product of purine catabolism.
Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of the inferior mesenteric artery or superior mesenteric artery .,Aneurysm is considered a severe form of dilatation.
Increased length of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
description_code: Long cerebellar peduncle,Long cerebellar peduncles,Elongated superior cerebellar peduncles

value_en: Abnormality of the superior cerebellar peduncle
description_en: An anomaly of the superior cerebellar peduncle.

An anomaly of the cerebellar peduncles. The superior, middle, and inferior cerebellar peduncles emerge from the cerebellum. The superior cerebellar penduncles connect the cerebellum to the midbrain, the middle cerebellar peduncles connect the cerebellum to the pons, and the inferior cerebellar peduncle connects the medulla spinalis and medulla oblongata with the cerebellum.
A soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between fingers 3 and 4.
A type of chronic kidney disease with normal or increased glomerular filtration rate (GFR at least 90 mL/min/1.73 m2).,Proteinuria is commonly seen in stage 1 chronic kidney disease.
Functional anomaly of the kidney persisting for at least three months.
description_code: Chronic kidney disease,Progressive renal failure,Renal insufficiency, progressive,Renal failure, progressive,Loss of renal function,Progressive renal insufficiency

description_en: Developmental anomaly in which the vagina, bladder, and rectum fuse resulting in a common channel.
Enlargement of the thyroid gland related to a singular nodule in the thyroid gland.
A developmental anomaly associated with the failure of rectum, vagina, and bladder to separate.
A structural abnormality of the thyroid gland.
A type of hypoparathyroidism with circulating antiparathyroid or anti-calcium sensing receptor antibodies indicative of autoimmunity.
