A type of hyperparathyroidism that occurs following kidney transplantation, which is a treatment for secondary hyperparathyroidism. Although kidney transplantation leads to a normalization of serum calcium and parathyroid hormone in most patients. The state of persistent hypercalcemia and hyperparathyroidism is referred to as tertiary hyperparathyroidism.
Presence of a many diverticula (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urinary bladder.
A cyst located along the allantois canal.
Presence of erythrocyte casts (cylindrical structures produced by the kidney in certain disease states) in the urine.
An abnormal anatomical location of the parathyroid gland.
Presence of leukocyte casts (cylindrical structures produced by the kidney in certain disease states) in the urine.
Abnormal embryonic development of the parathyroid gland.

The presence of renal casts (cylindrical, cigar-shaped structures produced by the kidney in certain disease states) in the urine.,Urinary casts are formed in the distal convoluted tubule or the collecting duct by solidification of protein in the lumen of the kidney tubules. The casts are suibsequently eliminated via the urine and may be seen by microscopy of the urine sediment. A large number of casts can indicate kidney disease. Urinary casts are composed of Tamm-Horsfall protein, which is a mucoprotein that is secreted by the distal loop of Henle.
A functional abnormality of the parathyroid gland.
An anomalous finding in the examination of the urine for cells.
A structural abnormality of the parathyroid gland.
Elevated concentration of SO4(2-), i.e., sulfate, in the urine.
Abnormal concentration of sulfate in the urine.

A spindled-to-epithelioid, oncocytic, nonendocrine neoplasm of the anterior hypophysis that manifests in adults and follows a benign clinical course. Pituitary spindle cell oncocytomas are firm, fibrous, and adherent to surrounding structures and are highly vascular.
Elevated concentration of urate in the urine.,Xanthine oxidase oxidizes oxypurines such as xanthine and hypoxanthine to uric acid. Uric acid is the final oxidation product of purine catabolism.

A pituitary tumor with subarachnoid, brain, or systemic metastasis. The diagnosis of a pituitary carcinoma requires evidence of metastatic disease, either outside the central nervous system (CNS) or as separate noncontiguous foci within the CNS.

value_en: Abnormality of urinary uric acid concentration
description_en: Abnormal concentration of urate in the urine.,Xanthine oxidase oxidizes oxypurines such as xanthine and hypoxanthine to uric acid. Uric acid is the final oxidation product of purine catabolism.
A type of pituitary adenoma that produces thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH).
A type of pituitary adenoma that is of unknown cellular origin and that lacks immunocytochemical or fine structural markers. Null cell adenomas are not associated with hormone excess.
description_code: Non-functional pituitary adenoma,Silent pituitary adenoma,Clinically silent pituitary adenoma,Hormonally silent pituitary adenoma

description_en: A type of pituitary adenoma that produces growth hormone.
An decreased concentration of magnesium the urine.
description_code: Decreased urine magnesium,Low urine magnesium levels

description_en: An increased concentration of magnesium the urine.
An abnormal concentration of magnesium the urine.
A type of pituitary adenoma that produces gonadotropins.
An abnormally increased sodium concentration in the urine in the presence of hyponatremia.
description_code: Kidney sodium wasting,Renal Na wasting,Renal Na+ wasting

description_en: An increased concentration of sodium(1+) in the urine.
Underdevelopment of the neurohypophysis.
A persecutory delusion of supposed hostility of others.
An abnormally decreased sodium concentration in the urine.
Absence of the neurohypophysis owing to a developmental defect.
An increased concentration of glucose in the blood following a meal.
An abnormal concentration of sodium in the urine.
description_code: Abnormal urine Na+ levels,Abnormal urine Na concentration

description_en: An abnormal anatomical location of the posterior lobe of the hypophysis, also known as the neurohypophysis. The posterior pituitary is normally present in the dorsal portion of the sella turcica, but when ectopic is usually near the median eminence. This defect is likely to be due to abnormal migration during embryogenesis.
Abnormally increased level of blood lactate following a meal.
High urine chloride in the presence of hypochloridemia.
description_code: Renal Cl wasting,Kidney chloride wasting,Renal Cl- wasting

description_en: A solid, low grade, spindle cell, glial neoplasm of adults that originates in the neurohypophysis or infundibulum. Clinical signs and symptoms include visual disturbance, headache and features of hypopituitarism. Pituicytomas are well-circumscribed, solid masses that can measure up to several centimeters. Histologically, they show a compact architecture consisting of elongate, bipolar spindle cells arranged in interlacing fascicles or assuming a storiform pattern.

Increased activity of coagulation factor V, Factor V, which is activated to factor Va by means of minute amounts of thrombin (and inactivated by larger amounts of thrombin). Activated factor V (fVa) is a cofactor in the formation of the prothrombinase complex.
description_code: Elevated factor V activity,Plasma factor V elevated

description_en: An decreased concentration of chloride in the urine.
description_code: Low urine chloride levels,Decreased urinary chloride

description_en: Abnormal development of the neurohypophysis during embryonic growth and development.

A bulging of the interatrial septum towards one side. In adults, atrial septal aneurysm can be defined as a protrusion of the aneurysm of >10 mm beyond the plane of the atrial septum as measured by transesophageal echocardiography.,Atrial septal aneurysm formation may be secondary to raised interatrial pressure gradients, producing a bulging septal shift toward the low-pressure side. However, it has been also found in patients with normal atrial pressures, suggesting a primary (congenital) malformation.
An abnormal concentration of chloride in the urine.
description_code: Abnormal urine Cl- concentration,Abnormal urine Cl concentration

description_en: The presence of a neoplasm (tumour) in the neurohypophysis, which is also known as the posterior lobe of the hypophysis.
An abnormality of the interatrial septum.
description_code: Abnormal interatrial septum morphology,Abnormality of the atrial septum

description_en: An abnormality of the neurohypophysis, which is also known as the posterior lobe of the hypophysis.
A reduction in the ability of neutrophils to kill bacteria.
A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the adenohypophysis, which is also known as the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland.
description_code: Neoplasm of the pars anterior,Neoplasm of the adenohypophysis

description_en: An abnormal form or size of neutrophils.
A deviation from the normal range of neutrophil cell counts in the circulation.
A functional abnormality of neutrophils.

Overproduction of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), which generally leads secondarily to overproduction of cortisol by the adrenal cortex.,This term refers to increased production of ACTH. If additionally hypercorticolism is present, this should be coded separated with HP:0011744.
A reduced ability to secrete adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), a hormone that stimulates the adrenal cortex to secrete of glucocorticoids such as cortisol.
An abnormality of the adenohypophysis, which is also known as the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland.
Formation of abnormal bony tissue within ligament tissue.
An hormonally active adrenocortical adenoma, that is, an adenoma that secretes excessive amounts of adrenal hormones.
Formation of abnormal bony tissue within tendon tissue.
An hormonally inactive adrenocortical adenoma, that is, an adenoma that does not secrete excessive amounts of adrenal hormones.
Formation of abnormal bony tissue within muscle tissue.
Hypercortisolemia associated with a overproduction of ACTH (often from a tumor), leading secondarily to overproduction of cortisol.
Formation of abnormal, extraskeletal bony tissue, i.e., the presence of bone in soft tissue where bone normally does not exist.
Absent development of the adrenal gland.
Clay colored stools lacking bile pigment.
Abnormal anatomical location of the adrenal gland.
Failure of formation of the lumen of the gallbladder, often associated with gallbladder hypoplasia.
A form of hyperaldosteronism caused by abnormally increased renin levels.
A type of pigment gallstone that is brown, containing calcium fatty acids. These stones are softer than black pigment gallstones.
A form of primary hyperaldosteronism in which the overproduction of aldosterone cannot be suppressed by the administration of dexamethasone or similar glucocorticoids.
A type of pigment gallstone that is hard and black, containing calcium carbonate and calcium phosphates.
Gallstones composed primarily of bilirubin and calcium salts (calcium bilirubinate) with a low cholesterol concentration.
Gallstones composed primarily of cholesterol, usually about 2-3 cm in length with an oval form and a yellow or green/brown color.
A form of primary hyperaldosteronism in which the overproduction of aldosterone can be suppressed by the administration of dexamethasone.
description_code: Familial primary hyperaldosteronism type 1,Glucocorticoid-remediable familial primary aldosteronism

description_en: Adrenal insufficiency secondary to a defect in the corticotropin-releasing hormone receptor.
Adrenal insufficiency secondary to a defect in corticotropin-releasing hormone production.
description_code: Tertiary adrenal insufficiency,CRH deficient adrenal insufficiency

description_en: An increased concentration of dopamine in the urine.
A form of hyperaldosteronism caused by a defect within the adrenal gland.
An increased concentration of vanillylmandelic acid in the urine.
Adrenal insufficiency secondary to a defect in ACTH production.
An increased concentration of homovanillic acid in the urine.
A form of adrenal insufficiency related to a lack of ACTH, which leads to a decrease in the production of cortisol by the adrenal glands. Aldosterone production is not usually affected.
An increased concentration of catecholamine in the urine.
A functional abnormality of the adrenal glands.

Partial or complete loss of hearing following ingestion of aminoglycoside antibiotics.,The ototoxicity of aminoglycoside antibiotics is related to the destruction of sensory hair cells in the cochlea and vestibular labyrinth.

An ulcer of the colon due to pressure and irritation from retained fecal masses.,Stercoral ulceration is the loss of bowel integrity from the pressure effects of inspissated feces. The lesion usually occurs in constipated, bedridden patients and presents as an isolated lesion in the rectosigmoid area.

value_en: Regional left ventricular wall motion abnormality
description_en: An abnormal motion of a segment of the left ventricle during the cardiac cycle.,This feature can be appreciated using color kinesis, which tracks the motion of the endocardium in real time throughout systole and results in color-encoded images reflecting the magnitude and timing of endocardial motion.

An inflammation of the choroid and retina.,Chorioretinitis is a form of posterior uveitis. Note that the term Chorioretinitis suggests that the origin of the process is predominantly in the choroid while Retinitis suggests that the process is mainly in the retina.

A large reduction in the fraction of blood pumped from the left ventricle with each cardiac cycle. The normal range in adults is at over 50 percent, and a severe reduction is defined as less than 30 percent.
The inability of the colon to modify stool to an acceptable consistency and move the stool from the cecum to the rectosigmoid area at least once every three days.

A medium reduction in the fraction of blood pumped from the left ventricle with each cardiac cycle.,The normal range in adults is over 50 percent, and a moderate reduction can be defined as 30-39 percent.

Overgrowth of the choroid plexus.,The most common location for overgrowth is the lateral ventricles. The choroid plexus folds into many villi around capillaries, creating frond-like processes that project into the ventricles. The terms choroid plexus hypertrophy or choroid plexus hyperplasia are used interchangeably to refer to an increase in size of these structures. Diffuse villous hyperplasia of choroid plexus (DVHCP) is a rare condition which is characterized by the presence of diffuse enlargement of the entire choroid plexus throughout the length of the choroidal fissure and overproduction of CSF.
description_code: Choroid plexus hypertrophy,Diffuse villous hypertrophy of choroid plexus

description_en: A diminution of the volumetric fraction of blood pumped out of the ventricle with each cardiac cycle.,The normal range is at least 55 percent.

Congenital lack of the skin of prepuce of penis, that is, of the double-layered fold of skin and mucous membrane that covers the glans penis.,Absence of the foreskin can be accompanied by Cryptorchidism and Hypospadias, which should be coded separately.
A small reduction in the fraction of blood pumped from the left ventricle with each cardiac cycle. The normal range in adults is at least 50 percent, and a mild reduction is defined as 40-49 percent.

Amniotic fluid containing the earliest stools of a mammalian infant.,Meconium may be expelled into the amniotic fluid before birth in response to fetal distress. If meconium is aspirated by the fetus, it may lead to meconium aspiration syndrome.
description_code: Meconium-stained amniotic fluid,Meconium staining of amniotic fluid

description_en: Reduced uptake of [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) in the parietal cortex as measured by positron emission tomography (PET) brain scan.,Glucose uptake measured with FDG-PET is a marker of neuronal metabolic activity, thus this sign indicates reduced metabolic activity in the parietal cortex.

Reduced uptake of [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) in the hypothalamus as measured by positron emission tomography (PET) brain scan.,Glucose uptake measured with FDG-PET is a marker of neuronal metabolic activity, thus this sign indicates reduced metabolic activity in the hypothalamus.

Reduced uptake of [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) in the thalamus as measured by positron emission tomography (PET) brain scan.,Glucose uptake measured with FDG-PET is a marker of neuronal metabolic activity, thus this sign indicates reduced metabolic activity in the thalamus.

An abnormally high level of blood oxygen.,Note that hyperoxemia is defined as a condition where arterial oxygen tension is above normal (80-100mmHg). Hyperoxia is defined as increased oxygen tension at the tissue level. Hyperoxia is not measured directly by a standard laboratory value.

An abnormally low level of blood oxygen.,Note that hypoxemia is defined as a condition where arterial oxygen tension is below normal (80-100mmHg). Hypoxia is defined as the failure of oxygenation at the tissue level. Hypoxia is not measured directly by a standard laboratory value.
Abnormally reduced blood carbon dioxide (CO2) level.
description_code: Reduced carbon dioxide in the blood,Hypocarbia

description_en: Reduced uptake of [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) in the prefrontal cortex as measured by positron emission tomography (PET) brain scan.,Glucose uptake measured with FDG-PET is a marker of neuronal metabolic activity, thus this sign indicates reduced metabolic activity in the prefrontal cortex.
Abnormally elevated blood carbon dioxide (CO2) level.

value_en: Abnormal brain FDG positron emission tomography
description_en: An anomaly detectable in [18F]-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) positron emission tomography (PET) brain scans. Glucose uptake measured with FDG-PET is a marker of neuronal metabolic activity.
An abnormality of the partial pressure of oxygen or carbon dioxide in the arterial blood.

A functional brain anomaly detectable by positron emission tomography (PET). PET scanning is a method for functional brain imaging, and its measurements reflect the amount of brain activity in the various regions of the brain.,Note that while structural brain anomalies can cause abnormal brain PET scan results, structural abnormalities are detectable by multiple neuroimaging modalities and should be coded using terms from the hierarchy under 'Abnormality of nervous system morphology' (HP:0012639).
Wasting or decrease in size of all or part of the duodenum.
Decreased concentration of dopamine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
The presence of a V-shaped indentation (notch) in the primary central incisor.
description_code: Notched front primary tooth,Notched front deciduous tooth,Notched front baby tooth,Syphilitic primary incisor,Hutchinson-boeck teeth,Hutchinson's teeth,Hutchinson's sign,Hutchinson's incisor

description_en: Increased concentration of dopamine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

Onset of adrenarche at an earlier age than usual.,Adrenarche is an early sexual maturation stage that typically occurs at around 6 to 8 years of age, during which the adrenal cortex begins to secrete increased levels of androgens resulting from the development of the zona reticularis in the adrenal cortex. Note that pubarche refers to the development of pubic hair, axillary hair, and adult sweat gland (apocrine) odor. The physical features associated with pubarche reflect the onset of adrenarche, which refers to the pubertal maturation of the adrenal and is associated with increased secretion of an adrenal hormone called dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEAS).
Abnormal concentration of dopamine in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
The onset of growth of pubic hair at an earlier age than normal.
Severe asthma unresponsive to repeated courses of beta-agonist therapy such as inhaled albuterol, levalbuterol, or subcutaneous epinephrine.
Asthma attacks following exercise.
A severe form of gait ataxia such that an affected person cannot walk at all.

Polymicrogyria (an excessive number of small gyri or convolutions) that is maximal in perisylvian regions (the regions that surround the Sylvian fissures), which may be symmetric or asymmetric and may extend beyond perisylvian regions. The Sylvian fissures often extend posteriorly and superiorly.,The Sylvian fissure (also known as the lateral sulcus) separates the frontal and parietal lobes superiorly from the temporal lobe inferiorly.
The deposition of calcium salts in the parenchyma of the renal cortex (the outer portion of the kidney between the renal capsule and the renal medulla).
The deposition of calcium salts in the parenchyma of the renal medulla (innermost part of the kidney).

A type of spastic paraparetic gait in which the muscle tone in the adductors is marked. It is characterized by hypertonia and flexion in the legs, hips and pelvis accompanied by extreme adduction leading to the knees and thighs hitting, or sometimes even crossing, in a scissors-like movement. The opposing muscles (abductors) become comparatively weak from lack of use.,Scissor gait is a form of gait abnormality primarily associated with spastic cerebral palsy.
A abnormal increase in the inflammatory response to injury or infection.
A greater than normal concentration of citrate(3-) in the urine.
An abnormal reduction in the inflammatory response to injury or infection.
A lower than normal concentration of citrate(3-) in the urine.

Any anomaly of the inflammatory response, a response to injury or infection characterized by local vasodilation, extravasation of plasma into intercellular spaces and accumulation of white blood cells and macrophages.

description_code: Anomaly of facial soft tissue,Abnormality of facial soft tissue,Malformation of facial soft tissue,Deformity of facial soft tissue

description_en: A deviation from normal of the concentration of citrate(3-) in the urine.
description_code: Abnormal urine citrate concentration,Abnormal urine citric acid concentration

description_en: A testis that is located at the upper scrotum or lower inguinal canal and that can be made to descend completely into the scrotum without resistance by manual reduction but returns to its original position by the cremasteric reflex.
Gain-of-function thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor (TSHR) defect.

A renal tumor originating from an oncocyte, which is an epithelial cell characterized by an excessive amount of mitochondria, resulting in an abundant acidophilic, granular cytoplasm.,Renal oncocytoma is seen in Birt-Hogg-Dube syndrome (OMIM 135150).

A lower than normal concentration of 2-oxoglutaric acid in the urine.,Note that alpha-ketoglutaric acid is also known as 2-ketoglutaric acid, alpha-ketoglutaric acid, 2-xxoglutaric acid, and oxoglutaric acid.

Increase in size of a peripheral nerve. This finding can be appreciated by palpation along the axis of the nerve.,This feature can be appreciated by imaging studies (magnetic resonancy tomography), by palpation along the axis of a nerve, and by biopsy, and may be caused by axonal swelling or by myelin thickening. The differential diagnosis of enlarged peripheral nerves includes leprosy, hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy type 1 (about 30% of patients), but not type 2 (the axonal form), some other polyneuropathies, neurofibromatosis, and nerve tumors. A good review is available in Practical Neurology, 2003,3:40-45 by Michael Donaghy (no pubmed id).
A type of papillary renal cell carcinoma that is characterized by small cuboidal cells covering thin papillae with a single line of uniform nuclei and small nucleoli.

A greater than normal concentration of 2-oxoglutaric acid in the urine.,Note that alpha-ketoglutaric acid is also known as 2-ketoglutaric acid, alpha-ketoglutaric acid, 2-xxoglutaric acid, and oxoglutaric acid.
An elevated concentration of lactate in the caudate nucleus. This finding can be elicited by magnetic resonance spectroscopy imaging.
Abnormally persistent foci of embryonal immature blastema located in the superficial cortical region (perilobar).

A deviation from normal of the concentration of 2-oxoglutaric acid in the urine.,Note that alpha-ketoglutaric acid is also known as 2-ketoglutaric acid, alpha-ketoglutaric acid, 2-xxoglutaric acid, and oxoglutaric acid.
description_code: Abnormal urinary 2-oxoglutarate level,Abnormality of urine alpha ketoglutarate concentration

description_en: Decreased amount of pigmentation in the fovea centralis.
Presence of persistent islands of renal blastema in the postnatal kidney, anywhere within a renal lobe (a portion of a kidney consisting of a renal pyramid and the renal cortex above it).

An abnormal concentration of aldolase in the serum. Aldolase is an enzyme responsible for converting fructose 1,6-bisphosphate into the triose phosphates dihydroxyacetone phosphate and glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.,The reaction catalyzed by aldolase is a component of the glycolysis pathway.
The presence of an embryonal neoplasm of the kidney that primarily affects children.
A reduction of the pressure inside the cranium (skull) and thereby in the brain tissue and cerebrospinal fluid.
Neoplasm categorized according to the anatomical site of origin of the neoplasm.

A deviation from the norm of the intracranial pressure.,Intracranial pressure (i.e., the pressure inside the skull) represents the pressue in the brain tissue and in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). Deviations from normal are generally identified by measuring the pressure of the CSF.
Neoplasm categorized according to type of histological abnormality.
Loss-of-function thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor (TSHR) defect.
A structural anomaly of the nervous system.
description_code: Abnormal nervous system morphology,Abnormal shape of nervous system

description_en: A functional anomaly of the nervous system.
High urine calcium in the presence of hypocalcemia.
description_code: Kidney Ca2+ wasting,Renal Ca wasting,Renal Ca2+ wasting,Kidney calcium wasting,Kidney Ca wasting

description_en: Blockage of the retinal vein.,Retinal vein occlusion can lead to edema and ischemia of the retina.
An elevated concentration of free 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine in the blood circulation.
description_code: Increased serum fT3,Increased serum free triiodothyronine,Increased serum free T3

description_en: Reduction in the amount of blood flow to the iris.,This feature can be diagnosed by iris angiography.

A type of hypothyroidism due to an insufficient stimulation of an otherwise normal thyroid gland. Central hypothyroidism is caused by either pituitary (secondary hypothyroidism) or hypothalamic (tertiary hypothyroidism) defects.

Shedding of the pigment granules that normally adhere to the back of the iris into the aqueous humor.,These pigment granules can accumulate in the trabucular meshwork and lead to increased intraocular pressure. That is coded separately as HP:001263.

value_en: Thyrotoxicosis with toxic single thyroid nodule

description_en: A difference in the amount of intraocular pressure in the right and left eye.
An anomaly in the amount of force per unit area exerted by the intraocular fluid within the eye.

value_en: Pigment deposition in the trabecular meshwork
description_en: Accumulation of abnormal amounts of pigment within the trabecular meshwork.,Gonioscopy can be used to reveal pigment deposition on the trabecular meshwork.

An anomaly of the trabecular meshwork, which is the porelike structure surrounding the entire circumference of the anterior chamber at the base of the cornea and near the ciliary body. The trabecular mesh work is responsible for draining the aqueous humor into the canal of Schlemm.

An abnormal growth of parafollicular (C-cells) cells.,Thyroid C cell hyperplasia usually occurs before the development of familial forms of medullary thyroid cancer and is considered a pre-cancerous condition.
Absence of a lobe of the thyroid gland related to a failure of its embryologic development.
Tremulousness (trembling) of the lens of the eye.,Phacodonesis results from lesions of some or most of the zonular fibres are broken.

value_en: Abnormal suspensory ligament of lens morphology
description_en: An anomaly of the suspensory ligament of lens, also known as the ciliary zonule. These ligaments represent a series of fibers connecting the ciliary body and lens of the eye, holding the lens in place.
description_code: Zonule of zinn abnormality,Ciliary zonule abnormality,Abnormality of the suspensory ligament of lens,Abnormality of zinn's membrane

description_en: Deposition of fibrillar material that can be found on all anterior segment structures bathed by aqueous humor.,In the eye, pseudoexfoliation syndrome is characterized by the deposition of fibrillar material that can be found on all anterior segment structures bathed by aqueous humor. PXM can be observed in vivo during slit lamp examination. It appears as 'dandruff-like' material in the anterior chamber or most characteristically on the anterior lens capsule deposited in a double concentric ring pattern. The rings are separated by a clear zone presumably created because of the movement of the iris on the anterior lens surface. The central ring is located at the area of the iris sphincter, while the peripheral ring is only visible after pupil dilation. PXM is also often observed by slit lamp examination at the pupillary margin, on the lens zonules and on the trabecular meshwork. The site of production of this material which is a complex of various glycoproteins is unclear, but PXM can potentially originate from the iris, lens epithelium, ciliary body, or the trabecular meshwork.
A type of chronic kidney disease with severely reduced glomerular filtration rate (GFR 15-29 mL/min/1.73 m2).
A type of chronic kidney disease with moderately reduced glomerular filtration rate (GFR 30-59 mL/min/1.73 m2).
A type of chronic kidney disease with mildly reduced glomerular filtration rate (GFR 60-89 mL/min/1.73 m2).

The presence of bacteria in the urine.,The urine is normally bacteria-free. The term refers to bacteria from the urinary tract and not to bacteria found in the urine because of contamination from the surrounding tissues. Significant bacteriuria is a sign of urinary tract infection.
A structural anomaly of the inferior portion of the vermis of cerebellum.

Narrowing of the urethra associated with inflammation or scar tissue.,A urethral stricture may result from surgery, disease, or injury. The term should not be used for a congenital narrowing of the urethra (Consider the term Urethral stenosis, HP:0008661).
Infantile spasms represent a subset of "epileptic spasms". Infantile Spasms are epileptic spasms starting in the first year of life (infancy).
The presence of a teratoma in the ovary.
Longstanding abnormal acid accumulation or depletion of base.
Reduced number of primary teeth.,Primary teeth are also called temporary teeth or deciduous teeth.
description_code: Failure of development of some deciduous teeth,Partial anodontia of deciduous teeth,Partial anodontia of primary teeth,Failure of development of some primary teeth,Missing some milk teeth,Missing some baby teeth,Decreased number of milk teeth,Fewer deciduous teeth than normal,Decreased number of primary teeth,Fewer primary teeth than normal,Decreased number of baby teeth,Missing some primary teeth,Decreased number of deciduous teeth,Fewer baby teeth than normal

description_en: Sudden onset of impairment in ventilation such that the removal of carbon dioxide by the respiratory system is less than the production of carbon dioxide in the tissues, leading to an elevation of the partial pressure of carbon dioxide (PaCO2) above the normal limits (more than 45 mm Hg) with an accompanying acidemia (pH less than 7.35).

Persistence of immune complexes in the blood circulation.,Immune complexes are formed of interlocking antigens and antibodies and are normally are rapidly removed from the bloodstream by macrophages in the spleen and Kupffer cells in the liver. If they persist abnormally in the circulation, they may become trapped in various tissues and induce inflammatory reactions.

Longstanding impairment in ventilation such that the partial pressure of carbon dioxide (PaCO2) is elevated above the upper limit of the reference range (more than 45 mm Hg), with a normal or near-normal pH secondary to renal compensation and an elevated serum bicarbonate levels (more than30 mEq/L).
A breach of the capsule of the spleen.
An increased level of iron in liver tissues.,This abnormality can be measured by liver biopsy or by hepatic magnetic resonance imaging.
description_code: Increased iron concentration in liver,Increased liver iron level

description_en: The presence of multiple hemangiomas in the arachnoid.

A below normal level of saturation of serum transferrin with iron.,Transferrins are iron-binding blood plasma glycoproteins that control the level of free iron in biological fluids. The transferrin saturation test (TSAT) refers to the ratio of serum iron to total iron-binding capacity, expressed as a percentage. Transferrin saturations of less than 20% indicate iron deficiency, while transferrin saturations of more than 50% suggest iron overload. Note that the results of the TSAT can be influenced by inflammation.
A type of blistering that affects the skin of the tibial region.

An above normal level of saturation of serum transferrin with iron.,Transferrins are iron-binding blood plasma glycoproteins that control the level of free iron in biological fluids. The transferrin saturation test (TSAT) refers to the ratio of serum iron to total iron-binding capacity, expressed as a percentage. Transferrin saturations of less than 20% indicate iron deficiency, while transferrin saturations of more than 50% suggest iron overload. Note that the results of the TSAT can be influenced by inflammation.

The presence of multiple epithelioid cell granulomas consist of highly differentiated mononuclear phagocytes (epithelioid cells and giant cells) and lymphocytes, not exhibiting caseation (a form of necrosis in which the tissue changes into a dry, amorphous mass said to resemble cheese).,This feature is a hallmark of sarcoidosis.
Involuntary and irregular twitches of the chin.

An erythematous eruption commonly associated with drug reactions or infection and characterized by inflammatory nodules that are usually tender, multiple, and bilateral.,The nodules of erythema nodosum are located predominantly on the shins with less common occurrence on the thighs and forearms. They undergo characteristic color changes ending in temporary bruise-like areas, and usually subside in 3-6 weeks without scarring or atrophy.

A type of soft tissue sarcoma with a histological appearance reminiscent of alveoli because of its reticulated fibrous stroma enclosing groups of sarcoma cells, which resemble epithelial cells and are enclosed in alveoli walled with connective tissue.

A headache disorder that occurs exclusively at night, waking the affected individual from sleep.,Hypnic headache can be unilateral or bilateral, and is often but not always described as throbbing. The pain begins abruptly and can last from 15 minutes to 6 hours, although typically it is about 30-60 minutes.
Constipation for longer than three months with fewer than 3 bowel movements per week, straining, lumpy or hard stools, and a sensation of anorectal obstruction or incomplete defecation.

An entrapment neuropathy of the suprascapular nerve, presenting with shoulder weakness confined to the supraspinatus muscle (this muscle initiates shoulder abduction) or to the infraspinatus (this muscle externally rotates the arm), as well as with pain in the posterior part of the shoulder and upper periscapular region.

Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts in the tunica media of small arteries.,The general construction of small arteries is very similar to that of muscular arteries. The media is still muscular and has up to 8-10 layers of smooth muscle cells.
The deposition of calcium phosphate microliths within the seminiferous tubules.
Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts in the tunica media of medium-sized (muscular or distributive) arteries.
An abnormal rise in the volume of water filtered out of plasma through glomerular capillary walls into Bowman's capsules per unit of time.
Calcification, that is, pathological deposition of calcium salts in the tunica media of arteries.,Medial arterial calcification causes stiffening and decreased compliance of the affected arteries.

An abnormal reduction in the volume of fluid filtered out of plasma through glomerular capillary walls into Bowman's capsules per unit of time.,Renal clearance is defined as the volume of plasma per minute needed to excrete the quantity of a solute appearing in the urine in a minute. Normal values for adults are 97 to 137 ml/min (male) and 88 to 128 ml/min (female). This term refers to a reduction below normal limits in the ability of the kidney to clear creatinine from the bloodstream.
description_code: Decreased GFR,Reduced creatinine clearance,Impaired renal creatinine clearance

description_en: A chronic loss of wrist joint motion on one side only.
An abnormal functionality of the kidney.
description_code: Renal functional abnormality,Abnormal renal function,Abnormality of renal physiology,Kidney function issue,Abnormal kidney function

description_en: A chronic loss of wrist joint motion on the right and left sides.
Any structural anomaly of the kidney.
description_code: Structural kidney abnormalities,Structural anomalies of the renal tract,Structural renal anomalies,Abnormal kidney morphology,Kidney structure issue,Renal malformation,Kidney malformation,Abnormally shaped kidney

description_en: A feeling of uneasiness and restlessness in the legs after going to bed (sometimes causing insomnia).,Restless legs syndrome is a disorder characterized by aching or burning sensations in the legs that occur prior to sleep or may awaken the affected persons. Complying with an irresistible urge to move the affected limbs brings temporary relief. Sleep may become disrupted, resulting in excessive daytime hypersomnolence.
Constipation of sudden onset and lasting for less than three months.

Juvenile myelomonocytic leukemia (JMML) is a lethal myeloproliferative disease of young childhood characterized clinically by overproduction of myelomonocytic cells and by the in vitro phenotype of hematopoietic progenitor hypersensitivity to granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor.
A lack of mobility of ejaculated sperm.
An abnormal reduction in the mobility of ejaculated sperm.
Inflammation of the synovial membrane of the sacroiliac joint.
An anomaly of the mobility of ejaculated sperm.
Delayed myelination.
A structural abnormality of the pineal gland.,The pineal gland typically measures 7 x 6 x 3mm in size and is located in a groove between the laterally placed thalamic bodies.
An anomaly of the pineal gland,a small endocrine gland in the brain that produces melatonin.
Any structural anomaly of the acrosome resulting in a round sperm head.
Any anomaly in the process by which myelin sheaths are formed and maintained around neurons.
Recurrent infection involving the vulva, vagina, and adjacent crural areas, whereby the causative agent belongs to the genus Candida.
A reduced concentration of 5-methyltetrahydrofolate(2-) in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). 5-methyltetrahydrofolate is the active folate metabolite.
A fungal infection of the toenails or fingernails that tends to cause the nails to thicken, discolor, disfigure, and split.
An increase in the concentration of bile acid in the blood.
Partial or complete wasting (loss) of brain tissue that was once present.
A structural abnormality of the brain, which has as its parts the forebrain, midbrain, and hindbrain.
description_code: Abnormality of the brain,Abnormal shape of brain

description_en: An anomaly of clotting factor II, which is known as prothrombin, a vitamin K-dependent proenzyme that functions in the blood coagulation cascade.

Reduced motility of the gallbladder with reduced emptying fraction.,Patients with this gallbladder dyskinesia present with biliary-type pain but no evidence of gallstones in the gallbladder. The diagnosis is made by performing a radionuclide investigation of the gallbladder ejection fraction. An abnormal gallbladder ejection fraction has a value less than 40 percent.

Reduced motility through the sphincter of Oddi, resulting in impedance of bile and pancreatic juice flow from the common bile duct into the duodenum.,The sphincter of Oddi (also known as sphincter of ampulla) is a muscular valve that controls the flow of bile and pancreatic juice through the ampulla of Vater into the second part of the duodenum. Increased tone of the sphincter or disturbance in the coordination of contraction of the biliary ducts prevents normal emptying of the biliary tree. This may result in biliary pain, common bile duct dilation and episodes of pancreatitis.

A glial uniloculated or multiloculated fluid-filled sac that either reside within or completely replace the pineal gland.,Pineal cysts are benign and often asymptomatic lesions. They are typically visualized by computed tomography or magnetic resonance imaging.
A structural abnormality of the biliary tree.
Accumulation of calcium salts in the pineal gland.,This feature can be appreciated on skull radiography.
A functional abnormality of the biliary tree.
A functional anomaly of the gallbladder.
A structural anomaly of the gallbladder.
description_code: Abnormal gallbladder morphology,Abnormal shape of gallbladder

description_en: An increase in the distance between vertebral pedicles, which are the two short, thick processes, which project backward, one on either side, from the upper part of the vertebral body, at the junction of its posterior and lateral surfaces.
Syncope following a quick change in position from lying down to standing.
Coronary disease that has not progressed to the point of causing significant occlusion (blockage) of the coronary arteries.
description_code: Non-occlusive coronary artery disease,Nonocclusive coronary artery disease,Non-occlusive coronary artery stenosis,Nonocclusive coronary artery stenosis

description_en: An anomalous build up of iron (Fe) in the substantia nigra.
Reduction in length of the ventral (lower) skin of prepuce of penis.
An abnormal build up of iron (Fe) in the globus pallidus.

A failure to meet one or more age-related milestones of social behavior.,This term should be applied to describe a child whose social development is delayed compared to age-related norms. For instance, at the age of 3 months, a child smiles in response to social interaction, at the age of 7 months, a child responds to the facial expressions of others, and at the age of 12 months a child is shy around strangers.
An anomalous build up of copper (Cu) in the brain.
description_code: Copper accumulation in brain,Brain copper accumulation

description_en: An abnormality of actions or reactions of a person taking place during interactions with others.
description_code: Abnormal social behaviour,Abnormal social behavior,Abnormal social interactions

description_en: An abnormal build up of iron (Fe) in brain tissue.
description_code: Brain iron deposition,Iron accumulation in brain

description_en: Subjective feeling of tiredness characterized by a lack of energy and motivation that persists for six months or longer.,Note that chronic fatigue can be a symptom of chronic fatigue syndrome (CFS), which is characterized by profound fatigue that is not improved by bed rest and that may be worsened by physical or mental activity. Symptoms of CFS may include weakness, muscle pain, impaired memory, impaired mental concentration, and insomnia, which can result in reduced participation in daily activities.
A failure to develop of the lower part of the vagina.
description_code: Agenesis of the lower vagina,Absent lower vagina

description_en: Intermittent and recurrent bouts of a subjective feeling of tiredness characterized by a lack of energy and motivation.

A failure to develop of the upper vagina.,The female reproductive tract primarily develops from the Mullerian ducts (MD), which form as an invagination of the coelomic epithelium and further develop into the upper two-thirds of the vagina, the uterus and the Fallopian tubes. Complete aplasia of the uterus, cervix, and upper vagina is termed Mullerian aplasia. This term refers to the aplasia of the upper roughly two thirds of the vagina that is characteristic of Mullerian aplasia.
Underdevelopment of the cerebral white matter.
Akinetic mutism is essentially characterized by a total absence of spontaneous behavior and speech occurring in the presence of preserved visual tracking.

Poverty of behavior and speech output, lack of initiative, loss of emotional responses, psychomotor slowing, and prolonged speech latency.,Abulia is less severe thana kinetic mutism, and more so than apathy.

value_en: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the cerebral white matter
description_en: Absence or underdevelopment of the cerebral white matter.
description_code: Absent/small cerebral white matter,Absent/underdeveloped cerebral white matter

description_en: Protruding heel bone, or calcaneus.

An increased degree of femoral version, which is defined as the angular difference between axis of femoral neck and transcondylar axis of the knee. Thus, femoral anteversion is an inward twisting of the femur that causes the knees and feet to turn inward.,Excessive femoral anteversion is a common cause of in-toeing that first presents in early childhood.

An exaggerated response to carotid sinus baroreceptor stimulation resulting in syncope from transient diminished cerebral perfusion.,Carotid sinus syncope cam be elicited mechanical manipulation of the carotid sinuses (eg, taking pulses in the neck, shaving).

Optic disc drusen are acellular, calcified deposits within the optic nerve head. Optic disc drusen are congenital and developmental anomalies of the optic nerve head, representing hyaline-containing bodies that, over time, appear as elevated, lumpy irregularities on the anterior portion of the optic nerve.,Optic disc drusen can lead to an elevated disc and thus mimic disc swelling (pseudopapilledema).
A subtype of ductal pancreatic carcinoma that is thought to originate from squamous metaplasia of pancreatic ductal epithelium.
description_code: Squamous cell carcinoma of the pancreas

description_en: Inflammation of the nasal mucosa with nasal congestion.
Pattern of blood flow in the heart that deviates from the normal circuit of the circulatory system from both right side of the heart to the left and vice versa.
Pattern of blood flow in the heart that deviates from the normal circuit of the circulatory system from the left side of the heart to the right.
A delay in the development of skills required to feed oneself in the toddler period (between one and three years of age).
Reduced carnitine O-palmitoyltransferase activity, i.e., reduced activity of the reaction: palmitoyl-CoA + L-carnitine = CoA + L-palmitoylcarnitine.
Myelodysplasia with dysplastic changes in two of the myeloid lineages: erythroid, granulocytic, megakaryocytic.
Myelodysplasia with dysplastic changes in two or more of the myeloid lineages: erythroid, granulocytic, megakaryocytic.

value_en: Reduced quantity of Von Willebrand factor
description_en: Decreased quantity of von Willebrand factor.
Muscular hypotonia of one or more limbs.
Decreased quantity or activity of von Willebrand factor. Von Willebrand factor mediates the adhesion of platelets to the collagen exposed on endothelial cell surfaces.
Inflammation of the large airways of the lung with rapid onset and short course usually associated with cough, mucus production, shortness of breath, wheezing, and chest tightness.

value_en: Abnormality of multiple cell lineages in the bone marrow

description_en: Inflammation of the large airways in the lung including any part of the bronchi from the primary bronchi to the tertiary bronchi.
Any structural anomaly of a myeloid mononuclear recirculating leukocyte that can act as a precursor of tissue macrophages, osteoclasts and some populations of tissue dendritic cells.
Aplasia of the hallux, that is, a development defect such that the big toe does not develop.
description_code: Missing big toe,Agenesis of the halluces,Absent big toe,Aplasia of the hallux

description_en: Any structural anomaly of megakaryocytes. Mature blood platelets are released from the cytoplasm of megakaryocytes, which are bone-marrow resident cells.
description_code: Abnormality of cells of the megakaryocyte lineage

description_en: The distal interphalangeal joint and/or the proximal interphalangeal joint of the fingers or toes cannot be extended to 180 degrees by either active or passive extension.
description_code: Permanent flexion of the finger or toe

description_en: A deviation from the normal count of erythroid precursor cells, that is, erythroid lineage cells in the bone marrow.
A functional anomaly of the eye.
An anomaly of erythroid lineage cells, that is, of the erythropoietic cells in the lineage leading to and including erythrocytes.
description_code: Abnormality of cells of the erythroid lineage

description_en: A structural anomaly of the globe of the eye, or bulbus oculi.
description_code: Abnormally shaped eye,Abnormal eye morphology,Abnormality of the globe

description_en: Abnormally anterior positioning of the infraorbital and perialar regions, or increased convexity of the face, or increased nasolabial angle. The midface includes the maxilla, the cheeks, the zygomas, and the infraorbital and perialar regions of the face,This term represents increased size of the maxilla (upper jaw) in length (increased midface height) or anterior-posterior projection (midface prominence). In the presence of normal mandible size, maxillary prominence may give the appearance of retrognathia.
description_code: Large midface,Big midface,Midface hyperplasia,Midfacial prominence,Midfacial excess,Hypertrophy of midface,Overgrowth of the midface

description_en: Large or prominent malar surface of the zygomatic bone of the skull, which is convex and forms the prominence of the 'cheek bones'.
description_code: Zygomatic bone excess,Cheekbone excess,Pronounced cheekbone,Malar hypertrophy,Prominence of cheekbone,Hyperplasia of zygomatic bone,Hyperplasia of cheekbone,Zygomatic hypertrophy

description_en: Decreased number of granulocyte precursors in the bone marrow.
An altered ability of any enzyme or their cofactors to act as catalysts. This term includes changes due to altered levels of an enzyme.
A subjective feeling of tiredness characterized by a lack of energy and motivation.,Fatigue is distinct from muscle weakness.
An anomaly of cells involved in the formation of a granulocytes, that is, of the granulocytopoietic cell.
description_code: Abnormality of cells of the granulocytic lineage

description_en: Partial or complete loss of vision in one half of the visual field of one or both eyes.
Abnormal smallness of the lens.
Decreased count of erythroid precursor cells, that is, erythroid lineage cells in the bone marrow.
description_code: Erythroblastopenia,Erythroid hypoplasia in the bone marrow

description_en: Edema (swelling) of the bulbar conjunctiva.
Increased count of erythroid precursor cells, that is, erythroid lineage cells in the bone marrow.
description_code: Bone marrow smear shows erythroid hyperplasia,Bone marrow biopsy shows erythroid hyperplasia

value_en: Abnormality of bone marrow stromal cells
Abnormal sialylation of O-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: An anomaly of the addition of sialic acids to O-linked glycans.

value_en: Increased fucosylation of O-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: Increased addition of fucose sugar units to O-linked glycans.

value_en: Decreased fucosylation of O-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: A reduction of the addition of fucose sugar units to O-linked glycans.
Death of cells in the basal ganglia.
Increased concentration of uracil in the urine.

An abnormality of the malar surface of the zygomatic bone and including the frontal process of maxilla.,The malar bones are a confluence of the convex prominence of the zygomatic bone known as the malar surface, along with the malar process (most medial and superior part) of the maxilla. It forms the medial border of the inferior bony orbit, and is contiguous with the lateral boundary of the nasal bridge.
description_code: Malar anomaly,Deformity of the malar bones,Malformation of the malar bones,Anomaly of the malar bones

description_en: A cancer arising in any part of the stomach.

Absence of concavity or convexity of the face when viewed in profile.,A useful guide is to imagine that a line connecting the glabella to the anterior most part of the mandible touches the top of the philtrum where it meets the base of the columella. The glabella is the most prominent point on the frontal bone above the root of the nose. If the superior philtrum is anterior to this line the face is convex, if the superior philtrum is posterior to this line the face is concave.
description_code: Flat facial shape,Flat facies,Flat facial profile,Flat face

description_en: A cancer of the prostate.
Bony defects situated along the cranial suture lines or at the junction of the bone plates of the skull.,Extra fontanelles include glabellar, metopic, sagittal (parietal) and cerebellar fontanelles.
Inflammation of the uveal tract in which the primary site of inflammation is the vitreous.

Projection of the tip of the dens more than 5 mm above a line joining the hard palate to the posterior lip of the foramen magnum (Chamberlain's line) or the tip of the dens is greater than 7 mm above McGregor's line (the back of the hard palate to the lowest point of the occipital squama).
Inflammation of the uveal tract in which the primary site of inflammation is the retina or choroid.
An abnormally decreased phosphate concentration in the urine.
Inflammation of the uveal tract in which the primary site of inflammation is the anterior chamber.
A decreased concentration of potassium(1+) in the urine.
description_code: Hypokaluria,Decreased urinary K,Low urine potassium levels

description_en: Inflammation of the uveal tract in which inflammation affects the anterior chamber, vitreous, retina or choroid.

value_en: Decreased sialylation of O-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: An reduced addition of sialic acids to O-linked glycans.

Abnormally increased levels of methemoglobin in the blood. In this form of hemoglobin, there is an oxidized ferric iron (Fe +3) rather than the reduced ferrous form (Fe 2+) that is normally found in hemoglobin. Methemoglobin has a reduced affinity for oxygen, resulting in a reduced ability to release oxygen to tissues.
A carcinoma of the larynx.,Laryngeal carcinoma often is related to a history of smoking and may manifest by hoarseness, a lump in the neck, persistent cough, stridor and other symptoms.

value_en: Increased sialylation of N-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: Increased addition of sialic acids to N-linked glycans.
Severely increased amount of excretion of protein in the urine, defined as 3.5 grams per day or more in adults and 40 mg per meter-squared body surface area per hour in children.

value_en: Decreased sialylation of N-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: Decreased addition of sialic acids to N-linked glycans.
Increased concentration of albumin in the urine.
An abnormal amount of urine production.
Elevation in the concentration of albumin in the blood.

value_en: Abnormal fucosylation of O-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: An anomaly of the addition of fucose sugar units to O-linked glycans.
Deviation from normal concentration of albumin in the blood.

An anomaly of protein O-linked glycosylation, i.e., of the process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via the hydroxyl group of a serine or threonine residue.
Inflammation of the liver.

value_en: Increased mannosylation of N-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: Increased addition of mannose to N-linked glycans.
An abnormal phosphate concentration in the urine.
A carcinoma of the endometrium, the mucous lining of the uterus.

value_en: Decreased mannosylation of N-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: Reduced addition of mannose to N-linked glycans.
An abnormal concentration of potassium(1+) in the urine.

A deviation from the normal concentration of creatine in the blood circulation. Creatine is a derivative of glycine having methyl and amidino groups attached to the nitrogen. Creatine is naturally produced from amino acids, primarily in liver and kidney, and acts as an energy source for cells, primarly for muscle cells.
description_code: Abnormality of creatine metabolism,Creatine metabolism abnormal

value_en: Abnormal mannosylation of N-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: An anomaly of the addition of mannose to N-linked glycans.
Severely increased levels of protein in the urine (1000-3000 mg per day in adults).
An abnormality of the concentration of corticosterone in the blood.

value_en: Increased fucosylation of N-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: Increased addition of fucose sugar units to N-linked glycans.
Moderately increased levels of protein in the urine (500-1000 mg per day in adults).
An abnormality of the concentration of a glucocorticoid in the blood.

value_en: Decreased fucosylation of N-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: Decreased addition of fucose sugar units to N-linked glycans.
Mildly increased levels of protein in the urine (150-500 mg per day in adults).
Underdevelopment of the pons.

value_en: Abnormal fucosylation of protein N-linked glycosylation
description_en: An anomaly of the addition of fucose sugar units to N-linked glycans.
The presence of mildly increased concentrations of albumin in the urine (in adults, 30-150 mg per day).

A type of glaucomatous optic neuropathy in an eye that has evidence of angle closure (i.e. significant iridotrabecular contact).,Evidence of optic nerve damage can include s optic disc abnormalities (Vertical cup:disc ratio over the 97. 5th percentile in the normal population), visual field defects. The role of increased intraocular pressure (IOP) in glaucoma is debated, but an IOP exceeding the 99. 5th percentile of the normal population may be considered to support the diagnosis.

A type of glaucoma defined by an open, normal appearing anterior chamber angle and raised intraocular pressure,,Evidence of optic nerve damage can include s optic disc abnormalities (Vertical cup:disc ratio over the 97. 5th percentile in the normal population), visual field defects. The role of increased intraocular pressure (IOP) in glaucoma is debated, but an IOP exceeding the 99. 5th percentile of the normal population may be considered to support the diagnosis.
Increased width of the cross sectional diameter of the fibula.
description_code: Wide calf bone,Thick fibulae,Wide fibula,Thick fibula

value_en: Abnormal sialylation of N-linked protein glycosylation
description_en: An anomaly of the addition of sialic acids to N-linked glycans.,The most common sialic acids is N-acetylneuraminic acid (Neu5Ac).

value_en: Entrapment neuropathy of the ulnar nerve at elbow
description_en: An entrapment neuropathy of the ulnar nerve in the cubital tunnel (in the elbow) characterized by numbness in the ring and little fingers and weakness of the intrinsic muscles in the hand.

Injury to the median nerve caused by its entrapment at the wrist as it traverses through the carpal tunnel. Clinically, constrictive median neuropathy is characterized by pain, paresthesia, and weakness in the median nerve distribution of the hand.,Constrictive median neuropathy is the major clinical feature of carpal tunnel syndrome.

An elevated concentration of high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL) in the blood.,The major apolipoproteins of HDL are apolipoprotein (apo) A-I and apo A-II, also known as the alpha lipoproteins. Thus, hyperalphalipoproteinemia refers to an elevated concentration of apo A-I and apo A-II.
description_code: Increased circulating high-density lipoprotein levels,High blood HDL level,Hyperalphalipoproteinemia

description_en: Presence of multiple hyperplastic polyps in the colon. Hyperplastic polyps are generally about 5 mm in size and show hyperplastic mucosal proliferation.
A squamous cell carcinoma that originates in the oropharnyx.

Malfunction of a peripheral nerve resulting from mechanical compression of the nerve roots from internal or external causes and leading to a conduction block or axonal loss.,An entrapment neuropathy is an isolated peripheral nerve injury due to mechanical contriction in a fibrous or fibro-osseous tunnel or to deformation of the nerve by a fibrous band.

A disorder of large arteries, in particular the aorta, characterized by an accumulation of basophilic ground substance in the media with cyst-like lesions associated with degenerative changes of collagen, elastin and the vascular smooth muscle cells.,The lesions of cystic medial necrosis are not true cysts.
A type of lymphoma characterized microscopically by multinucleated Reed-Sternberg cells.
Excessive vomiting in early pregnancy, leading to the loss of 5% or more of body weight.
An increased concentration of protoporphyrins in erythrocytes.

Poor anticoagulant response to activated protein C. A plasma is termed 'APC resistant' when the addition of exogenous APC fails to prolong its clotting time in an activated partial thromboplastin time assay.,The protein C pathway is a major anticoagulant mechanism that down-regulates the prothrombin- and intrinsic factor X (FX)-activating complexes via inactivation of their respective cofactors, activated factors V (FVa) and VIII (FVIIIa). Cofactor inactivation occurs by limited proteolysis at certain amino acid positions in FVa and in FVIIIa. These reactions are catalyzed by the serine protease activated protein C (APC) and stimulated by the APC cofactor protein S. Functional defects of the protein C pathway determine a plasma phenotype known as APC resistance, which is a prevalent and important risk factor for venous thrombosis. A plasma is termed 'APC resistant' when the addition of exogenous APC fails to prolong its clotting time in an activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT) assay.

A tumor arising from glia in the central nervous system with macroscopic regions of necrosis and hemorrhage. Microscopically, glioblastoma multiforme is characterized by regions of pseudopalisading necrosis, pleomorphic nuclei and cells, and microvascular proliferation.
An increase in heart rate with standing of 30 beats per minute or more.
Habitual repetitive movement of the body.
Habitual clasping and squeezing of the hands.
Habitual biting of one's own fingernails.

A form of focal dystonia affecting the face and especially the jaw that is induced by the act of speaking. It is an involuntary contraction of the masticatory muscles, resulting in dysarthria or dysphagia.
description_code: Distorted craniofacial posture,Abnormal craniofacial posture,Abnormal craniofacial muscle tone,Abnormal facial muscle tone,Facial Dystonia

description_en: Reduced ability of the natural killer cell to function in the adaptive immune response.
A functional anomaly of the natural killer cell.

An anomaly of the natural killer cell, which is a lymphocyte that can spontaneously kill a variety of target cells without prior antigenic activation via germline encoded activation receptors. It also regulates immune responses via cytokine release and direct contact with other cells.
description_code: Abnormality of natural killer cells,Abnormal NK cells

description_en: A clinical sign indicating a lapse of posture and is usually manifest by a bilateral flapping tremor at the wrist, metacarpophalangeal, and hip joints.,The examiner can test for asterixis by asking the patient to extend the arms, spread the fingers, dorsiflex the wrist and observe for the abnormal "flapping" tremor at the wrist. Asterixis represents the failure to actively maintain a position and is caused by the abnormal function of diencephalic motor centers that regulate the tone of the agonist and antagonist muscles involved in maintaining posture.
A dilatation (balooning or bulging out of the vessel wall) of a carotid artery.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of the common carotid artery wall.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of the external carotid artery wall.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of the intracranial portion of the internal carotid artery wall.
Habitual biting of one's own body.,Biting of one's own arms, lip, check, finger etc.
Habitual striking of one's own head against a surface such as a mattress or wall of a crib.
A phenomenon in which persons repetitively pull out their own hair, resulting in noticeable hair loss.
Repetitive and compulsive picking of skin which results in tissue damage.
A developmental defect resulting in the presence of fewer than the normal number of digits.
An decrease in the level of triglycerides in the blood.
description_code: Decreased plasma Tg levels,Low blood triglyceride levels,Decreased circulating Tg levels

description_en: An allergy experienced at a particular time of year when trees or grasses pollinate and elicit an allergic reaction.
Splitting of the retinal layers in the macula.
Allergy to iodine contrast media used in radiological studies.
The presence of blood in the pleural space.,Hemothorax may result from hemorrhage in the chest wall, lung parenchyma, heart, or great vessels.
An allergy is an immune response or reaction to substances that are usually not harmful.
Abnormality/dysplasia of a single myeloid cell (erythroid, granulocytic, or megakaryocytic).

Reduced intensity of muscle tendon reflexes in jaw.,The jaw jerk is elicited by the examiner placing the tip of the index finger on a relaxed jaw, one that is about one-third open. One then taps briskly on the index finger with the other hand and notes the speed as the mandible is flexed.
Reduced intensity of muscle tendon reflexes in the upper limbs. Reflexes are elicited by stretching the tendon of a muscle, e.g., by tapping.
A small tear in the thin, moist tissue (mucosa) that lines the anus. It appears as a crack or slit in the mucous membrane of the anus.

A separation (dissection) of the layers of the internal carotid artery wall.,The internal carotid begins at the bifurcation of the common carotid, opposite the upper border of the thyroid cartilage, and runs perpendicularly upward. It supplies the anterior part of the brain, the eye and its appendages, and sends branches to the forehead and nose. Interstitial hemorrhage into the media of the vessel wall can lead to occlusion of the internal carotid artery and aneurysm formation.
A separation (dissection) of the layers of the carotid artery wall.
Atrophy of the cerebral subcortical white and gray matter, termed subcortical atrophy, reflects loss of nerve cells in the basal ganglia or fibers in the deep white matter.

A type of ulcer that is caused when an area of skin is subject to pressure over a prolonged period of time, ranging in range in severity from patches of discolored skin to open wounds that expose the underlying bone or muscle. The most common sites are the sacrum, coccyx, heels and the hips.,Pressure ulcers tend to affect persons with reduced mobility who are bedridden or wheelchair-bound.

Phagocytosis by macrophages of erythrocytes, leukocytes, platelets, and their precursors in bone marrow and other tissues.,Hemophagocytosis is a nonspecific phenotypic feature observed in several conditions including hemolytic anemia, malignant disease, infections, and hemophagocytic syndrome (also known as hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis, a rare hyperinflammatory syndrome caused by severe hypercytokinemia due to a highly stimulated but ineffective immune process).
An abnormal accumulation of interstitial fluid in the soft tissues of the limbs.
The presence of atheromas or atherosclerotic plaques in the aorta.
description_code: Aortic atherosclerosis,Plaque build-up in aorta artery,Atherosclerosis of the aorta,Atherosclerotic changes of aorta

description_en: Inability to experience pleasure activities usually found enjoyable.
A motility disorder characterized by biliary colic in the absence of gallstones with a reduced gallbladder ejection fraction.
A type of tumor of the pancreatic beta cells that secretes excess insulin and can result in hypoglycemia.

An abnormal pattern of respiration characterized by cycles of respiration that are increasingly deeper then shallower with possible periods of apnea. Affected patients may display a 10 to 20 second episode of hypoventilation or apnea, followed by respiration of increased depth and frequency over the course of about one minute. The cycle repeats every 45 seconds to 3 minutes.
Uneven rhythm of breathing.
Transient episodes of weakness of the arm, leg, and in some cases the face on one side of the body.
A type of T-cell lymphoma that is characterized by so-called hallmark cells with a pleomorphic appearance that express the CD30 antigen, are lobulated, and have indented nuclei.
A type of T-cell lymphoma that exhibits malignant infiltration of the skin.
A type of lymphoma that originates in B-cells.
A type of lymphoma that originates in T-cells.

The presence of more than 5 juvenile polyps of the colon. The term juvenile polyps refer to a special histopathology and not the age of onset as the polyp might be diagnosed at all ages. The juvenile polyp has a spherical appearance and is microscopically characterized by overgrowth of an oedematous lamina propria with inflammatory cells and cystic glands.,A juvenile polyp is a hamartomatous growth that projects from the lining of the intestine. It does not arise from the colonocytes themselves but from the tissues underneath the lining cells.

One or more digit that appears disproportionately short compared to the hand/foot, whereby either the entire digit or a specific phalanx is shortened.,Note that the term brachydactyly is reserved for specific patterns of short digits, see HP:0001156.

value_en: Decreased activity of mitochondrial ATP synthase complex
description_en: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial proton-transporting ATP synthase complex, which makes ATP via oxidative phosphorylation, and is sometimes described as Complex V of the electron transport chain.

value_en: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex III
description_en: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex III, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

value_en: Decreased activity of mitochondrial complex I
description_en: A reduction in the activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain complex I, which is part of the electron transport chain in mitochondria.

value_en: Abnormal activity of mitochondrial respiratory chain
description_en: An increased or decreased activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain.

A type of pleural effusion with a exudate (extravascular fluid that has exuded out of a tissue or its capillaries due to injury or inflammation). Pleural effusions can be classified as transudates or exudates based on Light's criteria, which classify an effusion as exudate if one or more of the following are present: (1) the ratio of pleural fluid protein to serum protein is greater than 0.5, (2) the ratio of pleural fluid lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) to serum LDH is greater than 0.6, or (3) the pleural fluid LDH level is greater than two thirds of the upper limit of normal for serum LDH.,Transudates result from pneumonia, malignancy, thromboembolism, and other causes.

A type of pleural effusion with a transudate (extravascular fluid with low protein content and a low specific gravity). Pleural effusions can be classified as transudates or exudates based on Light's criteria, which classify an effusion as exudate if one or more of the following are present: (1) the ratio of pleural fluid protein to serum protein is greater than 0.5, (2) the ratio of pleural fluid lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) to serum LDH is greater than 0.6, or (3) the pleural fluid LDH level is greater than two thirds of the upper limit of normal for serum LDH.,Transudates result from imbalances in hydrostatic and oncotic forces and are caused by a limited number of recognized clinical conditions such as heart failure and cirrhosis. Less common causes include nephrotic syndrome, atelectasis, peritoneal dialysis, constrictive pericarditis, superior vena caval obstruction, and urinothorax.

value_en: Hypersegmentation of proximal phalanx of third finger
description_en: Presence of an additional phalanx-like bone, producing an extra, wedge-shaped bone at the base of the proximal phalanx of the third finger.,This anomaly is characteristic for brachydactyly type C.
Developmental hypoplasia (shortening) of proximal phalanx of toe.
Atrophy of the extensor digitorum longus muscles, which mediate extension of the toes.
Abnormal calcification in the cardiovascular system.
Excessive, increased hair growth located in the thoracic region.
Excessive, increased hair growth located in the lumbar region.
An anomaly of the glenoid fossa, also known as the glenoid cavity, which is the articular surface of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus.
An anomaly of a metacarpophalangeal joint.

value_en: Shortening of all phalanges of fingers
description_en: Abnormal reduction in length affecting all phalanges.
Accumulation of pus in the pleural cavity.
Bending or curvature of a fourth toe in the tibial direction (i.e., towards the big toe).
Underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the fifth toe.
description_code: Short pinkie toe,Short pinky toe,Short little toe,Short fifth toe

description_en: Hemoglobin A (HbA) contains two globin alpha chains and two globin beta chains. HbA is normally the main adult hemoglobin, representing about 96-98 percent of all hemoglobin. This term represents a decreased in the proportion of HbA below this limit, and can be seen in various forms of thalassemia.

Hemoglobin F (HbF) contains two globin alpha chains and two globin gamma chains. It is the main form of hemoglobin in the fetus during the last seven months of intrauterine development and in the half year of postnatal life. In adults it normally makes up less than one percent of all hemoglobiin. This term refers to an increase in HbF above this limit. In beta thalassemia major, it may represent over 90 percent of all hemoglobin, and in beta thalassemia minor it may make up between 0.5 to 4 percent.
Hemoglobin H (HbH) contains four beta-globin chains. It is normally not present at all in blood, but may make up about 1-40 percent of all hemoglobin in HbH disease, a subform of alpha thalassemia.
Anomaly in the level or the function of hemoglobin, the oxygen-carrying protein of erythrocytes.
Qualitatively abnormal fibrinogen.
Decreased concentration of fibrinogen in the blood.
Abnormally flat shape of the heads of the metacarpal bones.,The metacarpal heads articulate with the proximal phalanges of the fingers.
description_code: Flattened head of long bone of hand

description_en: Missing radius bone on one side only associated with congenital failure of development.
A reduction in the ratio of production of alpha globin to that of beta globin. This is the major abnormality in the various forms of alpha thalassemia.
A reduction in the ratio of production of beta globin to that of alpha globin. This is the major abnormality in the various forms of beta thalassemia.
Accumulation of serous fluid (pale yellow and transparent fluid) in the pericardial sac.

Accumulation of chyle (the whitish fluid taken up by the lacteals in the intestine, consisting of an emulsion of lymph and triglyceride fat thatpasses into the veins by the thoracic duct) in the pericardium. Chylopericardium is generally caused by obstruction of or trauma to the thoracic duct.
Accumulation of blood within the pericardial sac.
Inflammation of the parotid gland.

Any anomaly in the formation of bone or of a bony substance, or the conversion of fibrous tissue or of cartilage into bone or a bony substance.,All bones are formed by the replacement by osteocytes of mesenchyme-derived connective tissue. Intramembranous ossification refers to the direct replacement of primitive mesenchyme with bone, and is responsible for bones such as the calvarium (e.g., frontals, parietals, interparietal) and the clavicula. In endochondral ossification, the mesenchyme differentiates into a cartilaginous intermediate, which serves as a template (anlange) that is subsequently removed and replaced by bone. Most bones are formed via endochondral ossification, including those at the base of the skull, the vertebral column, pectoral and pelvic regions and long bones of the extremities. A reduction in the amount of mineralized bone compared with that expected for a given developmental age. In clinicakl parlance, reduced ossification and delayed ossification are often used synonymously, but in principle a bone delayed ossification in a child can display normal ossification at a later developmental stage. The HPO will therefore treat poor, reduced, and decreased officiation as synonymous, and delayed ossification as a specific kind of reduced ossification.

A type of abdominal pain that comes and goes in waves, most often starting and ending suddenly and being of severe intensity.,Colicky abdominal pain can be caused by kidney stones and gallstones, among other etiologies. This type of pain is thought to be caused by spasm, obstruction, or distension of any of the hollow viscera of the gastrointestinal system.
A bone tumor composed of cellular spindle-cell stroma containing scattered multinucleated giant cells resembling osteoclasts.
A benign, painful, tumor of bone characterized by the formation of osteoid tissue, primitive bone and calcified tissue.
Short (hypoplastic) second metatarsal bone.
An abnormality of the appendicular skeletal system, consisting of the of the limbs, shoulder and pelvic girdles.
An abnormality of the function of the skeletal system.
An abnormality of the form, structure, or size of the skeletal system.

A potentially lethal cardiac arrhythmia characterized by an extremely rapid, hemodynamically unstable ventricular tachycardia (150-300 beats/min) with a large oscillating sine-wave appearance.,If untreated, ventricular flutter typically progresses to ventricular fibrillation.
A functional anomaly of T cells.
A deviation from the normal count of T cells.
description_code: Abnormal number of T cells,Abnormality of T cell number

description_en: Localized thickening and tightness of the skin of the fingers or toes.
Detectable but decreased IgA levels that are more than 2 standard deviations below normal age-adjusted means.
Delayed maturation and calcification of the talus.
Congenital absence of the scaphoid..

A noninflammatory, progressive occlusion of the intracranial carotid arteries owing to the formation of netlike collateral arteries arising from the circle of Willis.,Cerebral angiography shows puff-of-smoke (moyamoya) collaterals at the base of the brain.

Positioning of the nasal tip inferior to the nasal base.,This finding is often associated with a long nasal ridge. It is best appreciated in profile. This may also coexist with a Depressed nasal tip and Low insertion of the columella and should be coded separately.
description_code: Low hanging nasal tip,Hooked tip of nose,Overhanging nasal tip,Nasal tip, overhanging,Drooping nasal tip

description_en: Decrease in width of the nasal tip.,Nasal tip width is assessed at the anterior junction of the alae and the tip. This is easier in persons with a somewhat squared shape of the nasal tip. This may be best viewed from the inferior aspect of the nose. No objective measures are available.
description_code: Pinched tip of nose,Thin nasal tip,Thin tip of nose,Pinched nasal tip,Narrow tip of nose,Narrow nasal tip,Nasal tip, narrow,Nasal tip, pinched

description_en: Nasal tip positioned to one side of the midline.,There is no specific minimal angle before the tip can be determined to be deviated. The assessment of a mild degree of deviation is highly dependant on the experience of the observer. A deviated nasal septum can accompany a deviated nasal tip.
description_code: Asymmetry of tip of nose,Crooked tip of nose,Deviated nasal tip,Nasal tip, deviated,Deviated tip of nose,Crooked nasal tip,Asymmetry of nasal tip,Distortion of the nasal tip

description_en: Abnormality of the oral mucosa.
description_code: Abnormality of oral mucosa,Abnormality of mucosa of mouth,Abnormality of lining of mouth,Abnormality of oral mucous membrane

description_en: Pit in the midline of the philtral groove.,Although congenital sinuses of the lips generally occur in the lower lip, in rare instances they may appear in the philtrum of the upper lip, commonly close to the insertion of the columella.
description_code: Philtrum, Midline Sinus,Central sinus of philtrum
